<DOCNO>GH950703-000003</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000003</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#7665 for rep with woolly sales area</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584180</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WOOL and clothing salesman -- whose area was the whole of Scotland
apart from a vague area 30 to 40 miles around Glasgow -- has won his
claim for unfair dismissal
For a ''heartless'' English company sacked him because the costs of
employing him outweighed his sales.
But an Industrial Tribunal said the arrangement excluded John
Marshall, of Knights Way, Stoneywood, Denny, Stirlingshire, from the
most densely populated part of the country.
And it found he was unfairly sacked by Roland Burgess Ltd., of
Newcastle, as their Scottish sales rep for hand-knitting wools and
ladies and kids clothing.
He was given notice and redundancy pay on January 3, 1995, but
complained to the Tribunal that there was no redundancy situation as TWO
new sales staff were employed to cover the area.
Mr Marshall also argued his selection for redundancy was unfair, there
was no intimation his job was in jeopardy, he had no consultation, and
wasn't offered one of the new posts.
The tribunal ruled: ''The manner of his dismissal, by a letter sent to
him by post, was heartless and fell far short of what would be expected
from a reasonable employer.''
Mr Marshall was awarded #7665.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000004</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000004</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fine for drugged joyride woman</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584181</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A JOYRIDER -- aged 27 -- took a spin in her own father's car while
under the influence of drugs.
And Lesley Gilligan failed to stop after being involved in a crash.
But Glasgow District Court heard that Gilligan was recognised by the
other driver.
Her father told police she had taken the car without permission and
was not insured.
Gilligan, now living in London, admitted taking the car without
permission from Glenhead Street, Possilpark, driving without insurance
and failing to stop after an accident on December 17 last year.
An agent said that Gilligan had taken temazapam and had simply
panicked after the accident. She was now drug free.
Gilligan was fined #400 and banned from driving for one year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000005</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000005</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BEST TIME TO BE A BABY</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>AGNES STEVENSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584182</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MUMS may find it tough juggling home, family and career. But as far as
creature comforts go, there has never been a better time to be a baby.
While working mothers are short of time, their earning power means
that most babies want for nothing.
As a result, babies are having more money spent on them than ever
before.
According to the latest survey from Heinz, the average baby works its
way through 6000 nappies, worth a grand total of #1000, before it is
potty trained. And despite the fact that the birth rate is falling,
sales of both disposable nappies are actually continuing to grow.
Also gaining in popularity are disposable trainer pants. And there has
been an explosion in the sales of baby wipes with new, more expensive
cloth wipes, making a big impact.
But according to Claire Lyons from Bishopbriggs, many of the products
on the market are nice to have but not actually necessary for bringing
up baby.
Claire who has two boys, Paul (4) and Mark (1[1/2]), says that when
she had her first baby she bought every baby product on the market.
''With your first baby you do it by the book and I still meet mums in
the changing rooms who have bought the lot.''
But by the time her second baby came along she realised that, apart
from the basics, most of the stuff clogging up the medicine cupboard and
bathroom shelves was not vital.
Claire said: ''I really feel that the manufacturers who come up with
new products are praying on the guilt of busy mums.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
