<DOCNO>GH950703-000009</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000009</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Union report pushes for low pay pledge</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT TAIT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584186</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTS trade unionists today fired a warning shot at Labour leader Tony
Blair over low pay.
They demanded Labour meets its pledge to bring in a national minimum
wage if it wins the next General Election.
The plea came at the launch of a new report on low pay from the STUC
and the Scottish Low Pay Unit.
The report - Minimum Wages: Dispelling the Myths - calls for a low
wage floor to be set at half the average male earning before eventually
rising to two-thirds.
At current prices, that means the new minimum wage will be set at
#4.15 an hour.
Trade unionists confirmed the report is aimed at pressurising Labour
bosses not to backslide on their commitment.
Mr Blair has repeatedly refused to commit himself to a set rate or
formula.
Today STUC assistant general secretary Bill Speirs said: ''We are very
anxious to put the strongest possible case to Labour that it should
stand by its existing policy of introducing a minimum wage formula.''
A spokeswoman in Mr Blair's office said: ''It's a matter of addressing
the problem of low pay but making sure it doesn't have an adverse affect
on jobs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
