<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000015</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000015</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Political Godfathers demand their cut</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584192</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONLY the Tories could find a way to make crime pay.
Their latest plan is to charge jobhunters a fiver a time for their
criminal records.
EVEN IF THEY HAVEN'T GOT ONE.
Under a White Paper to be revealed in the autumn, more employers will
be allowed access to criminal records.
Employers denied direct access would be entitled to insist applicants
provide a 'criminal conviction certificate'.
One argument is that it will protect children, yet most childcare
employers already have access.
So why push ahead with such a daft and dangerous scheme?
TO LET THE TORIES PRIVATISE CRIMINAL RECORDS AND HAND THEIR CITY PALS
A PROFIT.
Minor offences long buried in the past will be dredged up.
More serious ones will be flung in the faces of people who have paid
their dues.
If this crazy plan goes ahead, no offender can ever be rehabilitated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>DOCTOR LONG'S MONDAY SURGERY</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DR KATHLEEN LONG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584193</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT looks as if the sun was the only thing that had its hat on
recently.
Adults and children were seen looking like boiled lobsters in just
about every surgery and casualty up and down the country.
Is it lack of information that makes people rush out and sunbathe for
hours on end with a splash of sun cream on behind each ear?
I don't think so somehow. It's either some sort of masochism or summer
madness that does it, but it has crossed my mind that people don't buy
decent sun cream because it's expensive.
Certainly some can set you back six or seven quid. However I can
honestly say that after shopping around I have always managed to get it
much cheaper than that.
Now I figure if adults want to fry, they can accept the consequences
of pain, swelling and the increased risk of skin cancer.
But children don't deserve to suffer the pain and blistering from
overexposure to the sun whether it is Scottish or Mediterranean. Sun
burn in childhood has been shown to increase the risk of skin cancer.
And you don't need to mortgage the house to protect them either. A
floppy hat, a baggy T-shirt to cover shoulders and tops of legs and some
sun block should do the trick.
If you're off on holiday then it's also useful to take some antiseptic
cream for cuts, some paracetamol in case they get a high temperature,
some lacto-calamine which won't make them look like the pink panther and
will soothe any stings or, god forbid, sun burn that they get.
The usual household plasters should also be taken and some fluid
replacement sachets which are handy if they get diarrhoea.
And when you get to your resort whether it's Spain or Saltcoats, find
out where the nearest doctor is and get the telephone number.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The French connection</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GERALDINE ABRAHAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>JOB SEARCH</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584194</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is nothing new in Scottish further education colleges accessing
European Social/Regional Development Funds.
But the Glasgow College of Nautical Studies may be unique in that the
person they have employed to co-ordinate this effort is a European
herself.
Anne Robin Doherty arrived in Scotland from her native France in 1985
as an exchange teacher and then returned to Glasgow in 1988 to marry.
Until recently she has worked with Paisley &amp; Renfrewshire Trust and
has been now been employed specifically by the College of Nautical
Studies to access European funding.
She will work with Fiona Cherry, who is head of Cross College Services
and in charge of the whole European dimension.
''We felt the need to bring it all together because it was less
efficient before with me doing the job with one hand while running my
department with the other,'' Anne said.
''So one person was appointed to take it forward as a sole task.''
This move to build relationships and form partnerships with member
states is likely to result in increased job opportunities for students
at the college, and potential markets are being investigated.
Two weeks ago, the college played host to a delegation from Kotka
Polytechnic in Finland, which has its own Maritime Department and is
interested in fostering links with other European bodies that run
courses in Maritime Studies.
Glasgow College of Nautical Studies had already recognised this niche
marketplace and is keen to promote its courses in Europe.
It is one of the only places in the UK to run a Masters Certificate,
and was of interest to the Finnish visitors.
''The Finnish students are expected to come on the Masters course and
there will be further dialogue about our students utilising their
training ship,'' said Anne.
''There is also an idea of incorporating marketing in our courses, and
they have an HND in Marketing which, like most of their courses, is run
in English.''
And as Fiona explained: ''While Maritime Studies is our niche market,
it is not the only market.
''We have the School of Sport and Leisure, for example, and have led
the field in our HND in Sports Coaching development.''
Anne and Fiona are hoping that this first, exploratory visit by the
Finns will be reciprocated in the near future and envisage a growing
partnership with them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SAGA THAT'S SET TO RUN AND RUN</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALLAN STEWART</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584195</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Monklands saga looks to be about as long running as Coronation
Street. The inquiry announced by Ian Lang into staffing will take some
time.
The staffing figures are interesting. If the average person in
Monklands had as many relatives employed by the council as the average
councillor, Monklands would be employing well over 300,000.
Makes one think. Not that there is necessarily anything wrong in the
relatives of councillors being employed by a council. But the scale of
it in Monklands raises questions, to put it mildly.
What is surprising about the reaction of Monklands to Professor
Black's report is that they commissioned it. Now they reject it
completely.
As for the future, Monklands District Council, like all other existing
councils, will no longer exist from next year. The people of Monklands
will be citizens of a new council - North Lanarkshire. A much needed
fresh start.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
