<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Don't step into trouble at an interview. Do's and dont's of arranging to meet a would-be employer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GERALDINE ABRAHAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>JOPB SEARCH</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584198</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MANY people are willing to turn their hands to a variety of different
work - and that means that they often find themselves in unusual
interview situations.
While most of these will be straightforward, there is always the
possibility of 'rogue' situations arising with unscrupulous - or indeed
bogus - employers.
It is important to be vigilant in all instances and it is worth taking
on board the advice of the Employment Service when going for an
interview.
* Tell a friend or relative where you are going and when you will
return
* If the interview takes place after working hours, arrange for
someone to collect you
* Get as much background information on the company as possible before
you go
* Make sure your interview is at the employer's premises or in a
public place. Don't agree to meet in a location that you don't feel safe
in
* Don't agree to continue the interview over drinks or a meal
* Don't let the interviewer steer the interview towards personal
subjects unrelated to the job
* Don't accept a lift home from the interviewer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
