<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>JOHNNY RACES INTO A ROW</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584201</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER racing driver Johnny Dumfries is in the middle of a battle
between two Scottish health trusts.
Aristocrat Dumfries, an ex Formula One ace who won Le Mans in 1988,
and is now the Marquess of Bute, is offering land to Ayrshire and Arran
Community Health Trust to build a community hospital for East Ayrshire.
However, South Ayrshire Hospitals Trust wants the facility to be built
on a site at its own Ballochmyle Hospital near Mauchline.
The Community Trust is backing a consortium of Cumnock GPs who have
planned for the hospital to include a 24-bed medium acute unit at the
10-acre greenfield site Johnny Dumfries is offering in Cumnock.
Ayrshire and Arran Health Board has put the matter out to consultation
and is considering the views of both health trusts, local people, and
district councillors.
Community Trust chiefs feel Ballochmyle would be the wrong site for
the hospital to serve the health problems faced by East Ayrshire's
30,000 population.
Its vice-chairman Scott McConnell said: ''Now that we have obtained a
site the credibility of our case must now stand even higher with the
local population.
''We will now present our case to the Ayrshire and Arran Health Board
in the next few days, not as part of the battle between trusts, but as
an option based on good value for money for everyone concerned.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
