<HEADLINE>Security clampdown at murder station</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584202</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SECURITY is to be stepped up at an Ayrshire railway station, where a
young woman was murdered.
Closed circuit cameras are to be installed along with more effective
lighting at the unmanned West Kilbride station.
It was in a bothy at the station that the body of 27-year-old murder
victim Yvette Wilson, (pictured left), was found in January. Her killer
Edward Mullen, (25), was later jailed for life.
Now the Strathclyde Passenger Transport Executive has unveiled
measures to make the station safer and more attractive.
And they were today welcomed by Cunninghame North MP Brian Wilson as
''very solid progress''.
While Mr Wilson said that he would still prefer to see all stations
manned he added: ''In the present economic climate the cameras are a
very useful step forward.''
The station car park is to be resurfaced and new seating provided on
the platform.
</TEXT>
