<HEADLINE>SCOTS IN RAIL CHAOS THREAT. Union strike ballot over drivers' pay</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GORDON THOMSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584204</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTS rail commuters face summer holiday strike chaos.
Train drivers are thought to have backed a series of 24-hour stoppages
in a bid to win a better pay deal.
And the summer of discontent which is likely to bring Scotland's rail
network to a standstill could begin next week at the start of the
Glasgow Fair.
A strike ballot involving 12,000 thousand drivers with the Associated
Society of Locomotove Engineers and Firemen ended at noon today.
And Aslef sources predicted ''a significant majority'' wanted the
stoppages to try to force rail chiefs to improve a ''final offer'' pay
rise of three per cent.
Profit
Union officials will meet later today to be officially informed of the
strike ballot result.
If strike action is planned, unions must give BR 10 days notice before
the walk-outs.
Meanwhile, British Rail is set to announce bumper profits later this
week - its last financial year before privatisation.
Rail Maritime and Transport union members at BR are also voting on
one-day strikes over pay.
RMT general secretary Jimmy Knapp said: ''The expected profit
justifies the arguments we made during the pay negotiations that BR can
afford more and that the workforce deserve a better offer than three per
cent.''
</TEXT>
