<HEADLINE>Party punches cost man his job</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584206</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WORKER who punched a former works manager and his foreman at a
Christmas ''do'' has lost his unfair dismissal case.
An Industrial Tribunal heard the sacked employee thought the men, one
of whom was his brother-in-law, had kicked a stool he was dancing on.
John Moffat, of Inverurie Street, Springburn, Glasgow, was employed as
a yardman for 16 years by Clydeside Galvanisers, Yorkhill, Glasgow,
until he was sacked on December 20 last year.
Employees of the zinc galvanisers had been having a festive night out.
The Tribunal noted: ''The applicant was one of those dancing on a
stool and whilst doing so, considered that the stool had been kicked.
''He decided that the perpetrator was Mr Colin Turnbull - the ex works
manager and the applicant struck Mr Turnbull in the face.''
When Mr Moffat claimed Mr Turnbull had kicked the stool, his
brother-in-law Duncan Neilson said that it wasn't the ex works manager
but himself.
At this the yardman punched his brother-in-law on the mouth.
The tribunal verdict was: ''In our view the applicant's conduct
deserved dismissal.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
