<HEADLINE>Bosses say no to single currency</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584207</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTS business chiefs have voted against a single European currency.
Research carried out by the Forum of Private Business shows that 44.9
per cent of those polled oppose the move.
The survey shows that 31.4 per cent were undecided when asked if they
favoured a common currency in Europe.
And only 23.7 per cent were in favour of a common European currency.
A big majority - 65.2 per cent - would support a proposal for a
referendum on Europe.
Only 20 per cent of Scots businesses are opposed to the idea of a
European referendum.
Stan Mendham, head of FPB, said: ''The private business community is
saying that the politicians are pushing them further than they want to
go.
''Falling support for a single currency suggests that many business
owners fear this would signal the ceding to Europe to key areas such as
taxtion and employment issues.''
The survey shows that overall 71 per cent of members are against
speeding up the process towards a federal Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
