<HEADLINE>Minor Tec</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584208</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE name's Dunphy. James Dunphy.
I was bored with life so I decided to become a private eye. It kinda
appealed to me.
I got some funny looks at first because I'm only 11.
It ain't every day you see a primary school kid tracking down
unfaithful husbands and the like.
Still, they say size don't matter.
So how did I become an Honorary Investigator with a framed certificate
to prove it?
The kids in my class at Wallacestone Primary in Falkirk were
discussing what they wanted to do. Some said doctors. Some said train
drivers. Guess who piped up and said private eye.
I wrote to this Glasgow company, City Investigations in Ingram Street,
asking for tips. They gave me the 4.15 at Ayr. I told them I was
serious.
So they hauled me in and told me to stick in at school.
They've even promised me an interview when I'm 18.
And hey - guess the name of the guy who's taken me in hand here?His
name's Marlow. Not Philip, though. Ian.
But with someone with that surname looking out for me, a budding tec
can't go far wrong!
Picture: BRIAN HICKEY
</TEXT>
