<HEADLINE>Return of the young apprentice. NEW RECRUITS PREPARE TO STEP INTO THE FUTURE WITH CONFIDENCE</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GERALDINE ABRAHAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>JOB SEARCH</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584210</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A RECENT conference heralded the return of apprenticeships in
Scotland.
The Scottish Modern Apprenticeships Seminar was attended by training
representatives from the LECs, Scottish Enterprise and Industrial
Training Organisations.
The modern apprenticeships envisaged had been endorsed in a
consultation document from the Secretary of State, and will be delivered
through the Skillseekers training initiative.
Areas like engineering, chemicals, plumbing and information technology
are included and all have been identified as areas of need within the
Scottish economy.
John Cunningham, director of training at Lanarkshire Development
Agency said: ''This new initiative will ensure young people are educated
and trained to a high level to undertake careers in a wide range of
occupations.
''It is vital that we gather the views of industry throughout Scotland
to establish the best way forward.''
The new apprenticeships differ from the original ones in that the
training is not time-served but competency-based.
The young people involved will be employed from the start of training
and that training will be to Scottish Vocational Qualification (SVQ)
Level 3 or above.
The expectation is that in any of these industries, the apprentice
will be paid the rate for the job and, while this is not mandatory, the
Group would ask questions where it is not the case.
Mr Cunningham continued:''The vast majority will be employed
apprentices receiving the rate for the job.
''We believe that modern aprentices have a valuable role to play in
the future of scottish industry.
And he added:''It will not only mean that we have a highly trained
workforce, but young people will be given the chance to gain invaluable
experience on the job training within full-time employment.''
</TEXT>
