<HEADLINE>Upper-cuts give Lewis the upper hand</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>977584217</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THREE upper-cuts from Lennox Lewis were enough to stop Australian
Justin Fortune in four rounds in a non-title fight in Dublin last night.
The former World Boxing Council heavyweight champion finally found his
range and power just as Fortune was beginning to cause him problems. It
was no more than expected with Lewis, at 6ft 5ins, towering over the
former Sydney nightclub doorman by eight inches.
He also had a weight advantage of more than two stone, but Lewis did
not have matters all his own way and admitted: ''He caught me with some
useful shots. I deliberately started cautiously just to size him up but
knew when I stepped up the pace I would get to him.
''He was very game and I was surprised he did not go down as I threw
some tremendous punches. The referee was right to stop it. I was really
bending my knees into those upper-cuts and did not want him to get hurt.
It's the brave guys who always get hurt.''
Lewis was stung into action by a solid jab from Fortune, replying with
two looping right hands at the beginning of the second round and two
more towards the end. At 17st 8lbs he was always going to be too
powerful but for a while found his man awkward to hit as Fortune
bulldozed in and frequently ended up with his head in the former
champion's chest or under his arms.
Lewis was now beginning to put his jab together but Fortune came back
at him in the third when his willingness to trade punches was well
received by the crowd.
In the next, Fortune's head was rocked back by the force of those
three upper-cuts and as he staggered back across the ring into the
ropes, referee Roy Francis immediately called a halt.
''They told me he was a big puncher,'' said the Australian, ''but I
must say I was disappointed with his performance.''
* NASEEM Hamed claimed after having stopped Colombian Juan Polo Perez
at the Royal Albert Hall, ''I could have done better.''
A near-capacity crowd saw the 21-year-old underline his world
championship credentials with a crushing fifth defence of the WBC
international super-bantamweight title.
''I'm creeping up on the world champions,'' said Hamed. ''They know
I'm going to take away their titles. It doesn't matter where I get my
chance, but I would love to box at the Albert Hall again. It's a super
venue.''
</TEXT>
