<HEADLINE>Ball answers Lee's call and joins City</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>977584220</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALAN Ball was reaching for the sky yesterday after agreeing to become
the new manager of Manchester City. Ball was desperately trying to find
a flight back to England after cutting short a family holiday in Spain
to complete the deal.
City chairman Francis Lee admitted that he was so determined to team
up again with his old England team-mate that he was prepared to travel
to Ball's Marbella villa to discuss the deal. However, Lee managed to
speak to Ball by telephone yesterday and persuade him to walk out on
Southampton.
''There are a few details to finalise, but I see no problems,'' said
Lee.
Lee now faces a #500,000 compensation claim from Southampton, and last
week solicitors acting for Brian Horton revealed that the former City
manager -- now in charge at Huddersfield -- was suing his old club over
compensation for the remainder of his contract, around #200,000.
* UNIQUE new youth leagues proposed by Rangers and St Johnstone to
develop the skills of Scotland's top schoolboys and also cut down the
number of competitive games they play will kick off in September.
Under the auspices of the Scottish League, 14 of Scotland's senior
sides will meet each other home and away in under-15 and under-16
matches which will have no points at stake, or medals or trophies.
Instead, games will consist of three, 30-minute segments and ''time
out'' coaching breaks.
Rangers manager Walter Smith said of the initiative: ''It takes away a
lot of the pressure and puts the boys in an environment where they can
learn.''
