<HEADLINE>Accies still on the slide</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANK MORAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>977584221</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EAST LEAGUE:
THE second ball of the day at Raeburn Place accounted for Willie Tait
and after that it was all downhill for Edinburgh Academicals. Despite
another fine knock by Peter Flockhart, whose 71 was almost half the
innings total, and an early-order wobble by Heriot's, there were overs
aplenty in hand when Steve Litster hit the winning runs.
Victory for Corstorphine and a good draw for Falkland now means
second-bottom spot for Accies.
This grim turn of events contrasted starkly with the fortunes of their
visitors. The Herioters have yet to drop a point, whereas their
principal challengers, Carlton, were disintegrating against Grange.
Heriot's match-winner again was Shahid Aslam, who took six wickets for
62 off his 22 overs, Jim Love claiming the four others, and then steered
the ship clear of choppy waters at 55 for four in tandem with Mike
Allingham as they shared a fifth-wicket stand of 73, Allingham hitting
52 and Aslam 60.
There was some lively cricket across the way. The Carlton bowlers
regularly located a bald patch on the track which caused the ball to fly
off at unpredictable angles. Poor David McLean behind the stumps
conceded 34 byes in a remarkable total of 54 extras. And as Graham
Hurlbatt, Nick Peet, and Pete Steindl were to demonstrate later, that
was not the line to be bowling.
Grange prospered with 250 from 48 overs, Johnny Everett top-scoring
with 63 and Alec Davies hitting 53.
Carlton were soon losing wickets regularly to the three-pronged home
attack. Bryn Lockie (25) and Alan McLeod (31) offered the only
resistance as the innings petered out at 91.
Stenhousemuir hit 258 at Myreside, skipper Douglas Zuill 76 not out
and Eddie Pollock and John Owens contributing 40s. But they were unable
to bowl out Watsonians thanks mainly to Kenny Scott's 70, and had to be
content with the better of the draw.
So, too, had Falkland after Cheany Pandya (83 not out) had led them to
a massive 253 for three at home to Royal High. The visitors survived by
three wickets, Manzoor Elahi the mainstay with 82.
At Union Park, Freuchie set Corstorphine more than 200 to win and they
made it with three wickets to spare.
</TEXT>
