<HEADLINE>Parten ton but capital triumph</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>977584222</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
QUAICH
EDINBURGH made their Royal Bank of Scotland Quaich success academic
last night with a six-wicket victory at Selkirk against South to clinch
the trophy.
The hosts started brightly, and openers Jason Arnberger and David
Wilson raced to 45 inside half-an-hour, the former eventually making a
speedy 53.
The pace slowed after this but the runs continued to come, mainly
through man-of-the-match Tommy Parten, who made an unbeaten 102,
including a partnership with Peter Bruce which reached 78 as the locals
made a respectable 221 for six.
In reality, the Quaich was as good as won before a ball had been
bowled, but a heavy defeat coupled with a particularly bad run rate
might have proved Edinburgh's undoing.
However, despite a slowish start after tea, the capital side never
looked likely to let this happen.
Openers Brian Lockie and Chris Smith went early but Gordon McGurk soon
weighed in with 46 before Mike Allingham made 63 and Alex Davies hit an
unbeaten 46.
Edinburgh soon passed their target, making 225 for the loss of only
four wickets.
Strathclyde West secured second spot in the table with a two-wicket
victory at Hamilton Crescent over Strathclyde East.
Opener Alistair Storie made 70 for East, the home side, but despite 38
apiece from George Reifer and Greg Williamson, they could manage only
196 for eight.
After the restart, West made the target with three wickets to spare.
Central will have to settle for second-bottom despite a fine win over
North at McKane Park.
Aslam Raza's century, along with 63 from David Orr and 45 from Wayne
Sullivan, set the home side on their way to 295 for six.
After tea, Raza and Rob Mitchinson took three wickets apiece to
dismiss the visitors for 165.
