<HEADLINE>It's a breeze for Kirk and Geronimo</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDI ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>977584223</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GERONIMO, the IOR 50-footer run by Regatta Team Scotland, scored three
firsts from four races to win the 18-boat Class One at the Minerva Ford
Clyde Regatta at the weekend.
It landed Nicky Kirk the Clyde Master Helm trophy for the first time
and provided some consolation for the Largs-based thwarted Admiral's Cup
contender.
That project ground to a standstill due to a lack of sponsorship, but
the core of the proposed crew rarely put a foot wrong over the weekend's
four short Olympic triangle races in inconsistent shifting winds on the
southernmost of the two courses off Inverkip.
''It was pretty much the way things go, the boat likes light winds and
thankfully that's what we got, so we were able to capitalise,''
explained sailmaker Kirk, a former West Highland Week and Impala
European champion.
With an entry of 110 boats, boosted this year by a solid pack of 20
Etchells warming up for the UK championships which start on these waters
today, there was some evidence that a change of sponsors and revised
organisation might provide the initiative to rebuild what was once the
estuary's premier annual regatta.
Keith Lawrence, the local Gourock skipper, managed to hold off the
fiercely competitive Etchells fleet, taking two victories yesterday to
add to a second and third on Saturday.
Lawrence has paired Barcelona Olympian Andy Hemmings and Stuart
Childerly in his national championship campaign and they made a
formidable team winning the last race on the finish line from Adam
Gosling's Yes!
In second place overall was double Olympic gold medalist Poul Richard
Hoj Jensen.
Consistency throughout the very tricky conditions on the first day
when the upwind track frequently offered two competing winds and a
corridor of 'no man's land' where the conflicting breezes nullified each
other, prevailed into yesterday's two races for Simon Pender on the helm
of St Joan.
The double Scottish Series winner triumphed in the Sigma 33 fleet,
counting three thirds and a second.
In the Sport Boat class, Steve Goatcher, the Sonata UK champion,
steered the New Zealand designed and built Elliot 5.9 to an overall win
as his long-time rival from the Sonata and the Flying 15 classes Iain
Laidlaw won the Sonata Class in Rhythm Stick.
