<HEADLINE>Duel resumes in Paris</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>977584224</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO world-record attempts back up the latest confrontation between
Linford Christie and Carl Lewis at today's grand-prix meeting in Paris.
A 100m contest between Britain's Christie and American Lewis may not
hold the glamour it once did, with both athletes having had slow starts
to the season. But Christie is the world and Olympic champion, having
taken the titles from Lewis, and the contest should still hold centre
stage.
Record attempts in Paris, meanwhile, will be made by Algerian
Nourredine Morceli and Ethiopian Haile Gebresilasie. Morceli already
holds the world 1500m, 3000m, and mile bests and will be seeking to
better the 2000m mark held by Said Aouita. Gebresilasie, who broke the
world 10,000m record earlier this year, has his sights set on
recapturing the 5000m after Kenyan Moses Kiptanui beat his one-year-old
mark with 12min 55.30sec last month in Rome.
Britain's Colin Jackson is scheduled to run in the 110m hurdles and
another world record-holder, American Mike Powell, is in the long jump.
</TEXT>
