<HEADLINE>Neef too hot for rivals</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>977584225</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MELANIE Neef, winner of the 400m race at the Europa Cup final at Lille
last weekend, maintained her season's unbeaten record with an
outstanding run in the United Kingdom women's league first-division
match at Copthall Stadium, Hendon.
Running just 24 hours before competing in the 200m sprint in the
grand-prix meeting at Gateshead, Neef faced four Great Britain sprinters
in the 400m race.
Running strongly, she recorded her third-fastest time ever for the
event to win the class race of the day in 52.0sec, defeating
internationalists Stephanie Llweyellyn (Shaftsbury), who set an Irish
record of 52.4 in second place ahead of Lorraine Hanson (Birchfield)
53.3, Louise Fraser (Trafford) 53.9, and Jennifer Stout (Essex) 54.5.
The Glasgow woman also ran a fast stage in the 4 x 400m relay, lifting
her team from eighth to third on the third stage of the race.
Jane Low recorded another Glasgow win in the 400m hurdles in 60.4sec,
with team-mate Alison Mahindru winning the B race in 63.3, and Hazel
Melvin taking the B triple jump with a leap of 10.88m.
Because of holidays, injuries, and weddings, Glasgow were without 11
of their top athletes, including Great Britain shot and discus
internationalist Alison Grey, and with just one match remaining are
second equal with Shaftsbury/Barnet AC behind leaders Sale Harriers.
</TEXT>
