<HEADLINE>Skill factor is being bludgeoned out of Wimbledon. Power steals the glory</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SPORT, WIMBLEDON 95</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584227</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WIMBLEDON, home of the aloof, the unaccommodating, and the detached
from reality. That takes care of the players, who seem to become more
mechanical and less human every year.
It has been an interesting first week at the Big W, as some of our
American friends like to call the championships, but which should really
be referred to now as the Big Bang because of the thunderous power being
used. The tennis has been poor so far and interest came from taking part
in the Great Debate: has the skill been bludgeoned out of Wimbledon?
Actually, when I say great debate that doesn't mean everyone who walks
through the gates is fretting over a decline in standards of on-court
excellence. No, the majority of the visitors -- from the blue bloods who
wander around the All England Lawn Tennis Club's gardens watching to see
if they are being watched, to the great unwashed who sleep on the
pavements outside -- are in awe of the place and its stuffy traditions.
One gets the impression that Wimbledon would survive as a main stop on
the world's sporting calendar even if the players stopped coming. We are
talking about a heady mixture of history and myth here. People want to
say: ''I've been to Wimbledon.''
Yet they would be doing themselves and the sport a great service if
they were to question their own part in perpetuating the myth that this
is a magical sporting kingdom.
By God, it is not the players who are preserving the event. If it were
left entirely to them, the astonishing appeal of Wimbledon would have
diminished long ago, and you have only to glance back over a first week
which offered little.
If it hadn't been for a weary old-timer, Mats Wilander, who played a
thrilling five-setter against Marc Goellner on Wednesday, Tim Henman's
decision to use a ball-girl as target practice, or Jeff Tarango's
variation on the old ''I'll get my big brother to you'' line after
having been bullied by an umpire, the first half of Wimbledon would have
been a crushing bore.
Despite the sweaty, grunting, clenched-teeth endeavour of it all there
are people who believe the tennis has been thrilling. They reckon
Hangdog Sampras and little baggy-drawers Agassi with his latest
superstar lady are enough to keep fans happy. But we need more. Granted,
Agassi did serve up some delights in his match against David Wheaton on
Saturday, but come on, let's cut to the tennis.
Is there anyone other than Agassi out there playing it? Is it true we
will never see the likes of McEnroe, Edberg at his peak, Leconte, Noah,
or Borg again? Have their successors been killed off by sheer power?
The search for the answers veered away from Wimbledon towards
Gleneagles, where the rich and famous were out in force again. This time
they were competing in the Rolex Jackie Stewart Celebrity Challenge,
which raised #450,000 for four deserving charities. The list of names
was impressive and among them were Rod Laver and Stan Smith, who occupy
their own slots in tennis folklore.
Smith, who won the singles championship in 1972 after a thrilling
five-set final against the first of tennis's really bad guys, Ilie
Nastase, stands in awe of the power being delivered by today's
champions, but then the American could be cited as one of the
forerunners of the heavy-duty serve. ''The power today is truly
amazing,'' he said. ''Not only the serve, but also the speed of the
returns and passing shots.''
However, Laver, whose affair with Wimbledon was aesthetically rich and
profitable, was more scathing of the modern player and the four-times
champion won't even bother watching this fortnight. ''I came over here
to help with this cause, but I won't go to Wimbledon,'' he said. There
was a weary resignation, maybe even a sadness, in his voice.
Laver, winner of the first Wimbledon in the open era (1968) and a folk
hero of the world's courts, was only an hour's flight from the tennis,
but he lacked the desire to stop by the scene of his greatest triumphs.
''Racket technology has taken the game on to a new level and at the same
time this technology has allowed more ordinary people to play,'' he
said.
''The rackets made it easier for people to become professionals more
easily. It used to be a player had a hard job with the learning process
before he was able to compete at the top, and that was because the old
wooden rackets demanded more skill and more work on shots.
''In my time there was a wider variety of shot and the full dimensions
of courts were used, whereas players today know that, as soon as they
get a slight opportunity, the power in their rackets will allow them to
put the ball away. In other words, they may take the easier option.''
Laver, like a growing number of players, fans, and organisers, worries
about the power and speed, and of what these two qualities are doing to
Wimbledon's image. ''Look at the French (Open), look at the tennis
played on the clay there,'' he said. ''It is so much more entertaining
and offers greater variety.
''Players are required to manoeuvre and engineer shots more there and
you would only get that kind of tennis at Wimbledon with, say, a match
between Agassi and Chang, two players who rely on speed, anticipation,
agility, and shot-making.''
The great Australian player offered suggestions like slowing the balls
further, allowing Wimbledon's grass to grow slightly longer, and
regulating the tension of racket strings, but he knows nothing will be
done. The money keeps washing over Wimbledon, which had a surplus last
year of #28,888,806.
Consider Laver's lot after he had won in '68, and becoming the year's
leading money-earner with $124,000, to Sampras' income from his last
year. He banked $3,607,812.
It is important to remember also that this figure is only prize money,
and if you wish an idea of how much Sampras might have earned in total
you would be erring madly on the side of caution if you doubled this
figure.
Players earn staggering amounts through endorsements, with the wealth
of even the tour's mediocrities reaching into millions, and perhaps by
looking at the sums it is easier to understand why most of these players
show a disdain for their public. So many dozens of them have reached
their own financial comfort zones that they see no reason to accommodate
anyone.
Karsten Braasch, whose claim to fame is a service action which looks
as though it was taught by a contortionist, earned $317,232 last year,
Jonas Bjorkman got away with $756,552, Andrea Gaudenzi took $445,699,
and somebody who is really nobody, John-Laffnie de Jager, was given
$124,731. I could rest my case there, but Ivan Lendl's career prize
money is only a couple of notes short of $26m, which suggests the sport
is out of control.
''Money is a problem,'' Laver said, ''and the more someone has the
harder it may be for him to wake up and push himself every day. When
your pocket is full, it is easier to lie in.''
He shook his head and wandered off to continue his fund-raising
effort. Small and wiry, but his 56 years beginning to show on his face,
Laver could put most of them at Wimbledon to shame, but he won't be
going. Doesn't see the point. Besides, he talks some sense.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
