<HEADLINE>Celtic's Irish blues</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584228</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Celtic Swing bandwagon came badly off the rails at The Curragh
yesterday when Peter Savill's colt trailed in miles behind the winner,
Winged Love, in the Irish Derby.
Celtic Swing has often displayed a dislike for firm ground, but a
dejected Savill refused to accept that the going, officially described
as good to firm, had caused his runner's downfall and believes something
must have been wrong with the 5-4 favourite.
''The run is too bad to be true,'' said Savill. ''The horse that
finished behind him in the French Derby has won. It's not as if he has
turned the form round by a length -- Celtic Swing was way behind.
''Kevin Darley (Celtic Swing's rider) said that, for him, the ground
was plenty fast enough, but I can't use that as an excuse. Too many
jockeys have praised it, having ridden on it in the last three days.
''We can't make any plans now. We will take him home and have the vets
look at him to see if we can find anything wrong.''
But as Savill scratched his head in bewilderment, Sheikh Mohammed
really enjoyed his day, for not only did Winged Love impress by getting
his head in front on the line, but earlier in the afternoon the owner's
Carnegie, last year's Prix de l' Arc de Triomphe winner, instigated a
Group One double for the Arab owner with a thrilling victory in the
Grand Prix de Saint-Cloud in Paris.
Sheikh Mohammed, who donated his first prize of #338,350 in Ireland to
local charities, said after the race that the Arc will be Winged Love's
main target.
''We were only hopeful after the French Derby but he had improved
since then and he will be an even better horse in the autumn,'' he said.
Walter Swinburn, third on best British finisher, Annus Mirabilis,
said: ''He's run a big race. His heart is twice the size of himself. He
got the trip well. He is a real special horse.''
* PIQUANT will carry the Queen's colours at Edinburgh this evening
when Her Majesty visits the course to open the new #750,000 corporate
hospitality complex and improved stable yard, writes Tom McConnell.
The eight-year-old will be partnered by Jason Weaver in the East
Lothian District Council Handicap, the second of two races which the
Queen will watch after her tour of the new facilities.
Although Piquant has won eight races he has not shown much form this
season. His last win was at Lingfield in November, and on his most
recent run at Goodwood he was fourth in an amateur riders' race.
Gospel Song, a winner of two races earlier in the season, is not
without a chance but Mark Johnston's Jubran, second and third on his
last two visit to Edinburgh, is the most likely winner.
</TEXT>
