<TEXT>
FRANK Nobilo fought off local hero Bernhard Langer and rising Swedish
star Jarmo Sandelin to win the BMW International Open at St Eurach, near
Munich, yesterday.
The New Zealander, who lives in London, turned a five-shot deficit
into a two-shot victory to earn the #91,660 first prize. Nobilo, whose
last success was in Indonesia a year ago, fired a final-round 67 for a
16-under-par total of 272.
Victory was all the sweeter for Nobilo, who believes the Volvo
European Tour is getting tougher each year and that Nick Faldo's remarks
about ''comfort zones'' were out of order.
''The cuts are getting lower and the standards are getting higher,''
said Nobilo. ''After the way this year has gone, I am delighted to win
again. Five shots are difficult to get back.''
Sandelin and Ireland's Raymond Burns, who finished joint-seventh, both
stepped up from the Challenge Tour last season and are beginning to make
an impact.
Nobilo, who had a top-10 finish at the US Open, drew level with
Sandelin -- the overnight leader, who shot a course-record 63 on
Saturday -- at the turn thanks to an eagle at the first, followed by
five birdies.
Nobilo then made headway down the home stretch, fighting off the
threat from Langer, who is always a dangerous competitor and never more
so than on his home territory.
However, although the German also returned a 67, his 73 on the opening
day, when he was suffering from a neck injury, proved costly.
