<TEXT>
STEVE Redgrave, three times Olympic champion and five times world
champion, concluded his career at Henley Royal Regatta with a flourish
yesterday. He won the Silver Goblets for the seventh time with partner
Matthew Pinsent at the end of the day's racing, after earlier setting a
new record time in the Prince Philip Cup for coxed fours.
Redgrave will be involved in a pre-Olympic training camp during next
year's regatta and, with plans to retire after Atlanta, now looks likely
to conclude his domestic career with a total of 15 Henley wins.
In Saturday's semi-final, Redgrave and Pinsent set a new course record
of 6min. 56secs., beating their own previous record by 13 seconds and
becoming the first pair to go through the seven-minute barrier.
A number of records tumbled yesterday. The Australian double of Markus
Free and Olympic gold medalist Peter Antonie, beat a USA squad crew by
just two feet on the line in the closest race of the day. Then in the
Grand Challenge Cup final, this year's young British crew pushed the
American world champions all the way to go down by just a third of a
length.
In the Diamond Sculls, Juri Jaanson of Estonia, beat the defending
champion Xeno Muller of Switzerland, while in the women's singles
sculls, Maria Brandin of Sweden, beat controversial Canadian Silken
Laumann, taking 23 seconds off the course record which she set up in
1993. Winners:
Grand Challenge Cup -- San Diego Training Center, USA.
Ladies' Plate -- Nottinghamshire County.
Thames Cup -- Imperial College, London.
