<TEXT>
DAVID Gillanders crashed out of the lead in then Burmah Scottish Rally
Championship at the weekend on the sixth round of the series, the Jim
Clark Memorial event.
The former British champion was leading after four of Saturday's seven
special stages when he made rare mistake. Having just taken the lead of
the rally from last year's winner Michael Horne, Gillanders was going
well in the Kielder Forest complex.
His Ford Escort Cosworth crested a rise only to find the forest road
veering sharper right than the treeline suggested. The car slid wide on
the bend and vaulted a ditch, from where it took spectators more than
half an hour to extricate the car.
John Baird, the Merseyside-based Edinburgh exile, now heads the 85-car
field, but Horne was just three seconds behind with two stages to go.
As winner of this event, in a similarly close-fought fight last year,
the big partisan crowd were willing local man Horne to repeat that
success. Over the penultimate forest road special stage, he clawed back
a second of Baird's lead.
Going into the final stage at Riccarton on the Scottish/English
border, Baird's lead now was two seconds. Ahead lay nine miles of
flat-out, timed to the second motoring, with two seconds separating the
two favourites.
Within a mile of the finish, Horne's Ford Sierra punctured a tyre and
dropped half a minute to Baird. That put victory beyond doubt and Baird,
with co-driver Martin Forrest, scored a first outright victory on a
national championship event. Neil Hiorns found the long trip north
worthwhile with third place overall ahead of Walter Henderson
(Carnwath). Results:
