<HEADLINE>Scots trio making progress</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584233</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INJURY-HIT Tom McKean and Yvonne Murray made encouraging movements
towards top form in their first test of the season at the Gateshead BUPA
Games.
Though McKean could finish only seventh in the 800 metres behind
European silver medallist, Norway's Vebjorn Rodal, he slashed more than
two seconds off his season's best time, clocking 1min 47.76sec, with
which he was quietly pleased, considering the problems he has had
recently. Rodal scampered away from the field to win in 1-45.45.
''I'm not ready to run 1-45.0 yet but it's a step in the right
direction,'' said McKean.
The 31-year-old Uddingston star, who dropped out of last weekend's
Scottish Championships, tried to run a secret time trial in a
Lanarkshire League race at Coatbridge last Wednesday night, winning in a
slow 1-52.22.
The former European champion, who had knee trouble earlier in the
season, then made his British League debut for Haringey in London on
Saturday, winning the 800 in 1-50.25.
Sciatica-victim Murray showed no signs of the problem which kept her
out of the European Cup 5000m in Lille as she moved down a distance to
1500m to capture a gritty third just behind her great Irish rival, Sonia
O'Sullivan, in a fast 4-05.61. But there was no doubt about the winner,
Britian's Kelly Holmes sprinting clear in 4-04.21, the fastest time in
the world this year.
Mel Neef continues to break new ground and followed up her UK Women's
League 400m victory in 52.0sec at Barnet on Saturday with a new best
200m time of 23.35 in finishing second at Gateshead yesterday.
The top performance of the day came from Daniella Bartova from the
Czech Republic, who set a new world women's pole vault record of 4.14m.
Kate Staples -- better known as Zodiac on TV's Gladiators -- set new UK
and Commonwealth women's pole vault records with 3.80m.
Bartova's new mark was the first world record set in the arena since
Brendan Foster ran the 3000m in 7-35.1 on the day the stadium opened on
August 3, 1974.
Jonathan Edwards continued the magnificent form that saw him produce
the longest triple jump in history last weekend.
Edwards, in front of his home crowd, flew out to 18.03 metres in the
third round of the event -- the longest leap ever seen in Britain.
But, as at the European Cup in Lille last weekend, he was denied a
world record because of an illegal tailwind of 2.9m per second.
The Gateshead Harrier leapt an astonishing 18.43m in France last
Sunday but the wind also denied him a place in the record books that
time.
The wind finally died down for Edwards in the later rounds as he broke
his own UK record.
He equalled the 17.72m set last weekend in yesterday's fourth round
and, after having passed the fifth round, added two centimetres to his
legal best with his final leap to beat it.
The Gateshead Harrier also added 13cm to the UK all-comers' record of
17.61m set by Cuba's Yoelvis Quesada last year.
But Rob Denmark could finish only third in the 5000m, won by South
Africa's Shadrack Hoff. ''My mind was wandering on the last lap, which
is usually my forte,'' admitted the Commonwealth champion.
And there was worse trouble for European 400m champion Du'aine Ladejo,
who pulled up halfway down the back straight with a hamstring strain,
which must put a question mark over his fitness for the AAA
championships -- serving also as the world-championship trials -- in a
fortnight.
* KENYA will parade a galaxy of emerging stars blended with known top
performers at the world championships in Gothenburg next month after
some dramatic national trials held in Nairobi at the weekend.
With the main focus on the 800m -- where Olympic champion William
Tanui and world champion Paul Ruto were eclipsed in the semi-finals --
few noticed that established stars such as Paul Ereng, Billy Konchellah,
Patrick Konchellah, and Nixon Kiprotich had not even entered.
Instead, rising stars Joseph Tengelei, William Serem, and Philip
Kibitok completed a 1-2-3 at the games, used as trials for both the
world championships and the All African Games in Harare in September.
Former 10,000m record-holder William Sigei was beaten into sixth place
and former world champion Moses Tanui was dropped. Little-known Josphat
Machuka won in 27-53.0 followed by 20-year-old soldier Joseph Kimani and
cross-country star Paul Tergat. It was Kimani's major track debut.
