<TEXT>
WESTERN UNION:
FOR the past seven days, the Kilmarnock NK regulars have done little
else but moan. They reckoned it should have been them, and not
Uddingston, who rid themselves last weekend of the winless tag.
Those at Kirkstyle have been saying for ages that eventually things
would come good -- and that someone would suffer.
On Saturday, West of Scotland were on the receiving end at Hamilton
Crescent when Killie won their first DM Hall Western Union encounter of
the season. And they did it with style.
Alastair Storie, Mark Harper, and Jon Williams all got among the runs,
and were in turn removed by Asif Mujtaba in his spell that was worth
five for 56. From 76 for one after 27 overs, West managed 185 for six,
with the feeling being that the home side should have set a bigger
target.
But, given the way they set about the chase, Killie could have been
set 300 and still won with ease, as Mujtaba and Muzamil Malik especially
showed how to carry the attack to the bowlers.
After just three balls, Kilmarnock were 8-1, Mike Richardson driven
for 4, then edged to the boundary, before the bowler got his yorker to
work.
Mujtaba entered the fray, and simply destroyed the bowling. The
Pakistani Test man played every shot in the book, and some twice, as he
took just 54 balls to pile up his unbeaten 97, which contained 17
boundaries. At the opposite end, Muzamil Malik also went for his shots,
his 50 not out coming off 68 deliveries, with seven 4s.
In one ball short of 16 overs, they added 116 in an unbroken stand for
the fourth wicket, Kilmarnock knocking off the required runs in just 31
overs.
As one unwanted record went, so did a cherished one. Greenock lost for
the first time, beaten at Cambusdoon by defending champions Ayr.
Albert Simpson's 49 in 64 balls was in contrast to Bruce Patterson's
innings, with whom Simpson added 73 for the second wicket.
The Scotland opener struggled to find his touch on not the easiest of
strips. He hung around for 49 overs, by which time he had made 55. Andy
Baird and Adrian Holdstock applied the pressure, and the Greenock
batting crumbled. Only Ronnie Thomson, walking out when the score was
already 39 for three, made any impression. Ayr wrapped up both the
points and victory with eight overs remaining, Greenock bowled out for
126.
Poloc also bowled out the opposition, spin twins Keith Sheridan and
Muzaffer Mahmood reducing Drumpellier from 35 without loss to 138 all
out, leaving Poloc winners by 37 runs.
Elsewhere, there were a couple of quick finishes. By 4.22, Ferguslie
-- who gifted Uddingston 16 of their 69 runs in no-balls -- had won by
eight wickets. And, under an hour later at Titwood, championship leaders
Progress Software Clydesdale secured an identical result against Tilbury
Phoenix Kelburne.
Richie Henderson cleaned out the Kelburne tail, his five for 20
leaving the home batsmen needing just 75 for another win, achieved in
comfort, despite Aamir Hanif falling for a first-ball duck.
