<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584235</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MICHAEL Schumacher accused Damon Hill of unsporting and dangerous
driving after having stretched his world championship lead following
victory in yesterday's French Grand Prix at Magny Cours.
Schumacher, who beat runner-up Hill by more than 30 seconds in his
Benetton, said he was shocked and angered by an incident involving Hill
on the thirteenth lap of the 72-lap race.
Hill, now 11 points behind the German in the quest for this year's
driver's championship, was leading in his Williams with Schumacher close
behind when the German said it seemed that Hill had ''brake-tested'' him
as they approached a backmarker.
''I was very angry with Damon,'' said Schumacher. ''But I am not
speaking to him about it until we have cooled off -- maybe at a quiet
moment later in the week.
''He seemed to lift his foot off the accelerator or maybe even braked
a little, and it was wrong. It was dangerous and unsporting. If he does
it again I know what to do with him.''
Schumacher had earlier said he was happy with the way the race went
for him as he took the lead from Hill after the first round of pit stops
and was never headed thereafter. ''Everything was just perfect,'' he
said. ''We were better prepared and quicker in the race. I knew when I
went into the lead I would win,'' he said.
Hill was baffled as to why the Williams team were finding it so
difficult to turn excellent practice performances into victory on the
track. ''It's a mystery why the car is good in qualifying but not so in
the race. It's something we must sort out,'' he said.
''Michael has extended his lead in the championship and that's not
good. But there is a long way to go and I still believe the title is
wide open.''
Hill's team-mate David Coulthard ended his three-race failure to
finish by taking third, although more than a minute behind Schumacher,
after having staved off a fierce bid for the podium from fellow Briton
Martin Brundle.
Norfolk-based Brundle was desperate to make the top three in his
Ligier team's home race but, despite a magnificent drive, was less than
a second adrift as he claimed his first points of the season.
''I did not expect to have such a battle with the Ligier,'' said
Coulthard. ''Martin was pushing very hard and I remembered the last time
he was behind me in Hungary last year -- I crashed.
''He got within lunging distance of me and I'd dreamt the night before
that I would crash on the last lap. But it is just good to finish and
get in among the points again.''
Brundle, competing for the fourth time since rejoining Ligier from
McLaren just before the start of the season, said: ''I've had three very
good races and no points previously, so it was good to get some finally.
''We would have been third but for our last pit stop, which cost us. I
would have got Coulthard eventually, as I was lapping a second faster
than the Williams, which I found amazing.''
Frenchman Jean Alesi could not deliver a second-successive victory
which the majority of the Magny Cours crowd wanted. He finished fifth,
with Jordan's Rubens Barrichello in the points for the second successive
race in sixth.
Eddie Irvine, aiming to follow up his third place in Canada, paid the
price for a poor second stop in the other Jordan to slip out of the
points into ninth. Mark Blundell finished eleventh after another
disappointing day for McLaren.
Johnny Herbert, forced out of the Canadian Grand Prix on the first lap
after a collision with Mika Hakkinen, lasted only until the third lap
this time.
Herbert's challenge ended when Alesi tried to overtake him on the
inside. The Londoner went off the circuit as Alesi and Ferrari team-mate
Gerhard Berger manoeuvred around his Benetton. Details (British unless
stated):
