<TEXT>
* WEST Indies coach Andy Roberts has admitted that his side, beaten by
England in the second Test last week, are suffering from mental fatigue.
Roberts saw his struggling team endure more misery at Hove yesterday
when they slumped to 97 for seven in reply to Sussex's 446 for nine
declared.
Only an unbeaten 70 from Keith Arthurton, plus stout resistance from
tailender Rajindra Dhanraj, enabled them to finish a weather-shortened
day on 167 for seven.
Rain and bad light, which allowed a total of only 30 minutes' play
after the first interruption, enabled them to regroup.
Nevertheless, Richie Richardson's side still face the prospect today
of becoming the first West Indies side to have to follow on in England
since the 1933 tourists suffered that embarrassment against Kent.
And if they are bowled out a second time, they will be the first West
Indies team to be beaten by an English county since 1976, when Middlesex
triumphed at Lord's.
