<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>977584239</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JONAH Lomu, New Zealand's World Cup giant, is set to dash the hopes of
league clubs desperate to sign him by agreeing a huge cash deal that
will keep him in Rugby Union for the next three years.
Other leading All Blacks could also soon be offered around #88,000
plus annual contracts, according to New Zealand's Sunday Star-Times. The
newspaper said there was a strong push for an annual base payment of
about #66,000 per year for all players who make the New Zealand side.
All Black coach Laurie Mains is quoted as saying: ''A package has been
agreed by Jonah and Phil Kingsley-Jones (his manager). Now Jonah has to
be given time during the next few days to go over it.
''What Jonah has said to the team and ourselves is that he really
wants to play in the next World Cup. Hopefully, it is just a matter of
us being able to finalise things.''
The amount offered to Lomu, who shattered England's World Cup dreams
with four semi-final tries last month, has not been disclosed.
The issue has been forced by a multi-million-pound television rights
deal with Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation, and pressure from Rugby
League.
</TEXT>
