<HEADLINE>Martin's triple crown</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>977584241</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MICHELLE Martin recovered from losing the opening game to beat
fellow-Australian Sarah Fitz-Gerald and retain the women's world squash
title in Hong Kong yesterday.
The top seed from Sydney became the first player to win the crown
three times in succession with an 8-10, 9-2, 9-6, 9-3 final triumph over
fourth seed Fitz-Gerald.
''It's tremendous to win three in a row,'' said 28-year-old Martin.
''It was magnificent the first time, but this is the best of the lot.
''This win is also more satisfying because it was a harder final and
the pressure was on me. But I stuck with my game plan and experience
helped me through.''
Martin, whose brother Rodney is a former men's world champion,
squandered five game points in a marathon first game. But she produced a
string of winners in the second to square the match.
She had survived a match point when playing Fitz-Gerald in the
semi-finals of last week's Malaysian Open, but she never looked in any
danger of having to dig herself out of a similar hole.
Martin came out on top in a series of hard-fought rallies in the third
game and dominated the fourth at the front of the court to clinch the
match.
</TEXT>
