<TEXT>
SARAH Gourlay, in the best traditions of her native Ayrshire, is a
doughty fighter. That trait shone through at Ayr Northfield on Saturday
when she recaptured the Scottish Women's Singles Bowls Championship.
Gourlay, the winner back in 1991, has played better. But winners are
those who survive when not playing at the top of their form, and Gourlay
did just that to recapture the title.
Indeed, she was pushed to the limit in Friday's second round and
quarter-finals, surviving both matches by the narrowest of 21-20
margins. And only a superb last bowl in her morning semi-final,
conjuring up a 3, gave her a final place again with a 25-21 win over
indoor internationalist Evelyn McGarvie, from Perth Caledonian.
Gourlay's final opponent was international colleague Nan Stirling,
from Corstorphine, and the Edinburgh player dominated the early
exchanges. She opened up a 7-0 lead after just three ends and by the
close of the twenty-first end, had the winning post in sight at 19-12.
Gourlay, however, rallied to square at 21-21 after 26 ends and a double
on the next pushed the former champion 23-21 ahead.
Stirling rallied with two singles to square again at 23-all, but after
Gourlay had missed a golden chance to add a match-winning second on the
thirtieth end, the Ayrshire player got the shot she needed to take the
title again on the following end.
The junior singles final produced a remarkable fightback when Kelly
Wilson (Laurieston) recovered from 21-7 down to beat Alison Forsyth
(Galashiels) 25-22.
Ayr Forehill's Valerie Bryce and Dorothy Barr took the pairs when they
beat County rivals Isabel Marshall and Jessie Steed 29-12, thanks mainly
to a maximum count of 8 on the seventh end that turned a 6-5 advantage
into a commanding 14-5 lead.
Dumfries's Valerie Gordon, Alison McLelland, Mary Ferguson, and Irene
Brown enjoyed an uninterrupted run of 11 shots over the last six ends to
beat Doreen Hain's Riverside rink 25-18 and, in the triples, Dunblane's
Jean Thomson, Mary Wright, and Jean Nairn got the all-important shot on
the extra end to defeat defending champions Carnwath 18-17.
Colinton's Catherine Thorburn and Jessie Macdonald led from the fourth
end to take the two-bowl pairs title with a 20-15 win over Queen's Park.
