<HEADLINE>Not everyone warms to sunshine soccer. Eccentrics enjoy zany European tournament</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584247</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Partick Thistle 3,
IBK Keflavik 1
IT BEGINS to look as if Thistle and the Intertoto Cup are meant for
each other. There are matching facets which suggest that the Firhill
club might just take one of their defiant turns and end up qualifying
for the preliminary round of the UEFA Cup.
For most folk, this Intertoto tournament is eccentric; who is more
eccentric than the Jags? It is a cup competition which does not have a
cup. That seems ideal for the old Maryhill troupers. No-one really
understands this competition. Does anyone truly understand Thistle?
The way things are going, it would be entirely appropriate if the
Firhill lot topped their group and went on to go further. Zany? You bet
they are.
They have played two games, looked beaten on both occasions, yet ended
up with four points out of a possible six. Their best player of last
week, Ian Cameron, who was outstanding in the 2-2 draw with Linzer ASK
in Austria, preferred to do his flitting on Saturday, after having
failed to agree a new contract. Manager John Lambie brought in Tom
Smith, who scored two goals. It seems logical enough.
The coach of the Icelandic side, Thorir Sigfusson, while a bit miffed
that his side squandered a first-half lead, and missed two golden
chances into the bargain, believes Thistle are good enough to win their
next assignment, against Metz in France on Saturday. Said Sigfusson:
''They are very strong and deserved to win in the end. They are much
harder and more physical than Metz, who beat us 2-1.
''I think they can beat Metz but, if the Scottish team play the way
they did against us, they will have to careful of Metz' quick
breakaways. I thought Tom Smith was excellent, with good skill, and he
always wanted to use the ball sensibly.''
Sigfusson's team next meet Zagreb, and he promises they will be doing
their best to help the Firhill cause, even if IBK are out of the running
themselves now.
Lambie, never one to couch his views in ambiguous language, did not
have a high opinion of the Icelanders. ''They wouldn't live in the
premier league,'' he said. ''If we were geared up we would have
crucified them.''
The manager's intention to use these games as a pre-season build-up is
questioned by many in the game, but he insists that it is better than a
tour of the Highlands or Ireland or some other ploy of that type. ''We
did that last year and ended up with two players out of action before
the season started. This tournament is giving our lads a good work-out.
''They said it was too hot and maybe that explains why they were so
sluggish in the first half. I don't think summer football would suit our
players but, having said that, once we started playing our own way, we
got better.''
As with the opening tie in Linz, Thistle's inclination to pass the
ball about at the back did not meet with the manager's approval. He was
waiting for them at half-time to give them a fair old rollicking, which
produced the desired change of style and gave the Icelanders a taste of
what the up-and-at-'em game is all about.
''These teams like to give you all the time in the world to build up,
but then they hit on the break. I hate to say it, but our best efforts
in the first half came from long, Nicky Walker clearances. Once we went
at them we gave them problems.''
Lambie, you would guess, has not been deterred by the defection of
Cameron or the fact that four other first-team regulars, plus many
others on the fringe, are out of contract. As well as Cameron, Greg
Watson, Alan Dinnie, Steve Pittman, and Derek McWilliams have yet to
sign new deals.
''I don't expect to have many problems,'' said the manager. ''If any
of them can better themselves they are free to do so, but everything
will change after 31 days, when we stop paying wages.''
He had hoped to have at least one new face in the side by the weekend,
but may not make it even by next weekend. However, he is determined it
will be done. Asked about filling Cameron's role, he said: ''If he
doesn't come back, I will just go out and sign someone better.''
Striker Rod McDonald had to leave the field after 23 minutes,
following a severe tackle that left him with an ankle injury. He was
taken for X-rays later but, other than that and a niggling Wayne Foster
injury, the pool seems in good fettle for the next chapter of this
bizarre summer tale.
They didn't look too sparkling after IBK, who had been content to let
Partick make the running, struck with a fine goal scored by their best
player, Yugoslav Marko Tanasic, in 20 minutes.
The Thistle crowd, all 3182 of them, had been in benevolent summer
mood until then, but they changed their mood, as Scottish fans do, when
their heroes lost their way a bit. ''Bonuses, ya balloons?'' was one
heart-felt cry. ''We should get the dough for turning up.''
They were a diferent team after the break and goals seemed inevitable.
Albert Craig headed in the equaliser seven minutes after the break,
although there were spoil-sports who suggested the Icelandic defender,
Holgi Bjorguinsson, had actually made more contact.
Seventeen minutes afterwards, Smith scored the first of his two goals,
a well-struck right-foot shot, and nine minutes from time added the
finishing touch to a neat bit of play by Roddy Grant.
Craig, the captain, reckons the toughest game could be in Metz on
Saturday, but also believes Thistle could win it and virtually be
through to the next stage. It might be best not to argue.
PARTICK THISTLE -- Walker, Dinnie, Pittman, Watson, Welsh, McWilliams,
McDonald, Craig, Grant, Smith, Foster. Substitutes -- Cairns, Milne,
McKee, Docherty, Gibson.
IBK KEFLAVIK -- Gottskalksson, Bjorguinsson, Steinarsson,
Gudbrandsson, Sigurdsson, Finnbogasson, Hauksson, Tanasic, Margeirsson,
Einarsson, Gudmundsson.
</TEXT>
