OCCASIONALLY in the game of golf you get the feeling that somehow it
is going to be your day, writes Scott Crockett. Borderer Graham Davidson
experienced that at Lundin Links yesterday as he triumphed in the East
of Scotland Open.
Five strokes behind the leaders at the halfway stage, a course
record-equalling six-under-par 65 in the third round of the Bank of
Scotland sponsored event put him one stroke off the pace, then a closing
71 ensured victory by a stroke from Graham Lowson and Stuart Meiklejohn.
The mere statistics of the final round, however, do not do justice to
the manner in which they were achieved, particularly the events of the
last five holes.
One over par at the turn, Davidson had seemingly blown his chances
when he drove out of bounds at the 512-yard thirteenh, but amazingly
rescued a par-5 courtesy of an eagle with his second ball, holing a putt
of 35 feet.
As if that was not enough minutes later, at the 314-yard sixteenth, he
chipped in from the adjacent seventeenth tee for an eagle 2, which gave
him the lead.
Lowson failed with the birdie putt from 10 feet at the last which
would have taken the contest into a play-off. Meiklejohn, the 1993
winner, also harboured play-off hopes before three-putting the
eighteenth from 50 feet. Leading aggregates:
