<HEADLINE>They're on the ball at Firhill</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM SHIELDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SPORT, DIARY</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>977584249</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOU have to hand it to Partick Thistle. Asked to put on an important
Intertoto European cup-tie on the unseasonal date, football-wise, of
July 1, the finely-honed Firhill machine was up to the task.
The representative of the parking conglomerate, Urchins plc, was on
hand to ask the usual question: ''Look efter yir motor, mister?'' The
wee wumman form the Sally Ann was out with her collecting tin.
Even the Firhill food franchise people, 007 Catering (''Licensed to
Grill''), were ready for the challenge of summer football with a menu of
strawberries and cream, a brochette of satay chicken on a bed of
endives, and a terrine of summer fruits. Actually, the last bit about
the food is made up.
The 007 people were offering burgers, bovril, tea, coffee, Pepsi and
Tango as usual. Although I am reliably informed that in the executive
dining area, the first course of pea-and-ham soup had been replaced by
prawns with melon.
The chap in front of me was having no truck with Wimbledon-style
menus. He was eating a pie supper. Despite the heatwave he also was
wearing a woolly scarf and bunnet. But many of the Firhill faithful had
embraced the good weather.
One old-timer who had concessions to the hot weather was greeted at
the main door with the words: ''Oh, it's you, Wullie. I didn't recognise
you without your bunnet.'' Another elderly Jags fan went for broke
fashion-wise and turned up for the game against Keflavik with a pair of
Bermuda shorts, a singlet, and straw hat which looked mighty fine,
finished off with black ankle socks, and the Marks and Spencers brogues.
Thistle's many female fans responded to the weather by turning out in
eye-catching summer apparel which made a pleasant change from the shorts
and colourful girls' blouses being worn by the players on the field.
But to get back to Thistle's great European campaign. Firhill fans
have had a slender diet at this level. The Jags got stuffed by Honved in
1972 in the first round of the UEFA Cup.
But those who follow Thistle are undeterred. Participation in the
Intertoto -- or the It's A Knockout Cup or the Cup-losers' Cup, as some
call it -- gives them the chance for European adventures. Some 50 of
them had followed the Jags to Linz in Austria and were proudly showing
their holiday snaps to fellow Thistle fanatics in the Jackie Husband
stand.
More than 400 are set to bus it to France next weekend for le crunch
against Metz. After Saturday's match, grown men, having seen the notice
in the Jackie Husband lounge at the Woodside Bar advertising a #49
return trip, were busily constructing scenarios which might convince Her
Indoors of the need to see Thistle through these important times.
About 3800 fans were treated to a game of dubious quality. Misplaced
passes and many embarrassing attempts at ball control, but what do you
expect when you ask Partick Thistle to play on a pitch which isn't
waterlogged?
Given the heat, it was understandable that the fans, smothered in
factor 20 suntan lotion, were in lethargic mood. One diehard tried in
vain three times to get some community singing going with ''We love you
Thistle, we do . . . '' He eventually settled for a solo ''I love you
Thistle, I do . . . ''
Thistle, after having gone behind to a team they should have
mollicated in the first 10 minutes, then scored three beautiful goals
and the smiles on the Firhill faithful were beatific.
But, as ever, there is no point in being a football fan if you can't
have a good moan about the board of directors. Chairman Jim Oliver and
his colleagues appear to be giving their supporters a lot to moan about.
Fifteen players, including last year's player of the year, Ian Cameron,
are out of contract and have been offered Oliver Twist-style wages.
The Thistle fanzine, Sick in the Basin (a reference to the proximity
of the canal to Firhill), asks where Partick Thistle's money from
healthy gate receipts is going. Certainly not into players' wages or
into big-money buys.
The fanzine vendor made interesting allegations about the chairman.
The laws of libel prevent me from giving details.
Sick in the Basin also suggest that George Galloway, Labour MP for
Hillhead, was involved in a group interested in buying Partick Thistle.
This seems unlikely, given Gorgeous George's affiliation to Dundee
United and the fact that Thistle aren't even in his constituency.
It's going to be a long, hot summer, we hope, at Firhill.
</TEXT>
