<HEADLINE>A song, a dance and a nice wee hurl</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JACK MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584252</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CAMOGIE is girls' hurling. It is the first time it has been played in
Scotland because hurling is much the same game as shinty and, until
recently, girls didn't play any sport at all, let alone shinty and
hurling.
But Irish girls did, because the Gaelic Athletic Association goes in
for dance and sport. Dance is important, for since the remarkable
achievements of River Dance at the European Song Contest, Irish dancing
is much to the fore. In truth, Irish dancing has been splendid for years
and, all credit to this newspaper, we have been writing about it for
some years, too.
But the purpose of the GAA has been to bring back -- a bit like the
Gaelic language, really -- Gaelic arts and sports. One of them was
camogie -- hurling for girls, and grand it was.
Truthfully, some of the girls were not girls and some of them were.
One was called Colette and was in her thirties. She was playing for the
Toryglen, Glasgow-based Tir Connail Harps, replendent in green skirt and
gold-and-green top. So was the smallest girl on the park, who was eight.
There are 25 girls playing camogie in South-side Glasgow, most of them
of Irish origin, some of them even Irish. Yesterday, there were Irish
girls playing against the Harps, too. Two of them and both representing
Lochgilphead. This takes a bit of explaining. Shinty has for many years,
like many other male sports, eschewed females in their games, but things
have changed. Shinty now permits women and girls to take part in what
is, after all, a splendid sport. This is a recent development, as Jean
and Rosie and Lesley told me.
All three played shinty. Rosie, from Edinburgh, a textile designer,
told me more. ''We got into this from shinty: just liked playing sport.
Speak to wee Stevie Coyle. Here's her cousin Katie: she's only nine.''
The sudden realisation that girls don't have the same age differention
as boys possess was a bit of a shock. Not really, for I have seen this
before. Yesterday was a celebration, a bit, of Scotto-Irishism for there
were displays of Irish dancing and Irish consciousness. Actually not
much dancing, really, because the rain would have ruined the dresses
which are elaborate and incredibly expensive. But the wee girls and boys
danced for me all the same to the tune of an Irish band giving Rose of
Mooncoin fair laldy.
A lot of the children were from Holyrood Secondary, a nearby school.
Nearby? It is the biggest secondary school in Scotland, and in common
with many another educational establishment, it doesn't have enough
sport for the children. But there is most certainly not enough sport for
girls.
Despite the fact that camogie exists for girls -- the stick is for
young people, especially girls, and is different from the caman in being
narrower and rather more like a hockey stick -- despite the rules which
are designed for girls and young boys, despite all that, camogie has
very little opportunities for Irish girls.
There is no girls' shinty in Scotland, and no girls' hurling. Celts
seem to be similar to every other culture in that the men decide to stop
women from playing anything at all other than a hapless harlotry. This
is perhaps not fair.
Because, as in many sports, it is men who are helping out. The coach
for Tir Connail is none other than Jim McCurdie, a legendary figure in
Gaelic athleticism. Let me tell you about this Association. It started
up trying to recreate the world of Irish Gaeltacht. I mentioned Irish
dancing and rightly so, for Highland Dancing has but disappeared for
boys. Outside of a few spots in the Western Isles, shinty has gone.
Irish dancing is back and the boys are back taking steps. Thank God.
Yesterday at Cathkin Park, where the Third Lanark once were back in
the days of Jimmy Mason, with me standing once again on the terraces of
this hallowed ground, I watched what is, after all, everything which
sport is all about.
There was a 37-year-old girl playing out there, and a wee
eight-year-old called Anne Marie Collins. There was Katie, aged nine,
whose cousin was playing. There was Marie, who I daftly asked, after
interviewing her and getting all the information, what she did for as
living. She has five children. She looks after weans for a living and
quite right, too.
The rain came on, which was upsetting considering what the weather in
Scotland has been like for the past month. Tir Connail won, by three
goals to two goals and a point, against the team which had come all the
way from Lochgilphead, and the Highland girls with two Irish girls in it
as well.
Later on at night I dined with the girls. I even sang. I sang a song
from Philomena Begley's repertoire, ''She's just her mummy and daddy's
little girl.'' I sang it to a wee lassie called Collette Greene, who is
from Ireland. She telt me not be so sentimental and bought me a drink.
It was a good day.
</TEXT>
