<HEADLINE>Ginola setting a high price</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>977584253</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CELTIC'S hopes of persuading Paris St Germain star David Ginoli to
come to Scotland rose and sank almost at the same time yesterday.
It became clear that the main rivals for the French winger's
signature, Barcelona, have abandoned their plans to buy the
internationalist, thus leaving the way clear for the Parkhead club to
lead the race.
However, sources on the Continent indicate that the reason Barcelona
manager Johan Cruyff decided to step back was because of the wage
demands of the St Germain player.
Ginoli asked for a basic salary of #1.2m a year and a three-year
contract to go with it, demands which proved too much even for Cruyff to
tolerate.
The French winger, who made a huge impression in the Champions' Cup
quarter-final against the Spaniards last season, has fallen out with his
French club to the extent that they have told him he can move on if he
wishes.
Now the prospects of any club, other than in the Italian Serie A
league, meeting his demands seem remote.
That also would seem to be the word to describe Everton's chances of
persuading Rangers to part with their international keeper, Andy Goram.
The Merseyside team's manager, Joe Royle, is said to be anxious to get
Goram as a replacement for Neville Southall, the 36-year-old Welsh
international keeper whose testimonial game will be against Celtic in
August.
Royle has a long association with Goram over seven years at Oldham
before he went to Hibs for #200,000. He joined Rangers for #1m soon
after Walter Smith took over in 1991 and went on to become Scotland's
No.1 goalkeeper.
Although he was put on the transfer list last summer because Smith
felt Goram had not applied himself to recapturing fitness after a series
of knee operations, he has since won his way back to favour.
The keeper missed the second half of last season because of further
injuries but is fully fit again and will be a keen member of the Ibrox
side for their bid to get into the Champions League again this season.
Smith knows that Goram, as a Scot, is one guaranteed quality player for
the European competition and that is a major reason for keeping him in
his place.
* JOCK McStay, will sign for East Fife in a bid to rebuild his career.
The 29-year-old defender, at the centre of the Duncan Ferguson
head-butting incident, was freed by Clydebank last season.
And now McStay is hoping to put the trauma of the past year behind him
with a move to the second division outfit.
Manager Steve Archibald said: ''Preliminary negotiations have gone
well and I'm hopeful we can complete the deal.''
''McStay is a good, versatile player and I would be delighted to bring
him to Methil.''
* CELTIC will be forced to play in the European Cup-winners' Cup
preliminary round because of a Yugoslav second division side.
Modest Obilic lost 4-0 to League champions Red Star Belgrade in the
Yugoslav Cup final. But because Yugoslavia are rated higher than
Scotland, UEFA will rank Modest in fifteenth place, one above Celtic.
And only the top 15 will be seeded and have the luxury of avoiding the
preliminary round.
There are 49 entrants to the tournament, including holders Real
Zaragoza, and that number must be slashed to 32 for the first round
proper.
Celtic would have received the final seeded place had UEFA not taken a
late decision to welcome back teams from war-ravaged Yugoslavia.
Celtic will find out who they face in the preliminary round when the
draw is made on July 12.
</TEXT>
