<HEADLINE>City takes backseat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS,R E DUNDAS, CHIEF FINANCIAL EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584254</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FINANCIAL markets are likely to remain subdued this week as the battle
for the Conservative leadership continues.
Their initial hope for a resounding first ballot win for John Major
has disappeared and uncertainty will prevail until the issue is
resolved.
The FTSE-100 index did rally on Thursday and Friday last week but at
3314 it is still nearly 100 points down on its level before Mr Major
made his dramatic stand.
Business has been thin, with fund managers sitting on their hands and
the index could easily slide again this week, though many analysts
believe buyers would come in at the 3250 level.
Perhaps the worst outcome would be for Mr Major to win the battle on
the first ballot but not have enough votes to have won the war. This
would merely extend the uncertainty in the market's view, leaving the
basic split in the party festering whatever gloss the Major camp put on
the result.
A Major withdrawal and a second round possibly involving Michael
Portillo and Michael Heseltine would mean another week of uncertainty
without even the assurance the leadership issue would be resolved even
then. The market abhors a vacuum and tends to drift lower in such
conditions.
Sterling and gilts will be fearful that a chastened Mr Major or a new
leader would not be able to resist a loosening of monetary restraint in
a desperate attempt to win favour with the electorate.
There is also the worry that the Government would be forced into an
election before 1997 which it would almost certainly lose resulting in a
new and inexperienced Labour administration full of plans for the
economy, forcing interest rates higher.
THE Chancellor of the Exchequer meets the Governor of the Bank of
England on Wednesday morning in the immediate aftermath of the
first-round vote for the leadership of the Conservative Party, writes R
E DUNDAS, Chief Financial Editor.
Kenneth Clarke will stick to his view that the evidence of a slowdown
in the pace of economic activity has justified his decision to reject
calls from the Governor of the Bank of England for a rise in interest
rates.
Sterling remains weak, but it is difficult to see what additional
information Eddie George could muster to persuade the Chancellor that he
was wrong and should agree to a rise in rates.
Across the Atlantic the Federal Open Market Committee meets on
Wednesday and Thursday, but strong house sales figures last week are
thought to have dashed hopes that the US central bank would cut American
rates.
The week is light on official statistics. The narrow measure of the
money supply, due today, has followed an erratic path in recent months
because of the volatility of bankers' balances.
A bounceback in these last month is forecast by James Capel's Adam
Cole to give a 0.7% rise in M0, mainly notes and coins in circulation,
for a same-again year-on-year growth rate of 5.9%.
Also due today are the figures for new credit, expected to show a
recovery from April's #498m to #550m in May. Credit card lending is
known to have been stronger, and retail sales rose.
With the pound in the toils last month the reserves, due tomorrow, may
have fallen by an underlying $50m.
</TEXT>
