<HEADLINE>Setting standards</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH BRUCE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584255</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paul Motian's Broadway Music band knows jazz and what can be achieved
with its trendy reinterpretation of tunes. Keith Bruce reports on the
quintet which is full of surprises
THE oft-repeated adage that the path to building a jazz vocabulary is
to learn to play the standards, is somewhat out of fashion these days.
Musical boundaries are crumbling and many players are suspicious of the
use of the word jazz at all, never mind a retread of Body and Soul. On
the other hand, since 1988 Paul Motian's Broadway Music has been giving
the lie to such trendy disregard for the tunes that have been the
foundation of jazz.
Motian has appeared in Glasgow before -- on the same day in 1992 -- in
his superb trio with guitarist Bill Frisell and saxophonist Joe Lovano.
A quartet, with the addition of Charlie Haden on bass, recorded the
first two On Broadway albums at the end of the eighties. They have
recently been joined by volume three, which sees the band further
expanded with Lee Konitz on alto sax. Marc Johnson, another regular
Motian sideman, is on bass for the Glasgow concert, which kicks off a
European tour.
For those used to standard treatment of standard tunes, Broadway
Music's approach will seem oblique, and that can be put down as much to
the company Motian keeps as to his own distinctive style of drumming.
With his own band Frisell has been reinventing the idea of the standard
by covering songs like Madonna's Live To Tell, but there is no doubting
each Broadway Music player's familiarity with the standard repertoire --
a knowledge of the song has to be there before it can be taken into new
territory.
''I love those tunes and it is music closely associated with the
people I've played with. But I learned some of them because there were
lots of times in New York when times were hard and I couldn't do the
things I wanted to do. I played weddings, floorshows, and bar mitzvahs.
I even played with Cab Calloway one time -- it was a gig,'' says Motian.
The addition of Konitz, a player of Motian's vintage rather than
Lovano and Frisell's, might seem almost safe in the context of the
band's unconventional approach, but Motian bridles at the gentle
suggestion that the altoist is less aggressive than the ferocious
Lovano.
''I'm not sure about that. He's a jazz legend. I've known Lee for many
years and worked with him in New York in the fifties. He fits well with
Joe -- it's two different sounds but they sound great together. It is
more frosting on the cake.''
The recipe is not consistently that straightforward, however. This
quintet concert is not what it seems. ''There's not always five of us on
stage at the one time,'' the drummer explains.
Motian promises some trio music and the enticing prospect of an alto
and tenor duo of the two saxophonists. ''Just keep your ears open and
enjoy it,'' is the band-leader's advice.
Motian always has a number of projects on the go at one time, using
different musicians to play different music and touring with different
bands at different times of the year.
His most recent release in the US is by his Electric Be-Bop Band, an
outfit that includes bassist Steve Swallow, two saxophones and two
guitars, and ploughs through another repertoire: the classic jazz
compositions of the bop era, including Ornithology, Two Bass Hit, and
Round Midnight.
That band is set to tour Europe in November. It is to be hoped that
Scottish promoters who operate outside of festival time take note.
</TEXT>
