<HEADLINE>High peaks, big wheels</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER PORTWAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>HOLIDAY 95</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>977584256</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONNECTED by the great motorway arteries of the M1 and A1 as they
stride northward from London, the Shires of Middle England are too often
neglected by visitors drawn by the better promoted pleasures of
Britain's more touristy destinations. However, those who bypass this
region -- less poetically labelled the Midlands -- are missing much.
One of the shires that form this extensive territory is that of
Derbyshire headed by its traditional county town of Derby. Let it be
said that Derby is no showplace of the likes of Chester or York but
nevertheless has become a most attractive and well laid-out city that is
a pleasure to explore.
Its heritage embraces many famous names including Rolls Royce and
Royal Crown Derby, all proudly reflected in Derby's beautifully devised
free-entry museums. Its Eagle, Audley and Main covered shopping centres
and pedestrianised St Peters Street, St James and Irongate shopping
areas together with the magnificent Market Hall, blend comfortably with
ancient buildings and half-hidden corners of historic allure.
Kedleston Hall stands 4[1/2] miles north-east of the city and remains
a masterpiece of sumptuous style as does Calke Abbey to the south, home
of the Harpur-Crewe family and a jumbled treasure trove of furniture,
pictures, cartoons, books and maps, stuffed birds and animals, minerals,
shells and everything under the sun. Nearby is yet another great house;
the lived-in (by Lord and Lady Kerr) Melbourne Hall, one-time residence
of Lord Melbourne, Queen Victoria's first and much-loved Prime Minister
who gave his name to the Australian city.
Touring anywhere in Derbyshire is a joy, the villages of thatched and
picturesque cottages are well-endowed with mouth-watering pubs that make
perfect sources of home-cooked meals. Repton has its celebrated public
school, Cromford its Arkwright Mill, historic canal and High Peak
railway, Crich its Tramway Museum, Ripley the Midland Railway Centre,
and Lea is home to a striking collection of rare rhododendrons, azaleas,
alpines and conifers.
Should theme parks be to your taste then Derby can oblige. Within the
city's boundary can be found the American Adventure while the reservoir
of Carsington Water hosts a variety of activities of a more nautical
flavour. But the Disneyland of Britain, the redoubtable Alton Towers,
offers a thrill a minute if you go in for that sort of thing.
From high peak to the big wheel, Derby heads a county that has
everything at the heart of the under-appreciated, even spurned, shires
of Middle England.
Further details available from the Derby Tourist Information Centre,
Assembly Rooms, Market Place, Derby DE1 3AH.
</TEXT>
