<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sad Boardman shattered after a two-minute Tour</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584257</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOUR DE FRANCE
CHRIS Boardman was back in Britain last night for an operation on
three broken bones after having crashed out of the Tour de France on
Saturday, less than two minutes after the start of the three-week race.
Boardman, dreaming of a second prologue victory in the event, fell
heavily on a left-hand bend as he took risks on a rain-soaked 4.5-mile
circuit in the Breton port of St Brieuc.
The 26-year-old star from Hoylake, Wirral, underwent an operation at a
Birkenhead hospital last night after having been flown back from
Britanny.
Boardman, who is expected to be out for up to two months, said: ''I
have to think of the future now.'' He sustained a double fracture of his
left ankle and a broken right arm and said yesterday: ''The conditions
were extreme and dangerous.
''I really wanted to win the first stage. I was just pushing a little
bit too hard. It was a wet bend at 80kmh. I just lost the back wheel and
went spinning along the ground. I hit the barriers and then,
unfortunately, the team car hit me as well, because it couldn't quite
stop in time.''
The brave Briton, who won the prologue last year at an average speed
which was a record for any stage in Tour history, got back on his bike
and tried to carry on, but the pain was too severe and he was carried
away to his team car.
Boardman's accident was provoked by a rainstorm which turned the
traditional prologue time-trial start to the Tour into a mockery.
Almost half of the 189 riders in the field rode in perfect sunny
conditions, but the breaking storm left all the favourites, who started
later, with no chance of competitive performances.
Boardman's pain was Jacky Durand's gain. The Frenchman, one of the
early starters, won the prologue against all his own expectations to
wear the race leader's yellow jersey for the first time in his long
career.
Durand, a former Tour of Flanders winner, completed the course in
exactly nine minutes -- two seconds ahead of compatriot Thierry Laurent
and three faster than a third French rider, Francis Moreau. All rode
before the rain fell.
Spain's Miguel Indurain, last year's winner, took no chances on the
slippery course and came in 30 seconds behind Durand, and just five
slower than his expected main rival for overall victory, Tony Rominger
of Switzerland.
The irony of Boardman's accident was that the race had been put back
to the evening for the first time in 27 years so that his likely
prologue win could be seen live on prime-time television in Britain.
The first stage of the Tour took place in western France yesterday
from Dinan to Lannion, with Italian Fabio Baldato winning a mass sprint
finish, although Durand retained the race leader's yellow jersey.
Baldato, competing in his first Tour de France, outsprinted two
familiar figures in such finishes -- France's Laurent Jalabert and
Djamolidine Abdoujaparov of Uzbekistan -- at the end of the 146-mile
stage. Placings:
Stage: 1, Fabio Baldato (Italy) MG Technogym 5hr 49min 18sec; 2,
Laurent Jalabert (France) ONCE; 3, Djamolidine Abdoujaparov (Uzbekistan)
Novell, same time as winner. Others included: 6, Tony Rominger
(Switzerland) Mapei GB;  12, Miguel Indurain (Spain) Banesto; 26, Max
Sciandri MG Technogym all same time;  69, Sean Yates Motorola 24 seconds
behind.
Overall: 1, Jacky Durand (France) Castorama 5-58-18; 2, Brochard two
seconds behind;  3, Thierry Laurent (France) Castorama same time; 19,
Rominger  26 seconds behind; 50, Sciandri 52sec; 88, Yates  1-13.
</TEXT>
