<DOCID>GH950703-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Worry over business failures</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584259</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FURTHER signs that growth in the economy is slowing comes from two
surveys published today showing that the decline in the rate of business
failures is becoming less marked, writes CHRISTOPHER SIMS.
Year-on-year figures from Trade Indemnity show that business failures
notified to the credit insurance company were down 9% in the second
quarter, against a 19% fall in the opening quarter of the year.
It represents the sixth quarter that the rate of decline has slowed.
Failures in the second quarter, according the business information
group Dun &amp; Bradstreet, actually increased by 11% compared with the
first quarter to 11,033.
In comparison with last year the long-term trend is still down, with
first-half failures 10.6% lower.
Scotland remains the part of Britain most affected by business
failures, though this partly reflects changes in the bankrupty laws
which caused a small fall in 1994. Failures were 35% higher at 2060.
William Simpson, chief economist at Trade Indemnity, commented: ''The
pace of improvement in the economy has clearly slowed during 1995.
''We have identified three reasons for this slowdown -- manufacturers'
profits are coming under pressure from higher raw material and import
costs that are not being accommodated by similar rates of monetary
growth; weakness at the retail level is coming back to manufactuers in
reduced orders and, thirdly European and American retail sluggishness
will also intensify international competition.''
Dun &amp; Bradstreet says the London area has seen an increase of 22% in
failures in the first half of the year.
Senior analyst Philip Mellor commented: ''The increase in company
liquidations, particularly in London, is worrying because this seems to
be part of an accelerating process which started at the beginning of the
year . . . as yet smaller businesses have not been affected.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stephane Grappelli, Theatre Royal, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER MAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584260</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AT the formidable age of 87, French violinist Stephane Grappelli could
reasonably be expected to have slowed down a little. The jazz life is
not normally conducive to health and longevity. But Grappelli remains in
every sense formidable, the twinkle in his eye and the acid jazz
iridescence of his shirt and waistcoat underlining the fact that his
style, his technique and his joie de vivre remain gloriously intact.
Grappelli's music has changed little since his partnership with Django
Reinhardt in the Quintette du Hot Club de France in the 1930s, when the
duo forged the first wholly convincing European jazz perspective -- a
fleet-fingered, blissful confection of carbaret chanson and Broadway
show tunes, where thematic embellishment was more important than
extended harmonic improvisation.
Accompanied with great verve and sensitivity by Marc Fosset on guitar
(more Charlie Christian and Wes Montgomery than Reinhardt) and Jean
Philippe Viret on double bass, Grappelli took his delighted audience
through a 90-minute reprise of his back catalogue, the great hits of
Gershwin and Porter sounding as fresh as if they were written yesterday.
For the final 15 minutes, the trio were joined by the superb
Reinhardt-like Belgian guitarist Fapy Lapertin, coincidentally and
fortuitously in the city, kicking off with the old Hot Club favourite
Sweet Georgia Brown.
Even with the full complement of fingers and thumbs, Lapertin is not
quite in the same league as the digitally-challenged Reinhardt, but when
you closed your eyes you were back in Montaparnasse 60 years ago,
sipping absinthe and rapping with Cocteau. A magical evening.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fapy Lafertin et le Jazz, Tron Theatre, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON KERR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584261</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OK, it's early days yet, but it could well be that one of the
highlights of this year's jazz festival is actually a folk festival gig.
In the adman's vogue for things Reinhardt, Lafertin stands out as a
phenomenal exponent of the great guitarist's style: forget your Renault
Clios, this was music for Mercs. His playing, although apparently
effortless, was dazzling and passionate -- and no mere impersonation.
Equally impressive was Steve Ellsworth, whose fiddle solos were -- as
Stephane Grappelli's were to Reinhardt -- the perfect complement. His
playing on Minor Swing was red-hot and by Viper's Dream (two tunes
later), the strings must have been sizzling.
The programme dipped in and out of the Hot Club repertoire, but all
the numbers were characterised by that band's cheery twenties Gallic
charm: from Walter Donaldson's zithery and instantly smile-inducing I've
Had My Moments, via a spicy Mexican tune and the lovely lament Vous Qui
Me Passez Sans Me Voir through to the encore medley which should have
been titled The Sheik of Araby Meets The Third Man.
But the real five-star stand-outs were the lightning-fast version of I
Wonder Where My Baby Is Tonight and Putting On the Ritz; and the
sumptuous serenade, Melody at Crepuscule. One of the numbers almost
summed the night up: C'est Si Bon. More like merveilleux, I'd say.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Economists issue rate warning</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584262</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE economy is heading for a ''soft landing'' -- steady, sustainable
growth with low inflation -- but interest rates need to rise again, a
leading group of economists say in a report today.
After growing rapidly last year, the economy will expand more slowly
in 1995 and 1996 with gross domestic product expected to increase by 3%
and 2.4% respectively, according to the Ernst &amp; Young ITEM Club's latest
forecast, based on the Treasury's computer model of the economy.
Meanwhile, the Government's benchmark measure of inflation, excluding
mortgage interest payments, should remain in its 1%-4% target range. But
there is a significant risk that rising costs in industry could filter
through to retail prices despite the sluggishness of consumer spending,
said the ITEM Club.
''In order to address this risk ITEM feels it would be prudent to
increase interest rates to 7.25% (from 6.75%) by the autumn.
''While this should not place too large a cost in terms of output, it
could help avert the need for larger increases at a later date should
inflation begin to accelerate excessively,'' according to the forecast.
ITEM said it is increasingly evident that the Government intends to
cut taxes in November's budget to win votes in the next general
election, assumed to take place in the autumn of 1996.
But it warns that, although politically expedient, tax cuts may not be
''financially prudent''. ''We do not expect the Government to be able to
meet its ambitious spending plans over the lead-up to a general election
which will leave the public sector borrowing requirement standing at
#4000m higher than the forecast by the Treasury in its latest summer
forecast,'' said ITEM's chief economist Paul Droop.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tarango affair plumbs the depths of French farce</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SPORT, WIMBEDON 95</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584263</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONTROVERSIAL American tennis player Jeff Tarango, who stormed out of
a Wimbledon match in a blaze of anger and accusations on Saturday,
yesterday met tournament referee Alan Mills for an hour.
But details of the fine to be imposed -- probably a five figure sum --
were not being announced until later, according to a Wimbledon
spokeswoman, who added that a decision on the amount was being made by
officials at the All-England Club last night.
''I will stay here until justice is done,'' vowed Tarango as he
returned to his London hotel. ''I don't regret what happened.''
It is understood there may have been difficulty in reaching all the
officials and individuals involved in the Court 13 rumpus.
But Tarango may have a strong argument against heavy disciplinary
action. Bruno Rebeuh awarded a code violation for an audible obscenity
against him when Californian Tarango merely responded to crowd taunts by
yelling ''shut up.'' Tarango will have argued that by no stretch of the
imagination can ''shut up'' be regarded as an obscenity.
Tarango walked out of his match against Alexander Mronz -- at 7-6, 2-1
to the German, who faces Andre Agassi on Centre Court today -- and
accused French umpire Rebeuh of corruption and favouritism. When he was
denied recourse to the supervisor, he told Rebeuh: ''You are the most
corrupt official in the game.''
The umpire has been given the go-ahead to continue, but Tarango has
been banished along with his French wife, Benedicte, after a weekend
which surrendered the Championships to farce.
The 26-year-old player went to the meeting with Mr Mills with his
wife, who added injury to insult in unprecedented scenes at the club by
slapping the official in the face.
The nonsense reached another height yesterday when the Manchild
himself, John McEnroe, criticised Tarango's outburst. ''I just can't
believe he did that,'' said McEnroe, who was the bane of umpires.
McEnroe, who is commentating at the Championships for American
television network NBC, added: ''He has shot himself in the foot. I
never walked off court, I never wanted to be defaulted.''
Tarango snapped Wimbledon to attention after a first week of serve and
volley boredom. Then, when his wife stood up for her man and slapped
umpire Rebeuh, who the couple felt had been unfair, madness had arrived
back at sleepy hollow.
Mrs Tarango said yesterday she had no regrets over her actions and she
was fully supporting her husband. I don't regret anything. I am a little
hot-blooded but that is my Latin temperament.''
Tarango will be fined heavily and a ban on his participation in other
tournaments will also be imposed. Mrs Tarango can't be penalised
financially, but she can be be banned from courtside in future.
''I must admit I have said 'shut up' to the crowd before and not been
given a warning,'' McEroe added. ''I didn't think saying shut up was
profane.
''I have to say, though, I did find it funny the way his wife stood up
to the umpire. I thought that was a remarkable scene.''
Funny or not, there may also be legal implications and repercussions
for Tarango who alleged the umpire awarded matches out of friendship to
players and futher alleged that the Swiss player, Marc Rosset, seeded
10, was one who benefited in this manner.
Both umpire and Rosset, beaten first time out by Michael Joyce, could
consider having their names cleared in court. However, Tarango claims he
can substantate his claims if necessary.
Mr Rebeuh said last night that he would not be making any comment
about the scandal or whether he would be taking legal action until after
the end of the championships. He said: ''I am not going to say anything
until after my last day at Wimbledon. I just want to finish the
tournament and then after that I may be able to say something.''
The great British hope, Greg Rusedeski, is on the main court with the
defending champion, Pete Sampras, and the most remarkable thing about
the Canuck, apart from his peculiar desire to be British, is that he is
being given a chance.
Canadian-born Rusedski, who now considers himself as British as fish
and chips, said: ''The public have been brilliant. They have been full
of encouragement. I feel a great warmth from them.
''They have accepted me and consider me British.''
No less an authority than former Wimbledon champion Stan Smith, who
beat Nastase in a thrilling five-set final 23 years ago, believes the
big guy is a threat. ''Anyone who serves with his power has to have a
chance at Wimbledon, where left-handers always seem to do well,'' he
said.
Boris Becker rumbles on, but not with the old panache, and he wll have
to be extremely wary out on Court 2, the graveyard of the seeds, when he
plays against that long strip of nonsense with a huge serve, 6ft 8in
Dick Norman, who has already seen off two former champions, Pat Cash and
Stefan Edberg. Becker does not want to become third victim of the
unknown Belgian.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mackintosh tops bill</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584264</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WEST End impresario Cameron Mackintosh and publisher John Madejski top
the pay league for directors of growing private companies with around
#4m each, according to a book published today.
Profits at Mr Mackintosh's theatrical production company nearly
doubled to more than #14m in the last trading year, enabling him and two
fellow directors to share #11.3m.
Mr Madejski's Hurst Publishing, which publishes Auto Trader, also
virtually doubled profits to just below #10m. He shared a payout of
#7.8m with another director.
The figures come from the 10th edition of the Brown Shipley Growth
Companies Register, which tracks the 2000 fastest-growing private
companies.
''The overall trading performance of the top 2000 companies shows
spectacular improvements over the previous year as this important
section of British industry has moved strongly out of recession,'' said
publisher Roy Assersohn.
''Nearly 1000 companies doubled their profits, compared with only 500
in the previous edition in 1994.''
* The Brown Shipley Growth Companies Register is published by
Financial Publishing, 4 Middle Street, London EC1A 7JA.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Annie Whitehead Experience, The City Cafe Bar</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH MOORE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584265</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS the sun went down on Friday night, the summer feeling continued in
the City Cafe Bar as the Annie Whitehead Experience took to the stage
with their own brand of jazz.
Kicking off with The Culprit, a moody piece with an early sixties
filmic feel to it, the band quickly established its cross-genre
dexterity.
Hello Max, written with Harry Becket, was reggae influenced in a
friendly sunsplash-kinda-way, affording Whitehead the opportunity to
display some roaring trombone lines.
Three songs in, Whitehead announced the end of the first set,
promising a much longer second. But during the interval, she appeared on
stage asking if anyone had a trombone. It seemed a tall order, but this
is a jazz festival after all, and the Berklee bound Scottish player
Nichol Thomson gallantly nipped home and got his.
The Experience sound owes much to Whitehead's love of world music and
as a band, the players really excelled on a blues inflected piece,
with some neat playing by Jasper Von t'Hof on keyboards and slap bass
from Dudley Philips. His walking lines combined with Maidman's strolling
blues riffs, creating a wholly satisfying interplay while the vociferous
Genockey ensured they kept up with his own searing pace.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Joe Locke, McEwans Old Fruitmarket, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH MOORE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584266</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AFTER years as a Jazzfest favourite on the pub circuit, Saturday night
saw Joe Locke graduate to (in his own words) the big room. The
flamboyant vibraphonist admitted to being nervous, although this may
have had more to do with the suit he was wearing than the size of the
venue. It was one of the most sartorially-challenged outfits I've seen
since 1986. Happily, his taste in attire was not reflected in his
musical offerings.
Featured guest for the night was saxophonist Tommy Smith. It
transpires that the pair have been spending a bit of time together, and
the empathy that has grown between them, resulted in an inspired
improvisational playfulness. Smith was in fine form, creating sheets of
sound and playing with a warm lyricism, best heard on his own haunting
composition Memorial, based on the poem by Norman McCaig. Surely one of
the saddest tunes ever written.
Elsewhere, particularly on Andrew Hill's Tripping, we heard some
terrific ensemble playing; Alex Dankworth on bass, and the particularly
impressive New Yorker Joe Caldorazzo (sitting in for Cindy Blackman on
drums) who kept the quartet pieces moving along at a furious pace. Solo,
Locke embraced technology, creating haunting, impressionistic
soundscapes from mystical keyboard and percussion sound effects.
The encore saw Smith and Locke take to the stage for a duo piece; a
futuristic sci-fi soundtrack fantasy which would not have been out of
place in Blade Runner.
The gig, however, remained strangely unengaging, which was
disappointing, given Locke's legendary ability to charm audiences.
Perhaps he was genuinely nervous in finding himself promoted to the big
room.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Julain Arguelles, City Cafe Bar, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH BRUCE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584267</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PLAYERS like saxist Julian Arguelles make you long for a time when a
definable jazz ''scene'', in which talents like his -- at home in any
company and extraordinary in most -- would be properly appreciated. His
current quartet -- the live incarnation has brother Steve on drums and
bassist Steve Watts -- teams him with guitarist Mike Walker, who has
played in recent years with Tommy Smith and the George Russell
Orchestra, and they are an amazing partnership.
The duo's unison playing in 500 Broadway -- a tune named for the
address of the saxist's New York digs -- defined the evening, even if it
was often Walker who won the real acclaim of the punters for his
explosive soloing and wide range of expression. If that tune was
Arguelles' impressionistic response to the Big Apple, the first set
closer, Which Way Out, was pure NYC funk and a showcase for the
artist-formerly-known-as side of Walker's musical personality.
The saxophonist's writing style is impossible to define. Third
Escapade owed a debt to Mike Gibbs, while Hix -- featuring the leader on
soprano sax -- dallied in Ornette Coleman territory. A Month in Tunisia
(characteristically introduced by Arguelles in a way that made sure the
joke was not wasted) contained only the merest nod towards its titual
be-bop inspiration, and rather more of the African influence that is
detectable in much of his composition. On another piece he played two
flutes while Walker demonstrated that highlife guitar was also part of
his repertoire.
It all suited the sun-baked party atmosphere of the festival's opening
weekend -- so what did the quartet encore with? In the Bleak Midwinter.
No, really. And superbly arranged and movingly played it was.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Retailers hold spending clues</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584268</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GUIDE as to whether or not there has been any upturn in consumer
confidence and with it retail spending will come this week from results
from three leading retailers.
Today, John Menzies reports its annual results. Bell Lawrie White is
expecting these to show a small increase in taxable profit from #34.4m
to around #38.2m.
The High Street retail business is forecast to make a small profit of
perhaps #1m compared with a loss in 1993-94, still an inadequate return
on sales and capital. Flat operating profits are expected from the Early
Learning Centre business which is being steadily rolled out in a
superstore format.
MFI is also reporting annual profits today with the City forecasting a
drop from #87.8m to #65m. The group has found it difficult to pass on
higher raw material prices to its customers in the difficult retail
environment.
There is expected to be a more upbeat trading statement from brewer
Scottish &amp; Newcastle. NatWest Securities is forecasting profits up from
#222m to #265m, helped by the Chef &amp; Brewer pubs acquisition.
Investors will be interested to hear of the company's plans for the
integration of Courage, recently acquired from Foster's. A decision by
the OFT is expected next month on whether the deal, making S&amp;N's
Britain's largest brewer, will be referred to the MMC.
There are no major companies reporting results tomorrow, but on
Wednesday, Dixons is expected to show the benefit of a margin recovery.
Goldman Sachs expects a 31% increase in profits to #96m. Last year's
results were hit by exceptional charges which led to a pre-tax loss of
#165m.
The shares have enjoyed a strong run in recent times with many in the
City taking the view that the fundamentals of the business have improved
dramatically.
Over the last six months, the resolution of the OFT investigation into
extended warranties, the withdrawal of a number of major players, the
weak performance of rival Comet, the number two in the market, and the
growth in demand for home computers have all improved the trading
picture.
On the same day, flushed with success from the #800m acquisition of
Trident submarine manufacturer VSEL, GEC reports its finals. Rising
research and development costs on the Eurofighter 2000 and the Boeing
777 are thought to have depressed second-half profitability.
However, Natwest Securities is forecasting a #68m rise in profits to
#934m. There may be some exceptional charges for rationalisation and
problem contracts. The City will also be looking for any hint of a bid
for British Aerospace.
Thursday is a quiet day for results announcements but on Friday
attention will centre on Britain's biggest jeweller, Signet Group,
formerly Ratners. The group has forecast that that it will make pre-tax
profits of around #8m, up from #1.7m before provisions on losses from
disposals in 1993-94.
Signet is battling to rebuild profits after the recession and
over-expansion. However, it is saddled with #360m of debt and has #130m
of arrears on its Preference dividends.
There is also speculation that the catalogue showroom retailer Argos,
which has about 8% of the UK jewellery market, may want to buy Signet's
UK's businesses which trade under the Hill Samuel and Ernest Jones brand
names.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Last Night of the Proms, Royal Concert Hall, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584269</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WELL, they were there in their thousands on Saturday night for the
Royal SNO's Last Night of the Proms, balloons at the ready,
party-poppers loaded, the auditorium full, the arena packed like a
sardine can. But it took a Sousa march and a pair of polka-dot boxer
shorts in the second half to get the crowd roaring and jumping.
Not that it was the orchestra's fault that it took so long. They were
demob happy and primed for anarchy from the outset, as conductor Owain
Arwel Hughes -- sporting a recent injury -- hobbled onstage on crutches
to a chorus of Long John Silver impersonations from the band.
''It's all English music,'' said one patron in an explanation of the
sedate behaviour of the mob through first-half performances of music by
Arnold, Vaughan Williams, and Walton. And even though the
Whistlebinkies, in a guest spot with some very fine Celtic music, got
the feet tapping, their sound had neither its proper size nor immediacy
in the giant auditorium.
Second half -- principal trombonist Lance Green came on in his
underwear and stuffed a balloon in Philip Hore's tuba. Out came the
funny hats and the band blew the hell out of Stars and Stripes Forever.
From then on it was straight up the home strait, with Khatchaturian
sabre-rattling, Jeremy Randalls's Ceilidh, a compendium of Scots tunes
and reels, and an eloquent plea for support for the orchestra in its
winter season from conductor Hughes.
Incidentally, RSNO followers should note that the orchestra's new
winter season is being launched this week. Get The Herald on Wednesday.
* Concert sponsored by the Bank of Scotland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
