<DOCNO>GH950703-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>What's on at the jazz festival</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON KERR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584270</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
* THERE was an unadvertised change of personnel on the bandstand
during the Joe Locke gig on Saturday night. American drummer Cindy
Blackman had a good reason for her absence. Lenny Kravitz, apparently,
has first call on the drummer, and he decided that he wanted her for his
forthcoming tour.
As the Jazz Festival recovers from a weekend of indulgence, choices of
what to hear become simpler. In the McEwan's Old Fruitmarket 7.30pm slot
tonight is Paul Motian's Broadway Music outfit. Their self-imposed remit
is to resurrect and re-interpret standards from the great Broadway
musicals.
Over at McChuills pub on the High Street, at 8.30pm, the Scottish
women's group Engender is hosting a night of ''Women in Jazz''.
Back at the McEwan's Old Fruitmarket at 10pm, Chicago's young
trumpeter Robert Mazurek will be introducing Glaswegians to his blend of
hard and hot bop, with the help of his band -- Eric Alexander (sax),
Randy Tressler (piano), John Webber (bass) and George Fludas (drums).
ALISON KERR
</TEXT>
