<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rambert Dance Company, Festival Theatre, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584271</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I'VE already highlighted the last week of September in my diary --
that's when Rambert are in Glasgow, at the King's. Three of the reasons
I'm looking forward to seeing the company again soon are contained in
the programme that rounded off their performances at the Edinburgh
Festival Theatre last week.
This really was a treat of a triple bill, a well judged blend of wit,
drama, powerful emotions, and tongue-in-cheek fun that ably bore out
Christopher Bruce's contention that dance can be popular with a wide
ranging audience without any dilution of standards or ideas.
The ideas behind his own piece, Swansong, are in part a response to
Oriana Fallaci's novel A Man in which brutal interrogations of a
political prisoner take on a kind of heightened theatricality. This
element of showmanship Bruce tellingly translates into vaudeville dance
-- suddenly the rat-a-ta-tat of tap dance, the swaggering panache
attached to using a cane, take on an unexpectedly menacing edge.
Simon Cooper and Christopher Powney tap and shuffle with an ease that
is brilliantly, subtly sinister while Ted Stoffer -- the fall guy in the
chair -- brings an aching intensity to the lonely visions of flight that
intersperse bouts of fiercely athletic ''questioning''. Like an earlier
work of Bruce's, Ghost Dances, this is dance with a conscience --
eloquent, compassionate and crafted with integrity.
Another able craftsman is Mark Baldwin, whose Banter Banter opened the
programme. Bright, confident movement full of conversational gesture and
flirty humour -- set to energising Stravinsky rhythms -- it was neatly
balanced by Bruce's Rooster, a deliciously sassy evocation of the
generation who strutted (in flares and kipper ties) to the sounds of the
Stones. Absolutely ace -- not to be missed when the company make their
welcome return to Scotland in the autumn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish Jazzworks, Ramshorn Theatre, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ADAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584272</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish jazz scene has never been so rich in bands as it is
currently and this two-day event certainly proved the quality of the
product available. It's just a pity that this message never got through
to the public as attendances were uniformly thin.
I don't pretend to have the answer, although #5 tickets for bands who
can be seen either free or for half that price in clubs might have
something to do with it, but this is something the jazz festival will
surely want to look at in future.
The other problem is keeping all these bands working. The Spontaniacs,
though well-rehearsed and brilliantly marshalled by Des Travis's
precise, stylish drumming, lacked the freedom of movement within their
arrangements that comes with steady live performances.
In contrast, Chick Lyall's quintet, playing a not dissimilar, if less
self-consciously arty style of electric jazz used their tunes as a
jumping off point for some exciting solos from Lyall (keyboards),
saxophonist Phil Bancroft and guitarist Morph.
Pianist Steve Hamilton's trio reduced the heat but maintained a high
level of creativity with both original tunes and an unusual choice of
covers.
Leading a band seemed to weigh heavily on Robert Henderson. The
trumpeter, a dependably fiery and imaginative sideman, didn't play as he
can. But his specially commissioned compositions, particularly his
dedication to fellow trumpeter, the late Lee Morgan, captured the late
1950s/early 1960s hard-bop spirit to perfection.
Less easily pinned down stylistically, Mike Travis's EH15 closed the
weekend with another assured stride through a mix of African influences,
reggaefied blues and Spanish flavours that keeps getting better every
time I hear it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>It's all on the table</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEEDEE CUDDIHY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584273</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DEEDEE CUDDIHY looks at links between food and relationships
DOES marriage change our eating habits? That's the question a team of
researchers from Glasgow and Edinburgh universities are going to be
concentrating on over the next year or so.
Apparently, ''eating together is central to living together and in the
early stages of marriage or cohabiting, the eating habits of two
individuals are changing to become the eating habits of a couple''.
The researchers claim that the results of their study ''may ultimately
help people buy and choose food wisely and well''.
Who knows? But what is certain about the results is that, jargon
permitting, they're bound to make fascinating reading.
Although the universities' team is concentrating on first-time
cohabitees (married or otherwise), the whole business of just how much
control we have over our eating habits and how they change throughout
life is ripe for discussion and research.
On the face of it, it could be argued that mothers have total control
over what their children eat. But I have one child who seemed so
determined, from birth, that he was not going to be breastfed, that I
eventually had to give up and put him on to bottles. Since then we've
had such ferocious battles over numerous foods that I've now got to the
stage where I don't care what he eats (usually doughnuts and carry-out
chips with far too much tomato sauce), as long as he's getting enough
calories.
His sister, on the other hand, took to the breast like a seasoned
professional and is willing to have a go at most things including
creamed tuna fish and other dishes which don't look too promising but
actually taste quite nice (honest).
And what about school dinners, hospital food, canteen meals and other
institutional fare? Does exposure to all that alter our eating habits?
The researchers will have more than enough on their plates with newly
cohabiting, heterosexual couples (the sample of 45 pairs is, apparently,
too small to include gay people). For, as they state: ''In marriage,
food and meals have significant, symbolic functions which affect the
choice of food, its preparation, the way it is served and how it is
eaten. The role of gender in taking decisions and performing tasks is
crucial to our understanding of marital relationships.''
There is certainly no doubt in my mind that eating habits change when
you start living with someone. I distinctly remember, pre-cohabitation,
that my evening meal usually consisted of tinned tomato soup, cheddar
cheese and salad. Then, within hours of moving out of my flat and into
his, I found myself looking down a chicken's backside and feeling more
than a little uneasy about the prospect of roasting it.
I have a friend who, when her marriage broke up a few years ago, said
she only realised the relationship was in danger when her husband became
physically violent. However, I now recall that, some time before then,
he had begun rejecting the meals she made and latterly was buying and
preparing all his own food. Maybe that, and not the violence, was the
first sign of a marriage going down hill.
The researchers are still looking for volunteer couples to take part
in the project. You'll be doing them a favour and you get to talk about
yourself and what you eat -- all in complete confidence, at a time and
place to suit you.
Couples who will be interviewed by Deborah Kemmer just before they
move in together and again three months afterwards, must be childless
and be embarking on a first marriage or cohabitation some time this
year.
For further information, contact Doctor Kemmer on 0141 304 4686 or
0131 228 1484.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The unknotting of all those family ties</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LESLEY DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584274</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LESLEY DUNCAN finds it's now easy to get back to her roots
I'VE been digging up old family Bones. No macabre sorties to
graveyards were involved. Rather the location was that most handsome of
Glasgow enclaves, Park Circus. Here Strathclyde Regional Council's new
wedding suites are housed in the splendid terraced building that used to
be the Casa d'Italia. On the top floor, above the nuptual salons, is a
room kitted out with computer screens. These are the technological tools
for Strathclyde's new genealogy service. It will allow West of Scotland
residents to explore their family trees without having to go to Register
House, Edinburgh.
For the fee of #12 visitors can book a day's research, using visual
display units to trace information stored on microfilm or microfiche.
Two users share a link to the index of national records in Edinburgh.
Although this lists only names and dates, without giving details of
addresses and occupations, it gives basic information on every birth,
death, and marriage registered in Scotland. This in turn is a useful
tool for delving into microfiche showing all the entries made in the
area covered by Strathclyde Region since civil registration was
introduced in 1855. Pre-1955 Church of Scotland parish registers, which
listed most of the baptism, marriage proclamations, and burials in their
areas, can also be consulted.
A caveat about the last. ''These records are only as good as the
session clerks in each area!'' counsels Bill Craig, depute chief
registrar for Glasgow, who had kindly offered to guide me through the
intricacies of research.
There's a further bank of information available in microfilm records
of the census taken every 10 years from 1841 to 1891. It gives details
about households (enabling the tracing of siblings) as well as the
names, ages, occupations, marital status and parish of birth of everyone
listed.
All this is most impressive in theory. Now to put it to the test. I
start off with certain advantages. Ancestors on both sides of the family
-- with known Ayrshire and Paisley connections -- almost certainly all
lived within the geographical boundaries of Strathclyde for the last 200
years .
I've decided, however, to pursue one of my own middle names. This is
Bone -- my maternal grandmother's maiden name. Needless to say, it was
the cause of much leg-pulling when I was at school. Only when I reached
my late teens did I realise it had a certain kudos. For my grandmother
had been some sort of cousin to the celebrated Bone brothers who
included the war artist and etcher Muirhead Bone; David, novelist and
commodore of the Anchor Line; and James, London editor of the then
Manchester Guardian.
I start with myself. There's a slight hiccup because my baptismal
first name (Elisabeth) has been recorded with a Z rather than an S. My
full baptismal data is there pulled up on microfiche. From there we
pursue my father, because his surname, Munn, is less common than my
mother's, Stevenson.
We find my parents' marriage details, and from that my mother's age
and her parents' names. My grandparents' marriage is soon found and then
again, using the lever of my grandmother's age at marriage, her birth
information, and then her parents' marriage -- 1859 at St Quivox Church,
Ayr. I now have the name of my great-great-grandfather -- James, also a
coalminer, and his wife, another Elizabeth, who has, sadly, an illegible
surname.
In less than an hour I have traced this branch of my family back to
the 1830s. Lunch obtrudes. The link with the Bone brothers is still to
be made. But I've gleaned from The Dictionary of National Biography that
Muirhead Bone's father, David Drummond Bone, came from Ayr and probably
married within the same decade as my great-grandfather. Another session
will be sure to crack the Bones. That leaves only the Stevensons and
McCullochs, the Munns and Tainshes, and a few other surnames forbye, for
future sleuthing.
The combination of the uncommon name and Bill Craig's expert
assistance have made my introductory exploration unusually swift. Not
that difficulties will daunt members of the public such as Agnes Murray.
She emigrated to Canada in 1955 and is now back in Scotland from London,
Ontario, looking into both sides of her family tree. ''I've got back to
1850 and the marriage of my great-great-grand father,'' she announces
with satisfaction.
Strathclyde's pilot genealogy service can accommodate six researchers
at the same time. There will be a review after six months and the
possibility of doubling that number.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Conflicts still simmering away. The politics of milk</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584275</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was a senior Nestle executive who last year described how he used
to regard milk as ''wet white stuff'' which he bought as basic raw
material.
Deregulation has changed all of that and much more attention is being
paid to the composition of milk and to the price which processors are
prepared to pay producers for that basic raw material.
The Scottish Milk Marketing Board has gone and there is keen interest
in the prices paid to farmers by its partial successor, Scottish Milk,
and by private operators such as Wiseman or Nestle who are now free to
make their own contractual arrangements with producers.
People speak of the politics of milk and the indications are that
deregulation has not made the scene any less political.
A hint at some of the conflicts still simmering away was given at the
annual meeting of the residual board which is charged with the
responsibility over the next five years of winding up the affairs of the
former SMMB.
Scottish Pride, formerly the manufacturing arm of the board and now a
public limited company in its own right, is regarded with suspicion by
many of its dairy farmer/shareholders who fear that the company's desire
to be an efficient modern business may run contrary to their interests
as dairy farmers.
Scottish Pride's ambitions, they suspect, lie in screwing down the
cost of its raw material -- milk. If these fears prove justified will
the money they receive in dividends on their shares compensate for a
less-than-expected figure on the milk cheque?
It is these fears which have led to the formation of a shareholders'
association which is determined to raise its concerns at the company's
first annual general meeting later this month.
The interim-chairman of that grouping was Tom Reid, vice-convener of
the National Farmers' Union of Scotland Milk Committee, until it was
explained to him that there was a possible conflict of interest. He has
stepped down from the shareholders' grouping.
The possible conflict of interest became a reality on Friday of last
week when the milk committee decided to give its support to the Scottish
Pride board and advised shareholders to vote against the five
resolutions submitted by the shareholders' association for the company's
annual meeting.
It has become clear that the NFUS is anxious to maintain its sphere of
influence in the milk sector and does not regard Scotttish Pride as just
another company with whom some of its members do business. The union's
milk committee will not to support ''any action which might destabilise
the company'' during this first year of its development.
It invited both the dissident shareholders and Scottish Pride to be
represented at the specially convened meeting of the milk committee,
although the shareholders' grouping declined.
John Ross, national president of the NFUS, attended a meeting of milk
producers in Ayr last week to press home the point that the union very
much wants to be part of any discussions on milk. Concern over milk
prices was one of the causes which led to the formation of the union 80
years ago. That concern is not fading. ''If there are any problems,
bring them here,' John Scott, president of the Ayr area executive, has
told his members.
Michael McReath, secretary of the Scottish Pride shareholders'
association insists, however, that he and his 200 co-signatories have
done nothing wrong in putting forward critical resolutions for the
Scottish Pride meeting. The best way forward, he sees, is for the
resolutions to be voted on. That will give an indication of how much
support there is for the stance taken by the association members.
There is, of course, logic in all the arguments. Shareholders
obviously have a right to express concerns about their company, as they
did recently with great public acceptance, at British Gas.
Scottish Pride directors, naturally, have a responsibility to run the
company as effectively as possible in the interests of the shareholders
-- but they will presumably look at the shareholders' interests as
shareholders and not as suppliers of the raw material.
The union argues that it exists to protect the economic and political
interests of its members -- including its dairy farmer members -- which
it obviously interprets as not undermining one of the major players this
early in the post-deregulation game.
It is a situation which needs handling with kid gloves. It may be one
of the first hot potatoes to land in the lap of the NFU's new director
of public affairs and communications, if the union's council decides to
go ahead with such an appointment.
The recent surge of adverse publicity on animal welfare has caused the
union to review its communications procedures in the wake of complaints
from members that the farmers' side of the story was not getting over to
the public. Chief executive Tom Brady has prepared a paper for
Wednesday's council meeting which outlines the need for improved
communications both internally and externally.
His proposals are soundly based, provided whoever is appointed to the
post does not see his or her role as the conduit for all communication
with with the union's leaders. Journalists will always prefer direct
contact.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EUROVIEW,</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>977584276</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE had a glimpse of the future last week when Tony Blair and John
Major came to Cannes. Both had their media minders marching one step
behind them and both wielded carefully rehearsed soundbites. Indeed it
is becoming increasingly difficult these days to distinguish between
Blair and Major on European policy. Both are adept at news management, a
sinister but accurate enough phrase, first given to the world, I
believe, by officials in the Kennedy White House.
Getting to Major was the difficult part but the effort produced
another little victory which brings the latest score in the continuing
match between the Scottish press and the Whitehall machine to two-nil
for us.
Major was preparing his response to the news of the Redwood challenge
and agreed to meet British reporters on the Croisette in Cannes, where
he would say a few words, we were advised. But, it seems, when Number 10
talks of the British-only media, it means London-only.
This was to be a pool job with places for only 11 reporters, each
issued with a green badge of accreditation. The others were told they
could take a hike. My colleague from that Edinburgh rag and I were
included out.
Call me an old cynic, but it did seem strange there just happened to
be 11 Westminster lobby correspondents in town. A stushie ensued in
which demonstrations of the Glasgow kiss were promised. We won after
intervention by the Foreign Office team in Brussels, who understand
about our sensitivities on these matters.
Indeed, the brave chap who came to our rescue, again, must be bored to
death with them. But he proved he is one of us at heart. (His mum comes
from Bellshill.) Our greatest admiration, however, is reserved for one
hack -- who must remain anonymous -- who knew his chances of a green
card were nil but who needed to be there.
He scoured around for some green cardboard and black felt pen and
simply made his own. No-one rumbled him. This disgraceful forgery now
hangs on his office wall as a trophy. There was a time when enterprising
journalists like that were promoted and given a pay rise. Now they are
fired if the politicians' media minders complain.
Being Prime Minister (at the time of writing), Major has a battery of
media advisers. They will talk for hours about how wonderfully he
performed in negotiations, scoring lots of successes with his bulldog
determination to battle for Britain. What they don't tell you is, of
course, usually what their audience wants to know.
As always, Burns said it all:
Here's freedom to him who would read
Here's freedom to him who would write
There's nane ever feared
But the truth should be heard
But they whom the truth would indict.
If and when Major steps down, his media team will do the same for his
successor. Some of the key personalities will change if the governing
party changes, but the system will remain firmly in place.
Tony Blair is a dab hand at news management. His media trusty,
Alastair Campbell, is permanently at his side and destined to become the
Bernard Ingham of the Labour Party. I don't know whether Campbell's
relationship with Blair involves coaching, but there is no question that
when it comes to offering soundbites Tony Blair is almost ridiculously
determined.
At the socialist summit near Cannes, the British media were taken into
the garden where Blair appeared before them. Someone said they counted
seven questions to the Labour leader, all different, all on camera. The
trouble was that the seven replies to the seven different questions were
almost identical.
The Blair message that day was that the Tory leadership election was
damaging Britain. He said it every time, regardless. If you had asked
him if he fancied Queen of the South for the European Cup, he would have
replied that the Tory leadership election was damaging Britain. This
raises a neo-Orwellian concept: news programmes on the telly where
no-one asks questions. There would be no need because the political
parties would have already sent in their soundbites in advance. It would
matter not what viewers or newspaper readers actually wanted to know:
they would be told what politicians decide they must hear.
Most politicians are like Major and Blair. Douglas Hurd, elegant and
cultured, is an honourable exception. History might not be kind to Hurd
as Foreign Secretary, but no-one can deny he is an erudite and almost
poetic individual among less thoughtful men like Major.
Hurd loves conjuring phrases. He foresaw the grisly concept of the
''level killing field'' in Bosnia if the arms embargo was lifted; he
recalled Jacques Delors as the ''philosopher king in Brussels''. Hurd,
of course, is a writer in his spare time. Not for him the shameless,
glib soundbite. He would rather quote Shakespeare than struggle to
remember his media minder's script for the day.
Soundbite culture is having a curious effect on the general direction
of British policy in Europe. Blair and Major are in danger of becoming
indistinguishable. Telling who is saying what is confusing because the
same soundbites, with their need for simplicity, are becoming
attributable to either leader. This trend reached a new level of
precision when both Blair and Major talked about Britain ''at the heart
of Europe''.
For example, who do you think said: ''We will maintain the veto
vigorously in key areas.'' And who said: ''We shall not accept the end
of the national veto.'' Which Tory is the Tony? Well, not that it
matters much, the first was Blair last month in Bonn and the second Mr
Major in the Commons on March 1.
There are reams of speeches from both men on the issue of Europe. On
minor questions -- and the social chapter of Maastricht, which Labour
wants and the Tories don't, is a minor question if you consider its real
effect on working people -- there is some genuine difference of opinion.
Gradually, however, on the great issues such as the veto and the single
currency there is a convergence of soundbites (sorry, policies).
What will happen when Blair is in power is, of course, another matter.
</TEXT>
