<HEADLINE>Saudi prince set to bid for Canary Wharf</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584278</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SAUDI businessmen Prince al-Waleed bin Talal bin Abdul-Aziz is
preparing a bid for Canary Wharf, the London office development that
once symbolised the collapse of Britain's 1980s property boom, market
sources said yesterday.
They said that there were no other partners involved and that the bid
needed no outside financing as it would be backed by the prince's own
funds.
''He is now leading the list of bidders for Canary Wharf,'' said one
source.
The bid pits the prince against a consortium assembled by Paul
Reichmann that is trying to regain control of the development which in
1992 sent his Olympia &amp; York into administration as commercial property
prices plunged.
The market sees the bid by Prince al-Waleed, who owns nearly 25% of
Euro Disney and is Citicorp's largest single shareholder, in a
favourable light because, unlike Reichmann, he had no previous
involvement in the project.
Canary Wharf is now owned by an 11-bank syndicate headed by Lloyds
Bank, which pulled the east end dockside site out of administrative
receivership in 1993. The syndicate includes Barclays, Citicorp,
Commerzbank and Credit Suisse.
A spokeswoman for Lloyds would not comment on any specific bids but
confirmed a number of interests had been expressed. She said that no
sale prospectus had been produced and that all offers so far had been
unsolicited.
Though Canary Wharf was seen as a disaster after its financial
collapse, market sentiment has been changing recently. The huge
development, visible for miles around and now a London landmark, has
attracted a succession of high-profile businesses.
Investment bank Barclays de Zoete Wedd is based there and the complex
has become the new ''Fleet Street'' with several newspapers, including
the Daily Mirror and Daily Telegraph, working out of the east London
site.
Prince al-Waleed, a nephew of Saudi Arabia's King Fahd, has
specialised in making seemingly doomed ventures turn a profit. He has
taken stakes in and merged several failing firms in Saudi Arabia and
turned them into profitable ventures.
He is currently leading a consortium involved in talks to buy part of
former Italian Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi's Fininvest media
empire.
At 37 years old and a multi-billionaire, Prince al-Waleed is chairman
of United Saudi Commercial Bank and also counts among his global
holdings a 25% stake in the Toronto-based Four Seasons Hotels Inc. --
Reuter.
</TEXT>
