<HEADLINE>Tax protest</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584279</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE investment trust trade association has called on the Government to
exempt investors in school fee plans from the Inland Revenue's plan to
change the tax regime on gilts and zero dividend capital shares.
The Revenue is proposing that capital gains on gilts and zeros should
be taxed as income. Zeros rise in value by a specified percentage each
year and at present this is counted as capital gain and taxed
accordingly. They are often used in school fee plans where it is
necessary to have a particular capital sum available at a certain date.
''A large number of private shareholders have invested in good faith
under the existing tax rules to meet future spending commitments such as
school fees and retirement provision,'' said Ernest Fenton, director
general of the Association of Investment Trust Companies (AITC). ''I
thought the Government wished to encourage self-help, not penalise it.
To change the rules retrospectively would hit these people hard.''
The AITC has also objected to the changes in gilt taxation which it
says would result in double taxation on gilts and bonds held by
investment trusts. Around #5500m is invested in gilts and bonds by the
industry.
</TEXT>
