<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Making, not faking, news</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JULIA LANGDON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584280</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN A hilarious article in the current issue of the British Journalism
Review, the great Hugh Cudlipp discloses some 65-year-old secrets about
his graduation as a cub reporter in Blackpool. It was there, at the
tender age of 17, that he took his degree in street wisdom, with honours
in what he describes as ''creative journalism''.
When he arrived in Blackpool as a district reporter for the Manchester
Evening Chronicle, the young Cudlipp had already seen some life -- and
attempted death, having had to use his Boy Scout knife to cut down an
editor who had tried suicide with the cord of the window blind after
learning of the impending closure of his newspaper.
On the famous Front, amid the Kiss-me-Quick paper hats of 1930, he was
to be provided with a further introduction to the realities of survival
in the newspaper industry: his news editor reminded him every Monday
morning of the need for ''something the others haven't got''. By means
of creative journalism, Cudlipp gave it to them. ''Creative
journalism,'' he writes, ''is the art of causing something to occur that
would not otherwise materialise and is worthy of record in a newspaper;
making news, not faking news.'' How different, how very different, to
the kind of creative journalism so widely practised today.
If that sounds pompous, it is unintentional. It so happened that I was
reading Lord Cudlipp's article on Saturday shortly after reading the
morning newspapers and what he wrote acquired a particular relevance for
me because of a news report in that morning's Daily Mail.
The item concerned the Tory leadership contest. It reported how John
Redwood's campaign had allegedly received a considerable boost because
of the declared support of Lord Tebbit (who does not have a vote and
whose political position was, in any case, already obvious) and a
statement by Virginia Bottomley. The Secretary of State for Health had
apparently indicated in a TV interview that if John Redwood were elected
leader she would be prepared, if asked, to serve in his Government.
The correct reaction to that is: so what? Of course Mrs Bottomley,
like most other members of the Cabinet, would probably be prepared to
stay on under Mr Redwood. Some might not be able to stick the idea; some
might not be asked. As it happens, Mrs Bottomley is exactly the sort of
person Mr Redwood probably would NOT ask.
I saw the interview in question which was shown yesterday and what Mrs
Bottomley said, when asked if she would serve, was: ''I don't think
anyone seriously thinks that will be a prospect we will be facing.'' She
was also rather rude about Mr Redwood.
Nevertheless this interview had been turned into an item of ''news'',
as a huge blow for John Major, as an embarrassment to him and his
campaign, when in fact it was actually political propaganda by a
newspaper actively campaigning against him. Making news? Or faking news?
Its relevance for me was that I had spent much of the previous day
following Mrs Bottomley around her constituency, listening to her
addressing her local voters, answering questions from schoolchildren and
talking to individuals. According to my notebook she made at least seven
enthusiastic public references to John Major in which she spoke of him
as a ''nice person'', a ''good man'', and an excellent Prime Minister.
She liked working for him, thought he would win the election easily, and
was distinctly negative about any other outcome.
In her best Mary Poppins manner she told a schoolchild playing the
part of John Redwood in a mock election: ''If you don't win I hope
you're going to be a very good team player.''
The purpose of the Daily Mail story was pure mischief, and everyone
involved in its publication knew as much. It was not in itself damaging,
but then neither was it ''news'' and nor should it have been presented
as such.
Whose fault was this -- the ambitious young journalist who reported
the interview or the editorial staff who prepared it for publication? I
certainly remember the ignominy of my own youthful discovery that I was
not heading for a career as a fearless Fleet Street gossip columnist. I
had been sent to find out whether the late Bill Simpson, then enjoying
huge fame as the first Dr Finlay, was about to marry a particular
actress. I bought him lunch in a pub on some flimsy pretext and then,
hugely embarrassed, revealed the real reason -- which he had, of course,
already guessed. I had to ask him these questions, I explained, and he
took pity on me and kindly heard me out. To every question he replied:
''I don't know.''
When I returned to the office, claiming in relief that there was no
story, they asked me what precisely he had said. Had I asked all the
questions? Was he going to marry the lady? My relief was short-lived.
The story appeared as a page lead: ''TV's Dr Finlay is uncertain about
his future with Miss X. Is he going to marry her? ''I don't know'' he
told the Daily Beast . . .'' Making news? Or faking it?
Creative journalism as practised by Cudlipp was altogether a more
subtle and sophisticated matter. And was it wrong? As he argues himself
he gave them all manner of amusement, from church services for people's
pets and the artists of the Tower circus to Uproar Over Unfrocked
Rector's Public Shame and the mysterious Case of the Missing Blackpool
Fullback. But, he boasts, and with some justification, his exclusives
were not inaccurate, misleading or distorted; distinguished between
comment and fact; were not intrusive or intimidating; and did not
require misrepresentation or subterfuge. He made news in the public
interest for the public interest. Alas that we shall not see those days
again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
