<HEADLINE>Heady brew of victory that distorted reality</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT MCLAUGHLAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>BOOK WEEK</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>977584281</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE LOST VICTORY: BRITISH
DREAMS, BRITISH REALITIES
1945-1950.
By Correlli Barnett.
Macmillan #20 (pp 514)
UNDERSTANDABLY, in 1945, Britons believed they had won the war against
Germany and Japan. Their most successful general, Montgomery, had taken
the surrender of the German armies in the west, and their
representatives had been present aboard USS Missouri in Tokyo Bay when
the Americans accepted the surrender of the Japanese forces.
The Empire had been fully restored and, contrary to what is normally
noted in books, its fullest extent had not after all been fixed in 1918,
for Cyrenaica was informally added in 1945, an expansion devoutly wished
by the new Foreign Secretary, Labour's Ernest Bevin.
Moreover the Axis surrenders (and these included Italy earlier) were
unconditional, advertising in that fact the overwhelming extent of
victory, a victory which, from the British point of view, also knocked
out the threat German and Japanese exports had posed to their
international trade before 1939.
The victory had been won by three main allies: Britain, the US, and
the Soviet Union -- the Great Powers, to whom weak China and defeated
France were added only by generosity. Of the Big Three only Britain had
entered the war on grounds of principle -- the Americans and Russians
had merely responded to Axis aggression against them -- and Britain had
for a time faced the Germans alone, in what proved to be glorious
isolation.
Correlli Barnett is right to start his analysis of the comprehensive
disaster the country suffered under the 1945-50 Labour Government by
establishing how this view of our wartime role distorted reality. We had
not won the war, but instead had been on the winning side.
It was American money and Russian manpower which defeated the Nazis.
Our own effort was magnificent, but marginal to the outcome. At the end
we were close to bankruptcy, but could not grasp its meaning or
consequence because of the heady brew of succcess.
The Labour Government which was unexpectedly elected in 1945 had to
deal with this complex situation in which public opinion was
ill-equipped to recognise reality. It was ill-equipped to do so itself
and signally failed to establish the right priorities -- investment
before consumption -- which were unerringly accepted on the Continent,
since no-one there had any doubts about what the war had done to their
economies.
Barnett has a polemical tone -- this is not dry as dust history -- but
that does not affect the quality of the argument which begins by
noticing how the new Government adopted a stance in international
affairs commensurate only with being a Great Power, and not the much
more modest power which the country had become.
Hence the leaders of the armed forces (who might be forgiven, since
they had participated in the, eventually, successful fighting) shared
the grandiose notions of their political masters. Attlee, identified
here as a foreign policy realist, was somewhat more cautious (though,
without telling the Cabinet, he committed the country to the huge
expense of atomic weaponry) but his colleagues, notably Bevin, were for
maintaining the myth of Great Power status at enormous cost.
Defence spending under Labour took an enormous slice of the national
income, around one-quarter of the state budget, in spite of the
knock-out of the Axis and before the emergence of the Cold War.
The assumptions behind this policy, particularly the weight accorded
to the Empire, were themselves suspect -- here Barnett is maintaining
his argument from earlier books about the Empire being a burden rather
that a source of strength, an argument now widely accepted.
If the country could not afford this international role, could it
afford the vastly expensive welfare state and National Health Service,
designed with a prodigality far beyond that of Sir William Beveridge, on
whose thinking they were based? The financing of state insurance
benefits, already detached from contributions, was now massively
increased, and warnings of eventual catastrophe (now looming,
incidentally) were ignored. The health service did not even have a
contributions myth: its cost quickly escalated wildly out of control,
presenting the Government with continual stress, but no other country in
the world with a model.
No Government has successfully managed to reform the service because
of the political cost of assaulting its main assumption, that it is free
at the point of use. Even the one available wedge, prescription charges,
eventually conceded by its main creator, Aneurin Bevan, still leaves
more than two-thirds of prescriptions free.
The enormous sums involved in this, and the housing policy designed to
give every family a house of its own, were a colossal strain on
available resources. They were paid for by American loans and by not
investing in productive industry or the infrastructure.
The Government had no plan (nothing remotely analagous to the French
national plan) and no coherent policy for the economy. It had
nationalisation but that did not revolutionise anything and merely
distorted the allocation of scarce resources. It certainly did not
address technical, and technological, weakness from education to
management, identified here in page after page.
Nor could it when the Government itself, and its advisers, were so
conspicuously lacking in technical and managerial expertise. Of
Ministers, only Cripps had managerial experience to an extent sufficient
for Barnett to call him ''a technocrat''. The top civil servants were
nearly all Oxbridge classicists with no involvement in industry. Yet it
was mainly industry -- and its exports -- which were vital to the
economy's salvation.
Barnett runs through a range of industries and activities: textiles,
shipbuilding, the mines, the railways, aeronautics, gas (where he adds
notes of direct personal experience). Their experience had few positive
gains: state intervention proved to be more harmful than helpful.
Of course the Government had bad luck. Nationalisation changed little
if anything in workers' attitudes (voluntary absenteeism and strike
statistics make that clear) and the fearful winter of 1947, with the
coldest February in 300 years, was a disaster of its own, especially on
the railways (effectively denied investment by the Government which
funnelled it into housing).
The fact was that the economy did not grow very much, the foreign
loans (Canadian as well as American) were consumed and the investment in
new plant, new products, and the infrastructure to serve them, so
conspicuous in defeated France and Germany, was inadequate.
Those who presided over this failure were neither wicked nor stupid.
They believed in goodness and social improvement and they were thrown by
victory and the need to offer better lives to their fellow citizens.
Fifty years later it is clear that good intentions are not enough,
that profit is not a dirty word but a necessity, and that international
roles are only to be played where we have a direct material interest --
such as we did in Kuwait and assuredly do not have in Bosnia.
</TEXT>
