<HEADLINE>Pension power</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584282</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN your report, Region's role in gas row attacked (June 24),
Councillor Gould illustrates how unfit he and the entire Labour
administration are to protect the interests of the electorate, or to
understand financial matters.
No-one has suggested that Strathclyde Regional Council's pension fund
should not be invested in British Gas. What was suggested was that at
the AGM the voting power of the shares held by the pension fund should
have been used to express a vote of no confidence in the gas board
directors following their awarding a 75% salary increase to Cedric
Brown, chief executive.
All local authority pension funds should use their voting power to
ensure that the companies' profits go to the benefit of the pensioners
and not to awarding chief executives or directors undue salary increases
or share options.
Grampian region and Central have given a clear lead. Strathclyde and
the new unitary authorities must quickly follow their example.
A united lead on behalf of local government pensioners may encourage
the private sector pension fund holders also to ensure that their voting
power is used to represent the interests of pensioners whose funds they
hold.
Councillor Margaret Murray,
27 Birniehall Road,
Cumbernauld.
</TEXT>
