<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Parties without a soul</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584283</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WAS intrigued by the notion in your front-page headline on June 27
that the Conservative leadership contest was a ''battle for soul of Tory
party''.
I had thought that the purpose of politicians (if they have any) was
to try to knock the sharp edges off amoral market forces. Both Mr Major
and Mr Redwood seem to be of the view that market forces should shape
our moral values.
In the context that Mrs Thatcher held similar views and has already
dispensed with any soul the Tory party had, the current contestants
would seem to be too late to engage in the battle you suggest.
It is an unfortunate sign of the times that any political party
wishing to pursue the current Conservative agenda (even if it be New
Labour) has no need of, or apparently use for, a soul.
James Nelson,
17 Watermill Avenue,
Lenzie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
