<HEADLINE>Time to put stalking horses out to grass</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>INSIDE POLITICS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584284</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO factors in the leadership campaign emerged yesterday that should
have a considerable impact on tomorrow night's result. The first is what
Major and Redwood said, bearing in mind that the electorate in this kind
of vote may be duplicitous, but the candidates themselves rarely tell
outright lies in public.
Mr Major declared that he does not feel betrayed by Redwood's
challenge to him and that there will be no recriminations. Mr Redwood
stated that he wants the leadership resolved tomorrow and that whoever
wins should receive 100% support.
This contradicts the perception of some that what he really wants is
to damage Major sufficiently to cause a second ballot in which Michael
Portillo could take up his standard. This would create the risk of a
successful intervention by Michael Heseltine.
The second factor is that the Tory constituency parties are
overwhelmingly in favour of Major and threaten dark deeds if their
advice is ignored by their MPs. They find that they have already been
deserted by erstwhile Tory voters; now it might be their turn to desert
Tory MPs seeking to hold their seats in a General Election.
Let us take the second factor first. Anybody who has kept in touch
with the voluntary wing of the Tory party -- those who do the
door-knocking and raise the money -- over the past three years in
particular will have picked up the message. It is this: if the
parliamentary party cannot unite behind its leader, come what may, why
should we bother any more?
Weekend opinion polls, external and internal -- confirm this view. If
another Tory leader is dumped, these people will react furiously. It is
not just a matter of de-selecting sitting MPs as candidates for a
General Election. This is hard to do precisely and fairly when their MPs
vote tomorrow in a secret ballot.
It is more serious than this. The threat is that next time it will not
just be Tory voters who stay at home to accord Labour a victory, but
Tory activists who will do so -- to accord Labour a landslide victory.
Belatedly, the parliamentary party is moving towards the idea that it is
daft to have rules that allow an annual challenge to the leadership of a
sitting Prime Minister.
The party in the country has been telling the parliamentary party this
since Sir Anthony Meyer challenged Prime Minister Thatcher and opened up
the grudgers' delight of the ''stalking horse'' concept. In Opposition,
a party can take these kind of factional risks. In Government, that
party looks and smells suicidal.
Over the past week, full-time party political agents of long standing
in their jobs, plus a series of constituency chairmen, have told me that
they will quit if Mr Major is humiliated. ''If this happens, I go,'' is
what they say. ''If this happens, Blair would be crazy not to engineer a
General Election in the next nine months. That means obliteration for
us.''
So, emerging over the weekend is this new element, always there but
not so baldly stated: whoever Major's successor might be, he would have
no time to restore morale and loyalty in the constituencies. Discount
for hyperbole, and you still have a disaster potential for the Tories.
Unless, that is, you think Mr Redwood would give voters such a charge as
Prime Minister that the party activists would rejoin the Tory cause too.
Of course, this is what Redwood is offering in resigning from Major's
Government and standing against him. He claims that if the leader can't
make his own views clear, and state them sharply, he has no chance of
coping with Blair and his new model Labour alternative. He is developing
his campaign in its closing stages from the ideological to the starkly
practical. Vote Redwood for the best chance of holding your seats. No
change, no chance.
Both candidates were interviewed by Sir David Frost on BBC breakfast
television yesterday and it was from these interviews that Factor One
emerged. They have a common interest in not wanting a second ballot. Mr
Redwood went first and made his pitch as the best leader to win a
General Election. The formula is tax and spending cuts now, plus a
''never'' to a single European currency and a referendum on this issue
when it has to be faced.
He is playing on the gutsy factor -- ie, he and he alone has had the
courage actually to put up against Major whereas others, like Portillo
and Heseltine, are still lurking around awaiting the providence of a
second ballot. No wonder he wants it sorted tomorrow. Why should he owe
them anything, should he win? And why should he support them,
particularly Portillo, if he loses? To get a better Cabinet job than
Wales?
Mr Major followed him into the Frost studio, having heard what he said
about the need for 100% support for the winner tomorrow night. Major
said his opponent had behaved ''perfectly honourably'' in standing
against him. ''I am not in the business of recriminations. I am not a
factional politician. I don't feel betrayed by John Redwood. You don't
call a leadership election and then complain if somebody takes you up on
it.''
This sounds like mending fences. A Major victory will not mean a purge
of the right wing from his Government's 110 posts. It could also mean a
return to Cabinet for Redwood, providing he concedes defeat gallantly,
discounting abstentions and offering 100% support for the winner. What
chance then of his right-wing rival, Portillo, benefiting from a second
ballot at his, Redwood's, expense?
If this sounds fanciful, look at it this way. Such conduct would earn
the 44-year-old Redwood good opinions throughout the party, not least
from the activists. His integrity as a young, able, and honourably
ambitious politician would be re-established.
If Major reneged on his pledge of no recriminations his chance of
creating unity -- the whole purpose of the exercise -- would be gone.
Redwood lives to fight another day, still able to influence Cabinet
decisions. He loses the ''extreme'' right label and, centre stage, joins
the much broader power base of the centre right.
There is, of course, another side to the coin. Sufficient MPs may
seize this chance, the last before a General Election, for a more macho
alternative leader. A Redwood victory would bring about the instant
resignation of the Prime Minister, a concept deeply desired by sections
of the erstwhile Tory media and the Tory back benches. But Redwood would
be hard-put to establish unity.
It is commonly thought Mr Blair would rather have Major maintained in
office, preferably as a lame-duck leader. But a Redwood victory would
suit him by pushing the Tories further to the right, leaving him in
command of the centre ground that wins elections. So much so that he
could spring a confidence motion and bring forward the date of the
General Election.
Only suicidal Tories could countenance such a possibility. They need
all the time they have left to try to regain the country's confidence.
In short, when they vote tomorrow they might remember Margaret
Thatcher's Tina, (There Is No Alternative), as propounded now by her
successor.
Picture: REUTERS
</TEXT>
