<RECORDNO>977584285</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WITH a Conservative Party leadership contest sprung upon us again for
the second time in five years questions must be asked about the
credibility of the British political system as a bona fide democracy.
In April 1992 41.8% of the British electorate voted for the
Conservative Party led by John Major, yet in the weeks to come we may
well see the democratically expressed wish of this 41.8% overturned by
the very Conservative MPs who got elected on a platform of John Major's
leadership.
In the months running up to the 1992 General Election John Major, like
other political party leaders, was placed at the forefront of the
Conservative Party's campaign to gain re-election and thus when those
41.8% of the electorate put their cross in the Conservative box they
also explicity endorsed John Major as the Prime Minister for five years
in an indirect way by voting for Conservative candidates.
The Conservative Party's practice of changing leader when in
government is dubious in a democracy because the 329 Conservative MPs
who will decide John Major's fate this month have a democratic
legitimacy that is derived only from the particular constituency in
which they were elected as an MP, whereas John Major is the only
politician elected on a nationwide basis with his mandate derived from
the British electorate. Thus in a democracy the Prime Minister should
only be removable by that electorate at a General Election.
The Conservative Party should urgently consider scrapping this
leadership contest from the party constitution during the period that
the party is in government. Should the Conservatives continue with this
practice Britain may be lumbered with a one-party state for ever.
The danger is that if a Conservative Government is suffering extreme
unpopularity as in 1990 and 1995 it can dump the old Prime Minister,
wheel in a new Prime Ministger, and thereby change the whole personality
of the Government, giving the electorate the impression that the party
is revitalised with new policies when in fact it's the same collection
of Conservative MPs with the same old ideas.
Fergus Watt,
136 Main Street,
Callander.
</TEXT>
