<HEADLINE>Problem arising from popularity</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584288</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MAY I offer a few observations on the article by Mary Docherty on
local authority policies on placing requests (Education Herald, June
20)?
The placing request legislation was never thought through properly
before being implemented. Either that, or the implications were ignored.
As well as the problem experienced by Mary Docherty (of one child
failing to obtain a place in the same school as his brothers), it has
led inevitably to class sizes rising to the maximum of 33 pupils, in
both primary and secondary sectors, and to the situation where children
who have moved into the catchment area of a school have to be
transported by taxi to a school miles away until a place in their local
school becomes available.
While sympathising with Mary Docherty in her particular situation, I
find it hard to accept that she never foresaw the possibility of their
third son being refused a place in Notre Dame Primary School.
In a popular school there must always be the chance that this will
happen. Projected school rolls are available for several years ahead,
and they must have indicated a rising intake from the catchment area.
It was explained to Mary Docherty that the school had room for only
one primary one class, but this was disputed later at the appeal
hearing. Every school has an agreed capacity, designed to allow it to
operate efficiently and without overcrowding.
There may well be a spare room somewhere where an extra class could be
accommodated, but would this reduce the space available for other
essential school activities, such as music and drama?
As for the argument that the region should employ an extra teacher at
Notre Dame, current financial restrictions simply do not make this a
practical solution, bearing in mind that the same situation is repeated,
year in, year out, in many of Strathclyde's schools.
The main point in Mary Docherty's article seems to be the proposition
that in the case of too few places being available in a school priority
should be given to those children with siblings already at the school,
whether or not they live in the catchment area.
I find this amazingly self-centred. If all the 15 children from
outwith the catchment area of Notre Dame, but with brothers and sisters
already in the school, were to be allocated places this year, what does
Mary Docherty suggest should happen to the 15 children from within the
catchment area who would then be displaced?
To which school should they be transported, and how many miles away
from their homes would it be? Who would be responsible for ensuring, and
paying for, their safe transport there?
Most important of all, should every parent in the catchment area of a
school really be expected to live with the uncertainty until the very
last moment of wondering if their child will be allocated a place in the
local school?
I agree that the placing request legislation needs to be reviewed, but
the answer does not lie in scrapping the catchment area system. Without
it, administration of the education system would be impossible and chaos
would result.
Rachael B Smith,
25 Castlehill Road,
Stewarton.
</TEXT>
