<HEADLINE>A busy, busy line</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584289</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WAS rather aggrieved to hear that Michael Portillo has had no fewer
than 20 new telephone lines installed. It is presumed that this has been
done to assist hs challenge in the Tory leadership contest should there
be a second ballot. The decision to install them must, therefore, have
been made in the last very few days.
For more than a week now I have awaited the installation of a single
phone line to my factory unit. Today I was told that though it had been
scheduled for today I would have to wait.
In an effort to speed up my telephone installation, I should like to
make the following categorical statement:
''The rumours indicating that I might stand for election as leader of
the Conservative Party are unfounded. I have no plans to put my name
forward in the first ballot for Conservative Party leader. I assure you
that the Prime Minister will win in the first ballot and win
convincingly. There will be no second ballot and Mr Major continues to
enjoy my full support.''
After that denial, I assume British Telecom will be breaking down my
door to install my telephone line.
W Gordon,
40 Low Waters Road,
Hamilton.
</TEXT>
