<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Vetting by the Kirk's men in mufti</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584291</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE selection procedure for candidates for the ministry seems to me in
need of an overhaul. My main concern is for the candidates who feel
genuinely called to the ministry. In their years of study at divinity
college they can face a selection committee three times in all, if they
do not succeed first time round.
Failure to succeed at any of these interviews does not entitle the
applicants to the benefit of any constructive criticism. In fact they
are never told where they went wrong at all.
All the while, the earnest, diligent candidates are studying and
preaching -- it could be almost every week. In this way they are gaining
experience and the more mature candidates, with more experience of life
and the world in general, are very much in touch with grassroot Church
members.
If however the candidate fails the third interview then his hopes can
be dashed forever unless an appeal is made against the decision and he
appears before a further committee of 20 members.
Whether or not they are all qualified clergymen no-one knows because
they appear in mufti, but they have all reached the giddy heights of 121
George Street, the Church of Scotland's equivalent of the Houses of
Parliament, so are deemed capable of deciding who best to let loose on
unsuspecting congregations.
There is still no hint of criteria to be met, no encouragement, no
empathy. The inrerviewee is dealt with coldly and almost as a prisoner
in the dock who has to prove his worth to his inquisitors.
To have reached this rather demeaning stage in the process of
selection and still be able to be polite and rational deserves a medal
for tenacity, strong character, strong will, and strong stomach. Would
someone without the proper motivation have travelled so far along the
road to achieving his goal -- being called to the ministry of the Church
of Scotland?
If new blood in the form of genuinely dedicated candidates is
discouraged without explanation by unsympathetic, unfriendly,
uncommunicative selection panels, then the Church has no future, only a
self-perpetuating desire to live in the past and a seeming death wish to
hold itself aloof from the real world.
Christine Maxwell,
8 Milliken Place,
Kilbarchan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
