<HEADLINE>Cut-price purchase of green belt</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584292</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALL strength to the students of Gray's School of Art whom Clare Henry
extols (June 19). But shame on her for having believed the propaganda
that conceals the dirty deal between city councillors and Aberdeen's
newest university.
Robert Gordon University has offered to sell the old Gray's School of
Art at the city centre. In exchange the city might persuade the
Secretary of State to sacrifice green belt parkland, including part of a
designated conservation area on the River Dee.
Within yards, on a legitimate industrial site, Sainsbury's is hoping
to build beside a development proclaimed as Britain's biggest
home-improvement store -- all this on the road that funnels all traffic
from the north and west of the city into the notorious Bridge of Dee
roundabout.
But the regional roads department may not object. After all, their
next employers may be city councillors.
A ''university campus'' at Garthdee would only bring an additional
population the size of Stonehaven's. Much more important to get the
traffic off Union Street. And how nice to have a new Heritage Centre in
the old building beside the Art Gallery -- very cheap at the price of a
little congestion at the edge of town.
The former allotment holders have been quietly evicted and a block
vote by the economic development committee has pre-determined how the
planning committee should vote after the pretence of a public hearing.
The cut-price purchase of our green belt will bring Robert Gordon
University no popularity in a local community whose formerly quiet
streets have already become overspill car-parks and traffic ''rat
runs''.
Hugh Biggs,
137 Garthdee Road,
Aberdeen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Core of conflict</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584293</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Russians seem intent on going ahead with selling their Iranian
neighbours the nuclear technology consistent with developing a plant for
peaceful purposes. President Rafsanjani, the Iranian leader, said so at
the weekend, indicating that American diplomatic pressure on the
Russians spearheaded by Vice President Gore has been unavailing. The
Russians desperately need the hard currency the Iranians can provide
from their oil earnings and there is little doubt that what they will
offer will have peaceful uses. The rub is that the process involved is
bound to provide access to weapons-grade plutonium eventually, so that
even if the Iranians have only the most pacific intentions at the
moment, they are bound to be tempted to take the steps towards a nuclear
weapon capacity. Few observers would doubt that their intention is to
enjoy that opportunity.
The Americans have two motivations. In general they want to prevent
the proliferation of nuclear capacities. The case for their concern is
obvious, and will be widely shared. In particular, the Middle East is
already an unstable region, with the bitterness between Israel and some
of its neighbours, especially the most militant Islamic states,
remaining marked in spite of progress with the Palestinians. The
creation of Arab nuclear powers is bound to worry the Israelis acutely
enough for them to consider pre-emptive action, a move whose
consequences are not altogether clear. President Rafsanjani affects to
believe that any such course is unlikely since attacks might easily
involve casualties among Russian personnel who would be involved in
constructing any nuclear plant (Iran does not have the specialised
workers and scientists required).
The Israelis may not be deterred by that possibility. The chance of an
adverse Russian reaction to any pre-emptive strike will be less
important in their calculations than the chance of the Iranians
providing plutonium to other Israeli enemies, or of their using it for
nuclear warheads for delivery systems of their own purchased from the
Chinese. The Americans should redouble their efforts with the Russians
to keep tinder away from a region with so many matches waiting to be
struck.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
