<DOCNO>GH950703-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Private enterprise</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584294</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DR Elizabeth Wilson (Profits rather than well-being, June 21) forgets
that it was private enterprise which created the rail network she is
arguing it will now destroy.
Nor is it true that, presumably, rapacious private landlords, cleared
the Highlands for sheep. H H Lamb in Climate, History and the Modern
World, says: ''The physical background to . . . the history of Scotland
shows itself in the fact that the upper limit of cultivation on the
Lammermuir Hills south-east of Edinburgh, which had been as high as 425m
(nearly 1400 feet) above sea-level at one point in the mid-thirteenth
century, fell in stages until in 1600 it was 200m lower.''
Duncan Bryson,
109 Martin Avenue,
Irvine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Foreign Office inheritance</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584295</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN the debate about what happens to John Major, one of the
implications of his decision to call the contest has been neglected.
Douglas Hurd's departure from the Foreign Office was not prompted by the
Prime Minister's decision to call a leadership election, although it
affected the announcement's timing. But who inherits the Foreign Office
does depend on what happens to Mr Major. No unseasonable leadership
election would have meant that the Defence Secretary, Malcolm Rifkind,
could have inherited a job he dearly wants. Should Mr Major win hands
down, the reshuffle patronage is his to dispense without preconditions;
Mr Rifkind could still be a happy man. If Major is badly damaged, the
Foreign Office will probably have to go to somebody from the
Euro-sceptic right -- possibly the Home Secretary, Michael Howard, as
the price of survival. And if Mr Major is destroyed, we move on to round
two, and it is anybody's guess.
In a Heseltine Cabinet it ought to go to a good European, but Mr
Heseltine's victory could depend on deals struck with the Euro-sceptic
right, which is why Mr Portillo gets mentioned. The Foreign Office is
going to be increasingly important in the run-up to the 1996
intergovernmental conference, even if the timetable on economic and
monetary union continues to slip. The issue of Britain's role in Europe
will dominate political debate for the rest of the decade. While some
Prime Ministers try to do the Foreign Secretary's job themselves -- Mrs
Thatcher was always interfering -- Michael Heseltine, given his state of
health, needs a man he can trust to do things his way unwatched, not a
hostage to fortune. In a Portillo or Redwood Cabinet it would go to a
Euro-sceptic and it would be a case of fasten your seatbelts. Handbag
days are here again.
But Europe, and Yugoslavia, are not the only issues. There is a
Commonwealth Heads of Government meeting in the autumn where egos must
be massaged. Who follows Hurd matters. Malcolm Rifkind should be the
man, with Ian Lang as the preferred option, because the other
possibilities inspire little confidence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A noble legacy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584296</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AMONG the white writers and artists who struggled valiantly against
apartheid in South Africa was the theatre director Barney Simon. Simon's
death last week will be mourned far beyond theatrical circles. He earned
a world-wide reputation as an opponent of racism through the policies
and practice of the Market Theatre of Johannesburg, which he co-founded
and co-directed. The Market Theatre steadfastly opposed apartheid,
insisting there should be no discrimination either on stage or in the
auditorium, and that the repertory should continue to raise political
issues however unpopular with the administration. Thanks to Simon and
his colleagues, black and white, the fame of his theatre spread beyond
South Africa and the company received many invitations to appear abroad
-- resulting, for example, in appearances in Edinburgh at festival time
and currently in a visit (with Antony Sher) to Britain. Simon had the
satisfaction of seeing his work vindicated with the establishment of
Nelson Mandela's non-racial Government.
Sceptics have suggested the Market Theatre could be tolerated by an
oppressive regime only because theatre is not a mass medium; plays don't
topple governments. The theatre's function might even be interpreted as
a safety valve, a dissident institution cynically allowed to give
harmless voice to disaffection which might otherwise have found release
in more threatening ways. But ideas are dangerous to a tyrannical
regime, and theatre at best is a platform for ideas. The repression
which the playwright (later President) Vaclav Havel suffered in
communist Czechoslovakia demonstrates this, and there are many other
instances.
It is distressing that even as the barriers to freedom of expression
fall in one part of the world, intolerance and repression show no sign
of easing elsewhere; indeed, from Africa and South America to the Far
East, the reverse may be true. The case of the writer Salman Rushdie is
the most glaring example -- recently back in the headlines when hopes of
a release from the Ayatollah's fatwa were cruelly dashed. Rushdie
survives. The Bangladeshi feminist writer Taslima Nasreen flees. Others
die in the cause of free speech. To be a writer of independent mind in
Algeria is carte blanche for murder. Barney Simon's legacy is a noble
one, but far from comforting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
