<HEADLINE>Old school instincts keep forgotten history afloat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JACK WEBSTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>BOOK REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584297</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS YOU roll along on the conveyor-belt of a career, one of the
bewildering facts of life is that you run out of colleagues who have
shared your experience. I find myself raising the names of newspaper
characters from the past -- and encountering blank expressions from
those who have never heard of them.
''It was before my time,'' they say. So with a sigh of resignation I
must now accept that those who were around me in the 1940s are either in
retirement or have advanced to that higher point of Elysian contentment.
It was therefore all the more of a pleasure at the weekend to meet up
with one of the finest journalists of his day -- not a name widely known
to the public but a guiding hand who shaped up great newspapers and
became editor of two.
Jack Campbell takes his place in the history of Scottish journalism
for several reasons. As a youngster at Copland Road School, Glasgow,
just after the First World War, he found himself without a father -- and
with a mother left to bring up six children.
As so often in those days, there was nothing for it but to get out and
work. In 1928, at the age of 15, he turned up at this same Albion Street
building where I sit now, to become the very first copyboy and start a
newspaper adventure.
The Scots-bred Lord Beaverbrook had turned a tobacco factory into a
modern centre of journalism, home of his new Scottish Daily Express --
and to my knowledge Jack Campbell is the last survivor of that original
staff.
Within a year, the quiet, bright lad had become the paper's first cub
reporter. By 21 he was night news editor of the Express, a progress
interrupted only by the war, in which he was to be found in command of a
deep-sea rescue tug in the Atlantic.
His post-war story was a predictable one which took him to the
editorship of those other Beaverbrook enterprises, the Evening Citizen
and the Scottish Sunday Express.
And when he retired in 1978, he took a freelancing role in which he
edited the company newspaper of the great Christian Salvesen
organisation, founded by that Norwegian gent who came to Scotland and
established himself in whaling and with a fleet of merchant ships.
In that role, Jack Campbell came across a mystery which he set out to
solve -- and it was in that connection we met up the other day.
Among the models and pictures of ships, he found a Salvesen trawler
called Fairtry, which intrigued him. Although of post-war origin, it had
already slipped into oblivion. Yet, if it was as significant as Jack
Campbell believed, there was a story here to be dug up and recorded. His
newspaper instincts blazed into action.
The story was, indeed, a fascinating one. It began with a quite
remarkable inventor, Sir Dennis Burney, who had worked with ICI at
Ardeer during the war, developing secret weapons.
Before that, however, he was the man who had gone into partnership
with Vickers to build the famous R100 airship (the one which didn't
crash!). He then produced a streamlined car, which he also named the
R100 -- with its engine at the back. Was the man mad?
The Germans didn't think so, and it was left to them to mass produce a
smaller version under the name of the Volkswagen Beetle.
Such is the fate of inventors. Although his father had been Jellicoe's
second-in-command at the battle of Jutland, Burney had no connection
with fishing, except that his observation told him the industry was not
as efficient as it should be.
He thought he could change the face of it. And his proposal was to
send out a purpose-built trawler, fishing from the stern, which would
travel to grounds, catch, fillet, pack and freeze the fish and bring it
home to sell in the big stores.
There was little support for the idea. But Captain Harold Salvesen,
like Burney unconnected with the fishing industry, decided to gamble
that the inventor was right.
He backed the idea, had this stern-trawling factory ship built at
Lewis's yard in Aberdeen in 1953, and chose the name Fairtry, which had
a hint of daring adventure about it.
If there was resistance at home, the Russians were soon spying on
Fairtry -- and copying it. For good or ill, this forgotten ship had
certainly changed the shape of the industry. Among the side issues of a
remarkable tale, we learned how it came to introduce the name of
fish-fingers into our vocabulary, sparking off the massive frozen-food
industry we know today.
Jack Campbell had rescued a piece of modern industrial history which,
like so much of our heritage, was being allowed to slip down the drain
to oblivion. The man who started as a newspaper copyboy 67 years ago had
never written a book. But he couldn't avoid this one.
At 82, that's what he has done -- and appropriately, it was down by
the port of Leith, scene of the Salvesen origins, that The Fairtry
Experiment was launched. It bears all the immaculate research of a fine
journalist, complete with grammar and punctuation of the model variety.
* The Fairtry Experiment, from B+W Publishing at #7.99.
</TEXT>
