<TEXT>
Meanwhile, Cardinal Basil Hume yesterday reassured Catholics that
priests would retain their vows of celibacy.
The pledge, by the leader of Catholics in England and Wales, follows
Vatican approval for the ordination of former Anglican clergy.
In a letter read at masses, Cardinal Hume acknowledged the presence of
married priests in parishes raised a number of ''important and
sensitive'' issues. But he stressed it was not a step toward allowing
all priests to wed.
''The permission being given for the ordination of these married men
are by way of exception,'' he said. ''They will be given personally by
the Holy Father. These permissions do not change the general rule of the
Catholic Church, that priests must be celibate.''
The Catholic Church has been forced to consider the matter in the
light of the number of Anglican priests leaving the Church of England
over the ordination of women.
Cardinal Hume said priesthood would not be ''demeaned'' by the fact
that a priest could also be a husband and father.
</TEXT>
