<HEADLINE>Landslide for Labour that crushed Churchill</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BUTLER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584299</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
David Butler records how a shock defeat by Attlee at the polls 50
years ago robbed Winston Churchill of a peace-time victory that had
seemed assured
FIFTY years ago this week -- on July 5, 1945 -- Britain went to the
polls for the first General Election in 10 years.
It was high summer; the European war was at last over. Winston
Churchill, the victorious Prime Minister, has failed to persuade Labour
to continue the wartime coalition but his new ''caretaker'' government
was sailing to victory -- or so everyone thought.
The campaign had been vigorous, a reaction to the silent years of the
wartime party truce. Churchill drew vast crowds to his rallies but the
cheers were for the leader in war rather than for the leader of the
Conservative Party. Everywhere meetings were crowded and there was busy
canvassing.
In an old-fashioned pursuit of neutrality the BBC did not report the
election campaign in its news bulletins, but 10 half-hour broadcasts
were given to Conservative and 10 to Labour. Churchill gave four of
those for his party and one of them, in which he suggested that a Labour
victory would lead to a socialist Gestapo, was generally reckoned an own
goal.
The quiet Clement Attlee coolly dismissed the suggestion that he would
be at the mercy of the Labour Party executive and its over-assertive
chairman, Professor Laski. He focused on the theme that planning had won
the war and was needed to win the peace. The Conservatives displayed
posters of Churchill with the slogan ''Help him to finish the job''.
It was the first General Election to be held in June or July in this
century and it was unusual in other respects. In 19 seats, where a whole
town was away on a Wakes Week holiday, the vote was postponed for a
week. Nationwide the counting of ballots had to wait until July 26 for
postal ballots to come in from servicemen around the world.
On the day of the vote the News Chronicle published the first Gallup
poll election prediction ever made in Britain. No-one believed its
almost accurate finding of a Labour lead of 6%. A week later the Daily
Express had a headline: ''Experts tell Churchill 'You are in'.''
But on the morning of July 26, two hours into the count, the first BBC
flash reported that Labour had won 100 seats and the Conservatives 24.
By the end of the afternoon one of the greatest electoral landslides was
there for all to see. As a surprise outcome, its only rivals came much
later, in 1970 and in February 1974.
In 1935 the National Government won 432 seats and a clear majority of
249. Now Labour won 394 seats and a clear majority of 148 -- 226 seats
had changed hands. The 12% nationwide swing in votes was the largest
ever recorded in a British General Election. (It is noteworthy that
since 1945 the largest swing in a General Election has been 5%).
Five Ministers in the caretaker Cabinet lost their seats, including
the rising Harold Macmillan, the veteran Leo Army, and the Churchill
loyalist Brendan Bracken. Sir Archibald Sinclair was beaten in Caithness
in the narrowest of three-cornered races, and Dr McIntyre, the first
ever SNP member, lost Motherwell which he had just won in a by-election.
Notable among the 15 seats that changed hands in Scotland was Lanark
where Lord Dunglass (now Lord Home) was defeated. But Scotland swung
less than the rest of the country. In Glasgow the movement was merely a
2.5% swing with only one seat changing hands (Walter Elliott lost
Kelvingrove by 88 votes on a 0.2% swing). In Birmingham there was a 12%
swing and 9 seats out of 13 switched from Conservative to Labour.
Labour's English victory was in the most unlikely places -- prosperous
suburbs and traditional naval ports, as well as Eton, Cambridge, Harrow,
and Winchester.
And a new generation of politicians swept in -- Hugh Gaitskell, Harold
Wilson, Michael Foot, Barbara Castle and Hartley Shawcross. Others who
stood and lost were to come in five years later -- Roy Jenkins, Denis
Healey, Jo Grimond, Reggie Maudling and Iain Macleod (who vainly
contested his ancestral Western Isles).
On July 25 Roosevelt and Stalin agreed to suspend the Potsdam
conference for a day to allow the British politicians to go home for the
election results. It was a world-wide shock when Clement Attlee returned
alone to speak for Britain in place of Winston Churchill.
Labour has won only two General Elections with a working majority;
1945 was a much bigger victory than 1966 and the 1945-50 parliament left
a much bigger mark on British history than 1966-70.
Of course, if current opinion polls are to be believed, Labour now
stands ready to win an even greater victory. But 1997 is still a long
way off.
* Dr David Butler is a fellow of Nuffield College, Oxford and
Britain's leading electoral historian.
* Clement Attlee
</TEXT>
