<HEADLINE>Diplomats on last round of cocktails?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584300</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
William Russell considers whether in the age of satellite
communications and jet travel there is any need for Britain to maintain
a diplomatic corp around the world
WHAT do diplomats do? Hold birthday parties for the Queen, attend
cocktail parties, levees and balls, live in the lap of luxury in
splendid town houses in foreign capitals waited upon by liveried
servants, sip the odd Bucks fizz and nibble a canape while they compose
elegantly phrased telegrams containing the odd Latin or Greek phrase to
the Foreign Office about the local situation?
At times it looks like it, because there is no denying some of our
overseas embassies are housed in extremely grand buildings, occasional
posh parties are held in them, and there are ambassadors with toffee
noses, not to mention their wives. If the monarchy, Parliament, the
church -- those bastions of the Establishment -- come under fire today,
so too has that other pillar of the Old Boy network, the Diplomatic
Service. Does it deserve to?
Although to some extent the Foreign Office still is a home away from
home for the boys from the playing fields, the service is far more
democratic than the impression it gives.
Admittedly many diplomats do come from Oxford and Cambridge -- 73% of
last year's entrants did, which was in line with the number of Oxbridge
applicants -- but FO recruitment teams had targeted 23 universities from
Aberdeen to Brighton seeking recruits. The commitment was to choosing
the best.
But does the service have any place in a world rapidly turning into a
global village? Can much that it does not be done by fax? Do we need
reports from far-flung capitals when there are satellites, telephones
and computer links to make instant contact feasible?
One after-effect of the end of the cold war is that the secrecy which
was necessary for diplomatic dealings has been lessened. There can be
more openness. The problem is that people brought up to be discreet find
the change difficult. If one's career is founded on a nod, a wink and a
hint, rather than plain speaking it is difficult to speak plainly. It
has to be learnt.
Sir John Coles, Foreign Office permanent under-secretary, tried a
little plain speaking during a speech in Oxford when he tackled the
image problems facing the service. For a start, the cost of Britain's
entire diplomatic effort, including the World Service, the British
Council and peacekeeping, is #1300m, which is less than 60% of the
budget for West Midlands District Council. Or, to put it in another
context, roughly what we spend annually on buying jeans. It hardly adds
up to high spending worthy of a once great, imperial power, and if you
exclude all the extraneous things like our contributions to the UN,
Nato, the council of Europe, scholarships for overseas students and
military training, then the annual cost of the FO, at home and abroad,
is #650m.
What does that pay for? Some 215 diplomatic posts in 183 countries
staffed by 2530 diplomats from Britain and 7400 locally engaged staff.
As for those grand houses, there are only 25 which merit that
description and they are in capitals where, if one is to swim with the
big fish, one needs a decent pool. It is a tiny number out of some 3000
homes for foreign office staff around the world, and they are, Sir John
argued, ''a good tool to promote Britain''.
In fact, promoting Britain takes up a large part of a diplomat's time,
and while it is possible to argue that this could be done by civil
servants from the Department of Trade and Industry, they suffer from the
disadvantage of being home based. They would only be occasional
visitors. The diplomat is on the spot, and if trade and industry is his
special remit then he is in contact with the right people. Sir John
cited one of the grander expensive establishments, the Paris embassy --
cost #12.76m a year -- to demonstrate the job being done.
Paris arranges and staffs high-level visits to France -- more than 200
a year by politicians, businessmen, and others representing British
interests, Sir John said. Last year British exports to France, our third
biggest market, were worth #13.5bn. Commercial staff made more than 2000
visits to French companies and gave support to hundreds of British
companies at trade fairs, and the embassy helped Cable and Wireless
secure the licence for a new mobile phone network, and Forte fight off a
takeover battle for the Meridian Hotel chain. He believed that the
support offered to exporters could sometimes tip the balance between a
contract won or lost.
In addition, more than 10,000,000 Britons visit France each year, and
some 60,000 live there permanently. Their interests have to be looked
after. Last year some 14,500 Britons in distress were helped, and 11,000
passport problems solved. But those are the domestic things. France is
one of the major players in the Bosnian crisis, just as we are, and the
embassy is a vital channel of communication, and a look-out post. As
well as keeping in contact with French officials, it also watches how
French public opinion is reacting to events, something one cannot do
over the telephone, and not something one can learn from watching
satellite news.
There is much more -- from hostage situations, rebellions in which
Britons need to be evacuated, accidents, robberies, and assaults. The
consular service, one arm of the diplomatic set-up, is there to help.
As to whether there could be a world without diplomats, Sir John
believed he would not live to see it. It would have to be a world with
no conflicts to prevent, no political tensions to resolve, be free of
the menace of drugs, white-collar crime, money laundering and terrorism.
It would be a world in which British nationals never ended up in trouble
or in prison abroad, where British firms required no assistance to help
them export, and nobody needed overseas aid.
That world was not on offer.
</TEXT>
