<HEADLINE>Road protesters take to the superhighway</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANNE JOHNSTONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584301</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The anti-roads protest movement has come a long way from the days of
isolated 'angry young men' chained to bulldozers to co-ordinated action
via the information superhighway. But where does it go from here? Anne
Johnstone investigates
IN a recent Gallup poll 62% of respondents said they supported
protesters who broke the law while disrupting motorway building. Last
month Emma Must of Alarm UK, an umbrella group of nearly 300 anti-road
campaign groups, won the prestigious #48,000 Goldman environmental
prize, which honours grassroots environmentalists.
Last week more than 40 local campaign groups, along with Alarm UK and
Friends of the Earth, joined together to protest against the creation
''by stealth'' of a Folkstone to Honiton south-coast highway, under the
guise of a mass of by-pass and road upgrading schemes.
What a long way it is from the naive bunch of tousled-haired
protesters who took on the Department of Transport over the M3 extension
outside Winchester, symbol of Government eco-insensitivity. That was
only three years ago. The media, and not just the tabloids, continue to
caricature the anti-roads movement in terms of dreadlocked youths
chaining themselves to bulldozers and swinging around the treetops.
''Nobody wanted to take a picture of me. I look too ordinary,'' says
Ian Cowan, without rancour. Cowan is a 33-year-old languages graduate
who works for Glasgow for People. Articulate, cheerful, quietly spoken,
he is the pressure group's only paid employee, earning #8000 a year.
Despite the failure of the battle to halt the M77, Cowan realises that
groups like his are gradually winning the war. ''It's obvious to anyone
that there are too many cars. I don't think our message is far away from
being universally accepted.''
Lesley Boulton has just turned 50 and belongs to a number of
environmental groups, including Earth First!, the direct action group
which has stolen much of the media show at Pollok Free State. She laughs
at the way the group has been characterised as wild and woolly ''angry
young men''.
Boulton describes her background as ''classically bourgeois''. She
went to boarding school and art school, and took a degree in archaeology
and classics. Tree houses? ''I wouldn't mind living in a tree house if I
could be linked up to the Internet, and so long as there was lots of hot
water!''
Like many of those in the counter-culture, she's enthusiatic about new
technology as an easy and convenient way of networking and can't imagine
life without her computer and fax machine.
Organisations like Road Alert have sprung up to service needs like
hers. Originating at Twyford Down, it has developed into a network of
road protesters who publish a fortnightly bulletin, providing up-to-date
information about all the latest anti-roads protests. It goes out by
mail, fax and e-mail to subscribers, many of whom process it on to
hundreds of others. A spokesman said it was impossible to estimate how
many people saw it.
Another sort of cross-fertilisation in the movement is typified by
Smallworld Video, based in Oxford. A non-profit-making organisation, it
teaches protesters to use camcorders, and distributes films of previous
roads protests. This enables small, local groups to learn from similar
campaigns elsewhere -- DIY activism.
John Stewart of Alarm UK, says: ''Local groups are beginning to come
together in a more structured way because they realise they can put more
strategic pressure on the authorities that way.'' The south coast
highway protest is just the latest example.
Stewart detects two distinct strands within the current roads
movement: ''First there are traditional residents' associations and
small-town groups. Their protest about a road scheme may start off as a
NIMBY movement (''Not In My Back Yard'') but as they become more
informed, and join in with other groups, they develop wider objectives.
''Then there are the young people who believe in direct action. They
are activists who have grown up under a pretty right-wing Government.
They feel excluded from mainstream politics. They are like two circles,
and occasionally they cross each other.
''Earth First! supporters are very different from those fighting the
Hastings by-pass. But because until recently the Government's roads
programme has been so horrendous, everyone has been moving in the same
direction. The reason why the Government has come under such pressure is
that they haven't been able to marginalise the Earth First! types.
Instead, these protesters have had a lot of tacit and some active
support.''
This remarkable alliance between the radicals and legions of county
ladies is typified by Lady Bullock, who when confronted with the
prospect of another road through Oxford, declared: ''If this goes ahead
I will sit down in front of the bulldozer.''
Although road schemes are still going ahead, few doubt that the
protesters are winning the public relations war hands down. The notion
that more roads generate more traffic, once dismissed as radical
nonsense, is now almost universally accepted, and formed one of the key
conclusions of the Royal Commission's report on pollution. Faced with
massive opposition, not from shaggy youths denied their social security
benefits, but voters, many of them former Tory voters, the Government is
rapidly scaling down its roads programme. So where does the roads
movement go from here?
For a long time respected lobby groups such as Transport 2000 have
concentrated on suggesting positive alternatives to current policy.
Smaller local groups like Glasgow for People are now trying to go the
same way. Their Alternative Strategy to the Ayr Road Route was part
funded by the Scottish Wildlife Trust and Friends of the Earth. They
will continue to run campaigns. Next will be the M74 extension and after
that probably the M80 link through Strathkelvin. But with local and
national government quickly donning green clothes in their transport
policies, local protest groups have to adopt new roles and stategies.
''We'll keep highlighting their record and look at whether they are
putting their money where their mouths are,'' says Ian Cowan.
</TEXT>
