<HEADLINE>Street wise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEVE MCGRAIL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>977584302</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WITH the summer here, Scotland's towns are once more alive with
soldiers, wastrels and strumpets -- and with ghosts, hangmen and the odd
Mary, Queen of Scots. It is street theatre time, as the country's past
is acted out in a welter of Heritage Events, Living History and Ghost
Walks.
Street theatre has grown in popularity over a decade. Unlike
traditional theatre, the streets do not offer the security of reliable
lighting, controlled temperature and a distant audience. Street theatre
is raw and immediate -- and potentially unforgiving if things go wrong.
Nowhere is this more true than with the costumes.
A new breed of costumier has emerged to provide for open-air drama.
One of these is Sandra Morton, based in Stirling. A freelance, she
contracts to the Stirling Heritage Events Company, whose performances
range from Fort George to Ayr. ''It's not like ordinary theatre,'' she
says.
''Our actors are in among the audience. Costumes have to look
authentic close up. People notice things. Take machine stitching; it
simply looks wrong, so I try to hide it with braid where possible. Hand
stitching looks best but it's too slow. Whatever happens, seams need to
be strong. You can't have clothes held together with safety pins as you
can on stage.''
Weather, of course, is a big problem. Costumes must be neither too hot
nor too cold. Above all, they have to be able to survive a soaking.
Certain fabrics are definitely out. Velvet blotches horribly in rain,
and wool poses obvious difficulties. Once, Morton made Redcoat uniforms
out of woollen cloth, lining them with calico for stiffness in the
authentic manner. ''They looked wonderful,'' she smiles wryly, ''until
the sun shone and the actors just melted. You learn the hard way
sometimes.''
Finding the right cloth is crucial. For a start, it has to be tough.
Early on, the Events Company employed ordinary theatrical costumiers and
David Kinnaird, their events manager, recalls getting some men's coats
made of pressed felt. ''After one wearing they were like pobbly old
jumpers. That's why we turned to Sandra, who really understands the
properties of materials.''
Again, fabrics must look genuine without being too expensive. For
brocade waistcoats, for example, Morton uses upholstery material.
Needlecord makes a tolerable velvet substitute, and as it moves well,
actors like it. The most exotic fabrics, not surprisingly, cause the
most trouble.
Just now she is costuming for the Dundee Living History, which
portrays preparations for Captain Scott's Antarctic voyage. Able Seaman
Lashly's uniform is seemingly causing headaches. ''The old photos are
black and white,'' she frets. ''I'm guessing that the uniform was navy,
although I'm told his kerchief was pale blue. I hope it's right.''
Actor Rab Buchanan, playing the Able Seaman, is less concerned about
accuracy and wants to know what to do with the ''woggle thing'' around
his neck. Through a mouthful of pins, Morton makes a terse suggestion .
. . This advice was surely never in the script -- but maybe it is a
costumier's privilege to offer it at times like these.
</TEXT>
