<HEADLINE>Silently waiting in the wings</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANVAR KHAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584303</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Pop superstar George Michael is in self-imposed exile after the well
publicised fall-out with record company Sony. Anvar Khan reports the
successful artist is taking steps to break his vow of silence and
eventually go it alone
I have no control or say in the way that my work is exploited
IN the 1980s, George Michael, the frankly hirsute member of Wham!, was
one of the biggest pop stars in the world. There are different calibres
of silence; moody, recalcitrant, intimidating, monastic and vengeful.
When George Michael fell out with his record company, Sony, he pled the
Fifth Amendment for five years. He refused to record another song for
them.
It was a dramatic, self-imposed exile. George Michael wrote and
produced two of the hits of the decade: Wake Me Up Before You Go Go and
Careless Whisper. If you're a success in Scotland you want to break
London, if you sell records in the UK you want to crack America. Talent
and ability become a matter of geography and association.
As a singer, Michael earned the ultimate accolade, he recorded a duet
with Aretha Franklin on the transatlantic No 1 Knew You Were Waiting. He
revelled in working with the music industry's most fearsome mamma.
Franklin is a music industry matriarch, a measure of credibility. In a
comparative version of Sir Norman Tebbit's Cricket Test, where British
Asians were invited to show their patriotism by supporting England
rather than Pakistan, George Michael took the soul test, holding his own
alongside the Queen Bee. Michael's admiration is a precious commodity,
which he lends to few, but only those he respects. He respects only
talent, and most of all he respects his own.
When he broke up with Wham! partner and long-term friend Andrew
Ridgeley, his first solo album, Faith, included four US No 1 singles. It
became the biggest selling album of 1988 in the US, and won him the
prestigious Ivor Novello Songwriting Award -- and a personal fortune of
about #80m. To understand why Michael decided to take on Sony, in the
face of such fame and riches, it's necessary to go back a few years.
In the seventies Sony launched the Betamax video. Although generally
recognised as a superior product, Betamax lost out to the VHS system
because Sony didn't own enough films to release on compatible tapes. The
company then vowed it would never develop a new electronic product
without owning the software as well. When it dawned there was going to
be a battle to succeed the compact disc, between Sony's Digital Audio
Tape and Philips' Digital Compact Cassette, the Japanese giant paid
$2000m for CBS Records which also had Michael Jackson, Bob Dylan, Bruce
Springsteen and Barbra Streisand on its books. It was to this episode in
Sony's career that George Michael later referred to in court, by saying
he was tired of ''being treated like little more than software''.
His complaints against Sony were, like the key players in the music
industry, major but few. While Faith sold 14,000,000 copies, the
precociously titled Listen Without Prejudice, sold 6,000,000. Sony
justified the poor sales by saying that Michael had refused to do any
promotional videos. Michael returned that Sony couldn't be bothered
pushing the album properly. They were embroiled in a tit-for-tat
argument. Neither party sought a compromise.
When they bought CBS, Sony inherited a pop star who was getting on a
bit in terms of self-expression. Dance routines were no longer important
to him. Michael wanted his day as a party boy to be a mere 24-hours in
history. He wanted the gravitas of an elder statesman. His sexual image
had to go.
Watching people become serious about themselves is a spectator sport.
They change the way they look, as if we're a nation of window-shoppers.
The catalogue of naff attempts presently includes Celtic manager Tommy
Burns in round, professorial spectacles; Carol Smillie swapping
wedding-cake dresses for jeans; Sam Fox, after breast reduction, in a
smaller bra. Accessorise for an instant brain injection, why don't you.
Michael's prime contention was that Sony treated him as a product
rather than an artist, which is the superstar equivalent of ''I am not a
number'' and ''My wife doesn't understand me''. Let's face it, they
probably didn't. Matters with Sony evenually came to a crisis point when
the singer accused them of failing to handle his work for an Aids
charity correctly. His cause was human, people before business. But he
was expecting Sony to do the PR for his social work.
Michael intended that his stance against Sony be interpreted as
standing up against the bullies. The court case was intended to
illustrate a fault in the way artists are treated in the music industry.
Michael attacked the long-term written contract. He was effectively
minced in the press for his complaint that his was a position of
''professional slavery''.
Artists, the self-proclaimed sensitive ones, anchor themselves to
impersonal business to become as famous as they want. Their work is the
product, not themselves. But somehow Michael believed that Sony had
stepped over that fine line. Artists need a ringmaster. Michael,
however, was originally signed up in 1982 when he was on the dole. He
does discipline the way other pop stars do drugs.
During the court case in 1994, it became apparent that Michael's views
of Sony's attitude, motives and competence derived less from first-hand
experience than from reports to him by his advisers, particularly his
manager Rob Kahane. Despite his concerns about the promotion of the
album Listen Without Prejudice, Michael never sought a meeting with the
relevant Sony executives.
Like the Aids-ribbon frequently on his lapel, publicising support for
an infection which still doesn't kill as many people as heart disease,
Michael seems to lack perspective. The judge said he could not help
feeling, that if Sony had seen more of the star rather than less of Mr
Kahane, events might have turned out differently.
As it was, George Michael told the company he wanted to be released
from his contract of six albums by 2003. He took a vow of silence which
meant immediate anonymity. His attempt to escape from his recording
contract was finally rejected by the High Court. The episode cost him
#3m. ''Even though I both created and paid for my work, I will never own
it or have any rights over it. I have no control or say in the way that
my work is exploited'', he said at the time, explaining that there was
no such thing as resignation for an artist in the music industry.
''Effectively, you sign a piece of paper at the beginning of your
career and you are expected to live with that decision, good or bad, for
the rest of your professional life.''
Sony is like any huge company which trades on artists. The talented,
high-earners subsidise the wage-slaves, their glamour justifies the
endless mediocrity. In signing with Virgin and Dreamworks SKG, Michael
has forgone the globally powerful Japanese for the best of American and
British business talent. In short, one self-made musician signs with
four entrepreneurs. It is significant.
He has left working for the company behind, to deal with people who
make commercial ''products'' as artists of a kind, whether it be films
or aeroplane rides. Stephen Spielberg, ex-Disney boss Jeffrey
Katzenberg, and Richard Branson all made it on their own too, on the
strength of the work they knew was good enough to make money, and they
all had the integrity of imagination. The pop star has awarded his
custom to men whose credentials he respects. It makes sense that George
Michael would trust fellow strugglers more.
</TEXT>
