<HEADLINE>Oil slick leaks from locked cargo ships</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584311</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
New Orleans, Sunday
TWO cargo ships which collided in the Gulf of Mexico have created a
15-mile fuel slick as they have been drifting, locked together, in an
area studded with petroleum rigs.
The US Coast Guard did not want to pull the ships apart because one of
them, the Enif, could sink, said Petty Officer Tyler Johnson.
''It appears as if one of the ships is holding the other up,'' he
said. ''Our biggest concern is that the wreckage might drift into some
of the oil platforms.''
Tugs were brought in to stop the drift.
The Greek-flagged 750ft Alexia apparently rammed the Enif, out of
Singapore, on its port side. The Alexia was empty, while the 514ft Enif
was loaded with 1500 tons of steel.
No-one was hurt in the crash yesterday, about 70 miles south of New
Orleans. The cause of the collision was not immediately known.
Most of the Enif's crew was evacuated, as were nearby oil rigs. All 32
members of the Alexia's crew remained on board, and its engines were
used to control the drift away from an oil rig.
About 10,000 gallons of fuel leaked from the Enif, Coast Guard Captain
Gordon Marsh said. The Alexia's fuel was not leaking.--AP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>36 Japanese ill after new subway gas alert</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TERUAKI UENO</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584312</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Tokyo, Sunday
AT least 36 people were taken to hospital after being overcome by
mystery fumes at a subway station in the port city of Yokohama today,
creating new poison gas worries for Japan.
The incident happened at Kamioka Station, 20 miles west of Tokyo, at
about 3pm (0600 GMT), a spokesman for the local fire department said.
All the victims were complaining of sore throats and pain in the eyes
but were not in a serious condition, the spokesman said. No specific
cause had been identified.
A police spokesman said no suspicious objects or materials had been
found.
Kyodo news agency said police closed an eight-storey department store
with two basements leading to an underground passage just outside the
station.
It quoted an employee at a supermarket in the basement as saying:
''There was no odour, but I suddenly felt pain in my throat and later my
eyes started to hurt.''
The police spokesman declined to speculate on whether the latest
incident was linked to the doomsday cult accused of involvement in the
March 20 sarin nerve gas attack on Tokyo subways that killed 11 people
and made 5500 ill.
''At present, we can't say whether Aum Shinri Kyo (Supreme Truth Sect)
was responsible for the incident,'' the spokesman said.
An Aum spokeswoman refused to comment on today's incident.
Cult leader Shoko Asahara and several top followers face murder and
attempted murder charges in connection with the Tokyo subway attack.
Since the March 20 attack, there have been incidents similar to that
in Yokohama, with people complaining of sore throats and burning eyes.
None has been firmly pinned to the sect.
On May 5, an apparent cyanide gas attack was thwarted at Tokyo's
busiest underground railway station, Shinjuku.
The cult was suspected of involvement in another sarin attack in a
mountain resort city last year, as well as the attempted assassination
of Japan's police chief on March 30. It has denied the allegations.
On Friday, Japanese authorities began formal moves aimed at disbanding
the cult.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000135</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000135</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Four miners perish as South African fire team is trapped</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID TUCKER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584313</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Johannesburg, Sunday
FOUR miners killed by a fire more than a mile beneath the surface of a
South African goldmine died in a failed bid to rescue two colleagues
trapped behind a curtain of smoke, officials said today.
The fire at Gencor Ltd's St Helena mine, near the Free State town of
Welkom, had been isolated by early tonight and 100 miners were due to
resume work on the night shift at the Number Four shaft, about 2[1/2]
miles from the shaft where the fire started, they said.
Four of the miners died after running back through thick smoke to warn
colleagues further down an incline at the pit's Number Two shaft. The
men, and the two men they tried to save, were overcome as they tried to
get back above the smoke wall.
''The heroism and the selflessness of the . . . miners who ran back
through the smoke to warn their fellow workers serves as an inspiring
example to us all,'' Mineral and Energy Affairs Minister Pik Botha said
in a statement.
Andrew Davidson, spokesman for Gencor's mining division Gengold, told
Reuters the fire broke out in a disused stope about 5250ft underground
at the mine 150 miles southwest of Johannesburg.
He said four fire-fighting teams had sealed off the blaze site in the
shaft, which produced high-grade ore.
''The fire at Number Two shaft has been isolated . . . teams have
created a chimney within the mine so that the smoke can be channelled
out,'' he added.
''Some 100 workers will resume duty with the night shift this evening
at Number Four shaft which is . . . served with a separate ventilation
system,'' he said, adding that he did not have estimates of lost
production.
In the first three months of this year, the St Helena mine produced
3300lb of gold, making it the fifth largest producer out of Gengold's 10
mines.
Botha said the government was doing all it could to bring new mine
safety measures into force with the greatest urgency.
''We are striving to meet the risks inherent in mining with the most
effective safety measures that are humanly possible,'' Botha said in his
statement.
The accident is the latest in a series to hit South Africa's mining
industry, the mainstay of the country's economy.
On May 10, 104 miners were killed when an underground locomotive
plunged down Anglo American's Vaal Reefs gold mine shaft number two,
near the town of Orkney, crushing the lift cage carrying the men to
their night shift.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Israel and PLO fail on accord</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WAFA AMR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584314</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Erez, Gaza Strip, Sunday
THE PLO and Israel failed in marathon talks today to clinch an accord
on widening Palestinian self-rule but both sides said agreement was
still possible.
Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres and PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat
spent the night on the border between Israel and PLO-ruled Gaza in an
attempt to meet their July 1 deadline for agreement on pulling back
Israeli troops from West Bank towns and villages.
''The night was not long enough,'' Peres told reporters. ''We did not
reach yet an agreement.''
A spokeswoman for Peres said he would meet Arafat again tomorrow or
Tuesday.
The missed deadline, one of many, was likely to increase tension in
the West Bank, where violent protests have erupted in the last week over
the release of Palestinian prisoners.
Peres and Arafat emerged looking haggard but with no evident animosity
between them after more than eight hours of talks which did not produce
even a joint statement.
A US official familiar with details of the talks said the next target
date for an accord was July 17.
Troop redeployment and elections for a Palestinian Council, envisaged
in the 1993 Israel-PLO peace deal that established Palestinian self-rule
in Gaza and the West Bank enclave of Jericho, are already a year behind
schedule.
After the weekly cabinet meeting in Jerusalem today Israeli ministers
said that the talks were not in crisis.
''This isn't a crisis now but rather the last part of climb up a
mountain,'' negotiator and Environment Minister Yossi Sarid said. ''That
part, as you know, is always the steepest.''
PLO officials said the differences centred on security arrangements
after Israeli troops redeploy in the West Bank, home to one million
Palestinians and 100,000 Jewish settlers.
''What Israel is trying to do,'' said one PLO negotiator, ''is to
restrict the movements and deployment of the Palestinian police, and to
divide the West Bank in an attempt to avoid the establishment of a
Palestinian state at the end of the process.''
Israel rejected PLO demands to control security in villages and
refugee camps near Jewish settlements. It also opposed joint
Israeli-Palestinian patrols on roads to settlements, Israeli officials
said.
Arafat wants redeployment over two months from all major West Bank
towns, including Hebron which would have special security arrangements.
Redeployment would start four weeks after an agreement was signed. This
first phase would be completed 21 days before Palestinians elections.
PLO officials said Israel had agreed to pull back from major towns
although Ramallah and Bethlehem, both near Jerusalem, would not be
handed over fully until the completion of by-pass roads for settlers.
Peres said the talks were very complicated for both sides and he said
''some gaps'' remained. He refused to speculate when an agreement would
be signed.
* At least 19 people suffered from smoke inhalation as a huge fire
raged outside of Jerusalem today, whipped up by high winds, medical
officials said.
The flames spread quickly towards Jerusalem. The western outskirts of
the city were inundated with the smell of burning wood and ashes drifted
down onto the city's streets.
--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000137</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000137</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Seoul store rescue ends in grief</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>YEOM YOON-JEONG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584315</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Seoul, Sunday
A 22-YEAR-OLD woman rescued today from the wreckage of a Seoul
department store four days after it collapsed died later in hospital,
dimming hopes of finding other survivors in the debris.
Hospital officials said Lee Eun-young's injuries were too serious to
save her. She was pulled from the wreckage of the five-storey Sampoong
Department Store on a stretcher, bleeding and exhausted with an oxygen
mask strapped to her face.
''It was very difficult to get her out. The space down there was too
narrow, too hot and full of gas,'' said rescue official Kim Wol-sil.
''The rescue took longer (than anticipated) as we had to cut through
the steel bars and widen the hole to take her out,'' he said.
She was the first person found alive today, after 24 were saved
yesterday. Her death took the official toll to 104, with 347 still
missing. Some rescue officials said they were resigned to the final
tally soaring beyond the 300 mark.
Lee's cousin Kwon Eun-jong, who was rescued on Friday, had urged
rescuers to dig through a supermarket area in the basement of the
building to search for her after rescue work was suspended for safety
reasons.
Rescue officials earlier said their greatest hope was signs of life in
a basement food outlet where up to 30 people may still be clinging to
life.
''The survivors are believed to be trapped in a Wendy's hamburger
restaurant,'' a rescue official told MBC television.
There were signs today that pent-up grief was turning to anger for
relatives waiting at the site in southern Seoul to hear of the fate of
loved ones missing in the debris.
Around 500 relatives scuffled with riot police after safety officials
ruled the wreckage unsafe, saying an elevator tower left standing when
the store collapsed on Thursday was beginning to tilt dangerously.
But early today the rescuers were allowed to resume the search for
survivors.
Preliminary investigation teams have blamed the collapse on shoddy
construction and negligence.
Prosecutors have charged the founder and president of the store and
two other executives for failing to order an evacuation although aware
of structural problems.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Briton 'faces gallows'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584316</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Singapore, Sunday
A BRITON alleged to have murdered and mutilated his tourist victims
said in jail here this weekend that he was coming to terms with the fact
he will face the gallows.
John Scripps, 34, who admitted avoiding justice throughout a 20-year
life of crime, said: ''Whatever happens to me now is in the hands of
God. I know that Singaporeans are calling for death.''
Scripps has already asked for a Catholic priest after admitting he
killed South African Gerard Lowe whose dismembered body was found in
Singapore harbour last March.
He will be remanded in court again on Tuesday.
Scripps, 34, of Hertford, admitted in Taneh Merah Prison he had killed
engineer Gerard Lowe, 28.
Scripps says he will plead guilty to manslaughter, claiming that Lowe,
a brewery executive, had sexually assaulted him.
He has refused to talk about the murders of a Canadian mother and son
-- Sheila 45, and Darin Damude, 21 -- or about Briton Timothy McDowall,
who went missing in Mexico.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pope John Paul pays tribute to Protestants killed by Catholics</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PAUL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584317</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Kosice, Slovakia, Sunday
POPE John Paul paid tribute to Protestants killed by Catholics in the
17th century today as he made amends for perceived religious
insensitivity during his visit to Slovakia.
He spoke of ''praise and admiration'' for martyrs of all Christian
confessions after a service to confer sainthood on three Roman Catholic
priests tortured to death by Calvinist forces had alienated the minority
Slovak Evangelical churches.
Addressing the open air mass in the eastern city of Kosice, where the
three priests were killed in 1619 during the Thirty Years War, the Pope
told a huge crowd that Slovak Christians of various confessions had paid
for their faith with their lives.
He made special mention of 24 Calvinist pastors executed in the Slovak
town of Presov in 1687 by Catholic Habsburg forces, saying that the
Roman Catholic Church could not fail to acknowledge their ''spiritual
greatness''.
''To them and to all who accepted suffering and death out of fidelity
to the dictates of their conscience the Church gives praise and
expresses admiration,'' the Pope said.
He ater prayed at a monument to the 24 martyrs in Presov in an
unscheduled late addition to his four-day visit to strongly Catholic
Slovakia.
The stop, on the way to a meeting with Eastern rite Catholics in
Presov, was announced yesterday after several thousand Protestants had
gathered there to honour the 24.
They say they were upset that the Pope, who has set Christian unity a
goal of his reign, had not planned to acknowledge that Protestants as
well as Catholics died in the religious wars that swept central Europe
in the 17th century.
The Vatican denied the Pope had bowed to pressure from non-Catholics
by adding the visit to the Presov monument, saying that the idea had
come from the 75-year-old pontiff.
''He wants to help secure justice but also to heal historic wounds,''
chief spokesman Joaquin Navarro-Valls told reporters.
The Vatican was embarrassed in May when leading Czech Protestants
boycotted a meeting with the pontiff in Prague in a similar dispute over
the canonisation of a Catholic martyr.
The target then was Jan Sarkander, a Polish-born priest tortured to
death by Protestant noblemen in the 17th century.
The Pope responded at the time with an appeal to Catholics and
Protestants to forgive each other for what he called past sins and
errors on both sides.
Today's new saints were Marek Krizin, a Croat, Stefan Pongracz, a
Hungarian, and Melichar Grodziecky, from the Pope's native Poland.
Catholics from all three countries were among the crowds at the Kosice
service.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Serbs shell UN's Sarajevo headquarters. Mayor pledges battle to break the city's siege</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SEAN MAGUIRE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584318</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sarajevo, Sunday
BOSNIAN Serbs fired a mortar round at UN headquarters in Sarajevo
today and the mayor of the beleaguered capital said Bosnian government
forces would press on with an offensive to ease the Serb siege of the
city.
Three UN soldiers, including two Britons, were slightly wounded by
shrapnel when a mortar bomb exploded in trees next to the UN flagpole in
the compound. A local police guard at the United States embassy next
door was also slighty injured.
The building serves as UN peacekeeping headquarters in Bosnia and is
the residence of the UN commander in the country, Lieutenant-General
Rupert Smith of Britain.
Smith is on leave but the building was crowded with UN military and
civilian personnel when the mortar round struck.
The Bosnians said 25 people were wounded today after Serbs blasted the
city centre in intermittent attacks. On Saturday 13 people were killed
by the shelling.
Two Associated Press journalists were slightly hurt when two mortar
bombs fell near the UN compound about 45 minutes later.
Earlier in the day, French UN soldiers were targeted by a Serb heavy
machinegun as they left the city on the exposed road across Mount Igman,
a UN spokesman said.
After Bosnian Serb forces ignored a warning smoke shell, UN troops
fired two mortar rounds at the post and fire from it ceased when a round
landed within 20 yards. It was the first time UN forces used such force
near Sarajevo since deploying heavy combat weaponry after Nato air
strikes in May.
A heavy firefight broke out this afternoon around the Jewish cemetery
in the Bosnian capital with government and Bosnian Serb forces trading
machine-gun and artillery fire.
Sarajevo's mayor, meanwhile, said a Bosnian army offensive to ease the
Serbs' stranglehold was exacting a terrible price in casualties but it
represented his people's only hope. ''We will take the risk of fighting
for survival if the other option is surrender and survival,'' Mayor
Tarik Kupusovic told Reuters.
While the UN said the shelling was apparently unconnected with
offensive activity by Muslim-led forces, city dwellers were convinced
the attacks were revenge for successes by their army somewhere far from
the eyes of UN observers.
Bosnian state radio said government troops had advanced on high ground
north of the city towards the Serb-held town of Semizovac.
Mayor Kupusovic rejected the argument that the government had brought
unnecessary woes on its people, pointing out that shelling had
increased, water and power been cut off and all aid supplies blocked
before the offensive began.
In the Croatian capital Zagreb, EU peace envoy Carl Bildt said he had
discussed Serbian recognition of Bosnia with President Slobodan
Milosevic but emphasised he wanted Belgrade to do more to bring an end
to the war.--Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Crofter hurt in cliff accident</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584319</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CROFTER was flown to hospital in Inverness after falling from cliffs
in a remote part of the Highlands while going to rescue a sheep. The man
suffered head and back injuries in the accident at Reiff, by
Achiltibuie. It is believed he fell about 10ft after scrambling down the
cliffs after the animal. A major rescue operation was mounted after the
alarm was raised with police. They contacted a local doctor and an
ambulance crew also raced to the scene. Due to the remoteness of the
area and access problems the Stornoway Coastguard rescue helicopter was
also scrambled. A winchman was lowered to the casualty while the chopper
landed on a nearby island to preserve fuel. The man was then flown to
Raigmore Hospital in Inverness where the extent of his injuries were not
known last night. Police were waiting to contact the man's next-of-kin
before releasing his name.
</TEXT>
