<DOCNO>GH950703-000156</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000156</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BT's free calls plan to challenge rivals</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584334</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOCAL telephone calls could soon be free under proposals drawn up by
BT to halt the drift of customers to its rivals.
The idea, already popular in the United States, is among a series put
to industry watchdog Oftel.
Subscribers opting for free calls which, at the cheapest rate,
currently cost 1p per minute, would pay a higher rental charge -- as
they do in the US.
''The essence of the proposals is flexibility,'' said a BT spokesman.
''We want to offer a variety of packages tailored to particular groups
of customers.
''One of the proposed packages involves free local calls. We are also
examining the possibility of different charging structures for different
regions, but we would ensure no existing customers would be
disadvantaged.''
The company is losing around 50,000 customers a month, mainly to new
cable companies which offer a combined telephone and television service.
But it has been barred from delivering live TV programmes through its
telephone lines as part of a deal to give the cable industry a flying
start.
The free calls scheme, which would appeal to small businesses and
those who spend a long time on the telephone to local friends and
neighbours, is one way for BT to fight back.
The company submitted its plans to Oftel in the spring, and a ruling
is due this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000157</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000157</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Women hit by mouth cancer increase</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584335</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PIONEERING treatment has helped a mother recover from mouth cancer,
which is now affecting more than double the number of Scottish women
compared with 20 years ago.
Cancer Research figures reveal an increase from 41 to 96 cases a year
and for six out of 10 women the cause is unknown. Now doctors have
launched a drive to help patients spot it in time to save their lives.
Mrs Audrey Innes, a health visitor, was only 32 and newly pregnant
with her first child, Michael, now 15 months, when she discovered a
small lump on the floor of her mouth. ''Like most health workers, I
still held the belief that oral cancer was a disease of the elderly,''
she said.
''By the time Michael was born, the lump was big enough for me to be
worried enough to ask for a specialist's opinion. The surgeon at Paisley
Royal Alexandra Hospital took a biopsy and diagnosed cancer.''
Mrs Innes was transferred to the plastic surgery and head and neck
cancer unit unit at Canniesburn Hospital in Glasgow where surgeons
worked at removing the cancer and preserving her looks. Canniesburn
handles more than 25% of oral cancer patients in Scotland.
Pioneering work was carried out on nerve endings to ensure that she
retained sensation for eating. Mr David Souter, a consultant plastic
surgeon, said: ''The surgery took about seven hours because we had to
take out the tumour and the draining glands in the neck to where the
disease is most likely to spread.
''We then have to rebuild the mouth by taking tissue from Audrey's arm
to replace the lining of her mouth. To make the transplant successful,
we had to join the small vessels together using an operating microscope
and microsurgical skills. A nerve had to be carefully joined together to
ensure continued sensation in Audrey's mouth.''
Mrs Innes's treatment consisted of a combination of surgery and
radiotherapy. Speech therapy has allowed her to talk and eat again.
During that time, she lost more than two stones and survived on a diet
of food supplement drinks.
Doctors at Canniesburn are concerned about the rising number of women
with oral cancer, which was previously a disease of elderly men.
Consultant oncologist Dr Gerry Robertson said: ''It is vital to get your
GP or dentist to check any mouth ulcer, sore, or lump which has not
healed in four weeks. Teeth which fall out but where the socket refuses
to heal can be another early warning sign. Immediate diagnosis is
essential.''
''We do not know what causes this cancer in six out of 10 women and we
are very unhappy about the rise.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
