<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000159</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000159</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Row over limit on dolphin cruises</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584337</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ATTEMPTS by Scottish Natural Heritage to restrict the number of
dolphin cruises in the Moray Firth have run into opposition.
A new code of conduct seeks to have a maximum of four trips a day into
a ''sensitive'' part of the firth, where around 130 bottle-nosed
dolphins live.
But two Inverness-based cruise companies say the move could put them
out of business.
SNH drew up an accreditation scheme for boat operators last year to
protect the dolphins.
Both Moray Firth Cruises and McAulay Charters, which operate side by
side at Inverness Harbour, signed up to the scheme. Moray Firth Cruises
received a grant from Inverness and Nairn Enterprise only after getting
SNH backing for its operation.
But the code now includes a restriction to four trips a day in the
Kessock Narrows. Both firms run up to six trips a day into the firth.
Scott Gair, a partner in Moray Firth Cruises, said: ''We are totally
dumbfounded by this. On the one hand they have helped us set up, and on
the other they are trying to put us out of business. If we do as they
want and run only two trips a day we would go bust pretty quickly.''
John McAulay of McAulay Charters said the dolphins faced greater
problems from other shipping and from leisure boats and jet skiers.
''It seems we are an easy target. The dolphins are under greater
threat from increased use of leisure craft. It concerns me that two
creditable operators working in a sane and sensible way are being hit in
this way.''
The cruise firms claim that the restrictions on sailings are proposed
because noise from the boats could affect SNH-funded listening stations
where people can hear the dolphins ''talk'' via hydrophones.
Mr McAulay said: ''I believe the crux of this matter is the listening
stations. This is just as much about their commercial operation as it is
about dolphins.''
A spokesman for Inverness and Nairn Enterprise said: ''We are
concerned that the operators are not getting a fair crack of the whip.
They are quite happy to abide by the code of conduct, but it appears the
goalposts have been moved.
''Despite their best endeavours they are being asked to restrict their
activities to what most people would consider to be an unfair level.''
Ben Leishon, of SNH, said four trips a day was judged to be the best
precaution to limit disturbance. He suggested that any additional trips
should be made on a fixed route around the edge of the sensitive area,
and then concentrating on other parts of the firth.
He said 16 or 17 dolphins frequented the area, and were vulnerable to
all forms of disturbance. Four of the animals had died since 1990 before
reaching adulthood.
He agreed that boats might affect the listening stations. ''If there
are a number of boats near the dolphins for large parts of the day there
will be a visual and audible effect, and this could compromise an
extremely valuable land base.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
