<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000161</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000161</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Alert on Alzheimer's</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584339</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
almost 500 people develop Alzheimer's disease or some other form of
dementia every day -- but many go undiagnosed for long periods and
receive help only in a crisis, according to a report published today.
However, Scotland is leading the way in improvements that will help
GPs to recognise the disease. Dunfermline West MP Mrs Rachel Squire has
put down an early day motion in Parliament which asks the Government to
recognise the importance of training for GPs and early diagnosis of the
disease.
The Alzheimer's Disease Society's Right from the Start report
estimates that 180,000 people in the United Kingdom are struck down by
dementia each year. A survey of 2000 carers and 700 family doctors also
highlighted widespread ignorance of the condition, says the document,
produced to mark the start of Alzheimer's Awareness Week.
The survey found that seven out of 10 GPs felt they had not received
adequate training in managing dementia, while fewer than one in four
carers thought their GPs had good knowledge of the disease. More than
half of GPs said they were dissatisfied with community care services.
The study also discovered that 5% of carers were more than 90 years old.
Alzheimer's Disease Society executive director Mr Harry Cayton said:
''Our surveys show that neither GPs nor carers are satisfied with the
way in which people with dementia are identified and supported in the
community. The number of people diagnosed is only the tip of the
iceberg, leaving people with dementia and their carers to cope until a
crisis forces recognition and help.''
The report's recommendations include:
* GPs to pay greater attention to the value of early diagnosis.
* A call for the Government to consider introducing incentives for GPs
to carry out health checks on 75-year-olds.
* GPs to improve links with other professionals and work with
voluntary organisations to support carers and sufferers.
Alzheimer's Scotland -- Action on Dementia (SAD) has joined the UK
campaign with the publication of a free booklet, Getting Help From Your
GP, on how to get help for sufferers and their carers. Ms Jan Killeen,
assistant director of public policy for SAD, said the campaign in
Scotland was one step ahead of the rest of the country, adding: ''We
have begun to address the issue of GPs' training at Alzheimer's
Scotland.'' The Dementia Services Development Centre at Stirling
University had also produced a training pack on dementia.
There are about 60,000 people with dementia in Scotland. Ms Killeen
said training and education were central to improvements in dementia
services, and added: ''It is important that GPs are alert so that early
support can be given.''
Mrs Squire, leader of Labour's Scottish task force on community care,
will apply for an adjournment debate on the issue, and said she would
also be seeking more resources for the primary health care sector.
The free 24-hour helpline for dementia advice in Scotland is 0800
317817.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000162</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000162</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Melanoma in focus</HEADLINE>
