<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000163</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000163</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Looking to the stars for the Stone of Destiny's return</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584341</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROBBIE the Pict has told Hollywood film stars profiting from Scottish
connections to put up or shut up. The campaigner for independence has
called on actors such as Sean Connery and stars from the current spate
of Scottish films to repay the nation by offering a bounty for the
return of the Stone of Destiny.
In the past two weeks the Pictish Free State founder has raised #1200
towards a reward for any Scot who can steal back the stone from its
current berth, beneath the Coronation Chair at Westminster Abbey. He
said the money had been raised ''from common folk'' and added: ''If this
is what ordinary people can come up with then surely the stars in their
ivory towers can do something.''
He added: ''The stone is a tangible symbol of the nation's
sovereignty. It should be a matter of principle for them: this is a
cultural, not political question.''
The ancient stone, upon which Scottish kings sat during their
coronation, was removed by the Edward I from Scone in 1296. Its origins
are suffused by myths, among which are that it is the biblical Jacob's
Pillow or that it was brought to Scotland by St Columba.However, some
historical accounts claim the Westminster one is a fake.
A famous raid took place on Christmas Day 1950, when a group stole the
stone and brought it back to Arbroath Abbey.
Sean Connery was unavailable to answer the appeal, but a spokeswoman
for United International Pictures, which distributed Rob Roy, said: ''It
sounds a very good cause and I do hope he succeeds, but Rob Roy has
already contributed a lot of money to the local economy.''
The Scottish Film Production Fund said the matter was more political
than filmic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000164</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000164</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Professor paid bonus after treating fewer patients resigns in disgust. Royal surgeon in NHS attack</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RON MACKENNA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584342</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE surgeon who operated on Prince Charles, after he broke his elbow
in a polo accident, yesterday criticised the Government's health reforms
and said he was quitting the NHS.
In the first of two major public attacks made on the eve of the
British Medical Association's annual conference in Harrogate, Professor
Christopher Colton claimed many of the reforms were ''more to do with
politics than patient care''.
''I am fed up,'' he said, claiming that at one stage he was awarded a
#20,000 bonus for agreeing to treat fewer people.
''In order not to exceed the targets, I had to close my children's
clinic for about four months and not have any referrals,'' he said.
''I was seeing so few people it meant another target was 100%
successful, in that nobody would have to wait longer than 30 minutes.''
The professor, who will be taking early retirement from his post at
the Nottingham University Hospital, said he was glad to be leaving the
NHS.
''I've had enough. I feel unhappy with the way the NHS is going. I
don't like the market pressures, and I don't like the fact that
decisions are being made about care, based upon market forces and not
necessarily on clinical need.''
His resignation came as the Bishop of Ripon chose the traditional
church service held before the conference to make his own attack. The Rt
Rev David Young said the NHS was now more concerned with its own
survival than long-term health care.
He warned the reforms were splitting apart the NHS and said changes
could cause chaos in the future. He told doctors in his sermon that the
fragmentation of health care was ''increasing rapidly in the culture of
competition.'' If it went on unchecked, he warned, ''chaos will ensue''.
The bishop said some of the central aims of the reforms, to increase
patient choice and allow the money to follow the patient, had not
materialised. He argued that, to some extent at least, a competitive
market struck at the root of the principle of caring.
''The increasingly competitive nature of health care is damaging.
Although lip service is given to the idea of co-operation between
trusts, the reality of the internal market requires competition,
secrecy, and fragmentation of historical links and exchange of clinical
expertise.''
Doctors are heading for another clash with the Government over plans
for hospital trusts to take over the training of future consultants.
The BMA will today debate an emergency motion calling on the
Government to revise the ''ill-judged and potentially destructive''
decision to have junior doctors employed directly by trusts.
The re-siting of junior doctors' contracts with trusts is due to take
place next April, when regional health authorities are scrapped. But
professional bodies across the spectrum of medicine have argued strongly
against the move, claiming it threatens the future of post-graduate
medical training.
Dr Mac Armstrong, BMA secretary, said: ''The Government has ignored
the advice of the juniors backed by the seniors, and all of the great
royal colleges. ''This great body of medical opinion has said this is
something that will not fly, this is something we advise you not to
do.''
Meanwhile, talks aimed at achieving a breakthrough in the bitter
health service pay dispute take place today, as the clock ticks towards
industrial action.
All hangs on the meeting between employers, NHS officials, and 13
unions who will try to resolve the row over the Government's offer of a
1% rise plus up to 2% to be negotiated locally.
The round-the-table talks -- the third to be held -- take place just
days before the start of the ballot process on strike action.
However, the unions' fight against locally determined pay was severely
undermined on Friday, when midwives opened the way for ''cash on
delivery'' productivity deals.
The decision by the Royal College of Midwives to accept a 1% national
award to be topped up in local negotiations shattered the fragile
coalition that exists between the unions, and earned widespread
condemnation. But midwives are still planning to join today's talks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Eastwood Tories come out for Major. MP Stewart shares tea, sympathy, and pragmatism with the faithful</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NIC OUTTERSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584343</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nic Outterside takes a weekend reading from the man who remains the
most reliable barometer of political feeling on the Conservative right
BETWEEN the cream teas and an emergency executive meeting it was
business as usual for Eastwood Tories at the weekend.
At every level party activists are at one with their MP, Mr Allan
Stewart, in support for Prime Minister John Major in tomorrow's party
leadership election against former Welsh Secretary John Redwood.
However, although Mr Redwood is almost universally condemned as a man
''not up to the top job'', a stern warning to Mr Major came from this
most secure of all Scottish Conservative constituencies: ''Harden up
your act or we'll waste no time in choosing someone else.''
While Mr Michael Forsyth and Mr Michael Portillo pledge support for
the Prime Minister on the basis of their Cabinet positions, Mr Stewart
remains the most reliable barometer of political feeling on the right of
the Conservative Party.
He sees politics as a matter of pragmatism, and his pragmatic view is
that Mr Major is the one man who can continue to unite the party. Any
other option could be disastrous.
But he stressed that if Mr Major failed to reach the target needed to
secure the leadership a second ballot could provide a Pandora's box of
possibilities. The hint was obvious -- the result could be the return of
Mr Michael Heseltine as leader and Prime Minister.
Mr Stewart went back to Eastwood on Friday knowing he could rely on
the support of his constituency association. A special executive meeting
was called on Saturday morning at Rhuallan House, Giffnock. The party
hierarchy spent less than 50 minutes determining their advice to their
MP.
Chairman Ian Muir said there had been a ''full and frank'' discussion
but the executive had voted overwhelmingly to instruct Mr Stewart to
vote for Mr Major.
''We have in the past few years had some policies that have not been
totally acceptable or not very suitable to the grass roots,'' said Mr
Muir. ''But the overwhelming opinion is that John Major is the only
person who can unite the party and win the next General Election.''
Committee member Bill Cameron summed up the feeling of most of his
colleagues. ''I think Mr Stewart's views are as right-wing as anybody in
Eastwood, but we all feel for John Major and we don't want any change at
the moment,'' he said.
Mrs Muriel Mitchell added: ''I feel that John Major has had his
authority diluted and has spent all his time looking over his shoulder.
After Tuesday the party must get behind him and give him the authority
to win the next General Election.''
Ms Jean Hamilton -- a former constituency chair for Sir Teddy Taylor
-- said: ''I think Europe is the key to this. I am not for Europe, but
at the same time I think Major has done the best for us whereas Redwood
would have us out and that would be disaster, no matter how we feel
about the EU's shortcomings.''
Mr Stewart's day had begun with a spread of unity, but there was a lot
of policy-crunching to come. A short car journey and he was back at his
Neilston home -- an 1830s mill owner's house set in a couple of acres of
well-tended rural garden.
The sun drenched a private patio and amid budding lavender plants,
cold Australian Chardonnay, and crusty ham rolls -- served by his wife
Susie -- the MP ventured his views on the state of his party.
Two months ago he warned that the Government could suffer an electoral
wipe-out in Scotland if changes were not made on essential policy.
But Mr Stewart sees the Prime Minister as the best and only man
capable of carrying acceptable policy changes forward.
On Saturday he expanded: ''I believe governments have got to develop
policies. That doesn't necessarily mean radical changes -- but times
change and you need to change policies with them.''
He supported an increase in mortgage tax relief to help combat the
stagnation and negative equity evident in the housing market. ''There is
a need to put up the percentage rate on mortgage tax relief across the
board if we are to regenerate demand and help first-time buyers.
''A move on tax relief would also push house prices up and address the
problem of negative equity, which has become a problem in many other
parts of the country.''
Taxation is another primary issue he believes must be addressed if the
Conservative Party is to win back the voters who have deserted it in
droves during the past three years.
''You can put up a good argument for VAT on domestic fuel at half the
standard rate,'' he said, ''and I would now be inclined for the
Government to announce that the position is one which will not be
changed.''
But the MP admitted that a tricky problem existed in finding a
''painless way'' to raise extra revenue for the Government to fund tax
cuts, admitting that VAT on newspapers and children's clothes would not
yield a satisfactory return.
He said that an increase of the standard rate of VAT to 20% would be
one method that could be considered. ''It would be inflationary in the
immediate term because it would raise prices, but it is not necessarily
inflationary in the medium term as it takes money out of the economy.
''I would personally be slightly more relaxed about the inflation
target anyway. The 2.75% is an extraordinarily tight inflation target
and we could cope with an extra point on that.''
Care in the community is another issue where Mr Stewart believes his
party has come adrift of its electorate. ''The main problem seems to be
because it is delivered through local authorities and its implementation
is out of direct control of the Government.
''It's not a case of going into reverse, but there are horror stories,
such as instances where people have had to sell their houses to pay for
care and these need to be addressed. We need to look a lot harder at the
respective roles of the local authority sector, the voluntary sector,
and private sector and work out how their roles can be supported and
developed. But any changes must be carried out in a kind of pragmatic,
practical way.''
Mr Stewart also moved quickly to shift two of Mr Redwood's primary
election planks. He dismissed Europe as a pressing policy issue. ''I am
happy with the Prime Minister's policy of delaying the decision on a
single currency now. Parliament can decide when the time comes and we
can also keep the options open for a referendum. That's a reasonable and
pragmatic line to take.''
He added that the party now needed to put aside its own internal
debate on Europe and begin drawing demarcation lines over where it
differs from Labour. ''The single issue of Europe should not be one
which determines the leadership of the party or the Prime Minister of
the country.''
The second promise of Mr Redwood to stamp down on sleaze by screening
every Minister was dismissed as being fraught with difficulty.
''Who are you going to get to do the screening?'' asked Mr Stewart.
''Mr Redwood said he would call people in and ask them questions. But
nobody is going to say: 'Oh, by the way, I've got two broads on the side
and have my heroin every second Tuesday'.''
Turning to the leadership election, he said Mr Redwood's decision to
stand came as a ''complete surprise''. He believed there was an initial
knee-jerk reaction to support the contender but that support had
''noticeably waned'' as Mr Redwood's credentials were exposed.
There is a feeling of close loyalty between Mr Stewart and the Prime
Minister. He harks back to the mid-1970s when the two of them were both
active within the Beckenham constituency Conservative association.
However, he believes that Mr Major needs to develop a harder streak
and cites last week's meeting with the 60 Euro-sceptics and his loyalty
to David Mellor as two instances that were mishandled -- things Mrs
Thatcher would never have tolerated.
Lunch was soon over and it was time to face the constituents once
again. This time a Tory cream tea in the home of a party activist in the
Clarkston ward. The supporters had time to relax over their meringues
and strawberries and pass more thoughtful comment on the party's
problems.
''We will support the Prime Minister. However, if he does not get the
sufficient votes he needs to continue then Michael Portillo will get a
lot of votes,'' says businessman Malcolm Mulheron.
''If Major wins he must listen to the views of Mr Redwood's supporters
and take those views on board and act upon them . . . he can't afford to
cut off one wing of the party.''
Bunty McDowall believed Mr Major's decision to resign and force a
leadership challenge was ''a mistake in hindsight'' but agreed he had to
take action on internal bickering.
''Even if he wins on Tuesday I don't believe he will stop the
infighting. I don't think the whole bang-shoot augurs very well for the
next General Election,'' she added.
The same resignation was reflected by Mr Fraser MacIntosh, who
admitted that Mr Michael Heseltine would be his choice on a second
ballot. ''My honest opinion is that if Redwood was to win it would not
only be a disaster for the party but for the country as a whole.
''We must look ahead. What's hapening now is what happened to the
Labour Party a few years ago . . . we're tearing ourselves apart.''
Opinions, like the weather, cooled. Mr Stewart, asked by one party
activist whether he had changed his mind and would support John Redwood,
quipped: ''Aw no, we're all backing Ted Heath in the second ballot, then
we can give everything away to Europe.''
The fear of the Pandora's box is never far away.
</TEXT>
