<HEADLINE>Tory MP survives sacking call</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584344</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MAVERICK Scottish MP Bill Walker survived an emergency meeting of his
constituency party yesterday, over his support for the Tory leadership
challenger John Redwood.
Despite a call for his deselection and strong opposition to his
support for Mr Redwood, he emerged unscathed.
He said: ''I anticipate I will be the candidate (for Tayside North).
Of course, I accept that will depend on getting the support of the party
activists and party workers, and that's the majority that have to
support me.''
Opinion at the ''lively'' emergency meeting of the Tayside North
party's executive over Mr Walker's stance was ''evenly divided'', and
the MP admitted that strong views were expressed on each side.
Before the meeting, which was attended by around 40 activists,
constituency deputy chairman Charles Cormack said: ''I'm sure some
people are discontented. Obviously he's upset quite a few people, that's
the nature of the beast.''
But Mr Walker and constituency chairman Michael MacPhail presented a
united front after the meeting in a Blairgowrie hotel.
Mr MacPhail said: ''Everybody had points to make. There was, of
course, different opinions expressed, but we welcome that. Ultimately, I
think it will go on to show that we are united in North Tayside.
''Obviously, a leadership election, any election, makes for some
degree of division, and some controversy. Politics is more interesting
as a consequence.''
Mr MacPhail explained that under Scottish Conservative rules, Mr
Walker had the right to back ''whosoever he may wish to support'', and
added that it would be incorrect if Mr Walker's stance led to his
deselection.
Mr Walker welcomed the outcome of the meeting and said that he was
still absolutely behind Mr Redwood.
</TEXT>
