<HEADLINE>Labour calls for debt claim inquiry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584345</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SENIOR Labour figures last night demanded Government responses to
allegations in a newspaper that a company owned by a leading Tory
fund-raiser in Scotland owes more than #1.2m to the public purse for
property deals done in the 1980s.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson said the claims, involving
Glasgow businessman Mr Jack Harvie, should be the subject of a full
inquiry by Scottish Secretary Ian Lang.
Shadow trade and industry spokesman Brian Wilson said he would be
tabling questions in the Commons.
An article in Scotland on Sunday suggested that City Link Developments
-- owned by Mr Harvie, who organises lucrative annual dinners for the
Conservative Party in Scotland -- bought two properties from the former
Scottish Development Agency in 1987 and 1988.
He is alleged to have purchased Merlin House, an office block on the
Hillington industrial estate, for #850,000, in 1987, yet has paid only
#125,000 to date.
The following year, he is said to have bought a 10-acre site nearby
for #550,000, but has so far paid only 10%.
It is understood that the outstanding sum, in excess of #1.2m, is
registered as a loan in the latest published accounts of Scottish
Enterprise, which succeeded the SDA.
A Scottish Enterprise spokesman said the agency was completely
satisfied that there was ''no case to answer'' and that any inquiry
would show ''the high standards of professional business practice and
general integrity of all parties involved''.
Agency insiders are thought to regard yesterday's newspaper article as
politically motivated and selective in its use of facts. It is
understood that other companies have larger ''debts'' with the country's
main industrial aid body, which is subjected to regular auditing
scrutiny.
However, Labour's Mr Robertson said that, apart from demanding answers
from Mr Lang, he had also written to Professor Donald Mackay, chairman
of Scottish Enterprise, asking if interest had been paid on the
outstanding amount; and to Mr Robert Sheldon, chairman of the Public
Accounts Committee, requesting him to investigate.
He said: ''Serious questions are posed by these land sales and, given
Mr Harvie's close links to the Scottish Tory party, it is essential that
Ian Lang clarifies the picture right away.''
''He has responsibility for Scottish Enterprise, and he personally
must explain why any company should get preferential terms with valuable
public assets.
Mr Harvie, who received the CBE in the 1992 New Year's Honours List,
could not be contacted yesterday at his home in Mugdock, near Milngavie.
But Sir Michael Hirst, chairman of the Scottish Conservative Party,
leapt to his defence, claiming the Scotland on Sunday article was
''seriously flawed by inaccuracies, half-truths, bias and innuendo''.
He said he believed nothing illegal or dishonourable had occurred.
Sir Michael added: ''Not surprisingly, the article makes no reference
to the fact that Jack Harvie has, from scratch, built up businesses
which now employ nearly 1500 people. Scotland would benefit enormously
from a lot more successful entrepreneurs like him.''
</TEXT>
