<HEADLINE>Facts do not get in the way of the script as Bannockburn moves to the Borders. History loses an epic film battle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584346</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND has never had it so good on the cinema screen. This weekend
they have been fighting Bannockburn all over again. It seemed like going
from the sublime to the ridiculous, turning from watching the cast of
thousands being slaughtered in the battle scenes of Mel Gibson's epic
film Braveheart about William Wallace -- there are probably more people
on screen fighting than there were in all of thirteenth century Scotland
-- to viewing the cast of around 150 extras doing the same in The Bruce.
The two films are at the opposite ends of the film-making spectrum.
The Bruce, directed by Bob Carruthers, who made Chasing the Deer, is
largely financed by the public who, if they take shares, get the chance
to appear in it and their names in the end credits. One, a member of the
Anglo-Scottish squirearchy, told a chum watching the filming on
Saturday: ''It is what they call a low-budget film. I don't know why I'm
here. I just got the urge.''
But does this rewriting of history matter? Rob Roy, the most recent
Scots epic, took a swipe at the truth, much to the annoyance of those
who believe they know what it is.
In Gibson's Braveheart, Wallace wages his battles in selected Highland
or Irish beauty spots, not the dreary Lowlands, marries a lady called
Murren, a very odd name indeed, and romances the Princess of Wales. Does
it matter if, as here, the history is bunk? Only if those watching the
result take it as gospel. Brought up in Lanark in the belief that
Wallace could remotely look like the whitewashed figure in a skirt, and
wrap-around plaid, with a First World War tin hat and crown on his head,
on the front of the parish kirk, I was reared on largely imaginary
history.
But the Wallace story, provided one knows that much of it is legend,
only a little historical fact, gave the town a sense of its past, which
is what matters. Unfortunately, Braveheart, while being thrilling,
paints a world not remotely like thirteenth century Scotland. Given the
way history is taught in schools today, that is a pity.
How does Robert the Bruce, planned to ride along on the slipstream of
Braveheart, fare?
Historically, not all that well, but the makers' hearts are in the
right place in a film about freedom from English domination. Bannockburn
was re-fought over the weekend at Neidpath Castle outside Peebles, with
the Tweed standing in for the silvery Tay. It proved to be two days of
crises, some great, some small, involving much standing about for the
100-odd extras who played both the Scots and English armies.
Carruthers, sporting a Glengarry with a feather and a black The Bruce
T-shirt costing #10, summed things up at one moment of high tension. His
explicit instructions from on high were being wantonly disobeyed down
below. ''I think you start speaking Japanese when you start making a
film. I really do,'' he sighed. ''It is like bloody Hampden Park down
there.''
The extras may have found it tedious but it was not much fun for the
actors who had to do even more waiting. Edward I, played by Brian
Blessed, spent most of his time letting small boys take his photograph
and explaining: ''I am Edward I, Hammer of the Scots, a very cruel great
king who beat Bruce seven times and I am directing the English acting
scenes as well as acting.''
The small boys seemed surprised. Should you wonder why Edward I was at
Bannockburn, it was partly because they had some additional shots to
take of Blessed with an army behind him, partly, action being
Carruthers's specialty, so he could direct some of the scenes.
Unfortunately, somehow they kept never quite getting round to them.
This drove Edward II, played by Richard Brimblecombe, into quite a
tizzy as he was made to get on his horse, having just been told to get
off. ''I have been here since eight this morning and this is the first
thing I have actually done and it is wrong,'' he said. ''How do I know
what to do if they won't tell me? I'm not a mind reader.''
He is there as the sex appeal because, as Blessed admitted, the rest
of the cast are far from pretty. Bruce (Sandy Walsh) has designer
stubble, wears an orange fright wig, and will cause Mel Gibson no
worries.
''Oliver Reed is pretty ugly these days and I am what you might call a
rough-hewn Ulysses. Richard is handsome, the women swoon for him, so I
am making the character of Edward II stronger,'' proclaimed Blessed as
he rehearsed his colleagues in those scenes they never got round to
filming.
</TEXT>
