<HEADLINE>Book claims 60% of husbands unfaithful</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584347</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MORE and more husbands are cheating on their wives, a marriage expert
claims today.
In a new book, The Trouble With You, therapist Mrs Zelda West-Meads
estimates that 60% of married men are having affairs.
The numbers could hit three out of four if trends continue, she said.
Some husbands wait just six months after exchanging vows before
straying.
However, the phenomenon is not restricted to men only. Based on recent
research from magazines, books, and a paper from the Institute of
Marital Studies, Mrs West-Meads said 40% of women were also fooling
around.
The author, who has counselled couples with marriage guidance group
Relate for 20 years, said the rapid growth in adultery in Britain
mirrors a rise in infidelity in the United States.
There, expectations about the pleasures of marriage are higher and
divorce is more socially accepted, she said.
''Many philandering husbands and straying wives convince themselves
that adultery is actually good for their marriages,'' she said.
''They believe it does no harm as long as it remains a secret. Some
feel an affair is a way of staying together rather than seeking divorce.
''But really it's frequently just an excuse to have their cake and eat
it without ever trying to get to grips with what is wrong in their own
marriages,'' she said.
The book also reveals that one affair often leads to another and those
who were promiscuous before marriage often end up unable to settle down
when wedded.
''Once you have been used to having a variety of sexual partners, it's
more difficult to give up,'' she said.
</TEXT>
