<HEADLINE>St Mary's makes it six in a row</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584348</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A RECORD was claimed by an Edinburgh family yesterday as its sixth son
became a full member of the choir at St Mary's Episcopal Cathedral,
following in the footsteps of his five brothers.
Michael Wood, eight, from Craigmount Avenue North in the city's
Drumbrae area, donned his surplice and became a full chorister after
having served as a probationer in the choir for the past 18 months.
The remarkable achievements of the sons of Carol and Bill Wood began
in 1981 when their eldest son, Martin, began as a chorister at St
Mary's.
Martin, now 22, Stuart, 20, William, 16, and Mark, 15, have all been
head choristers.
Michael Wood joins his brother Stephen, 10, also a chorister. The
brothers celebrated at a lunchtime party yesterday.
Mrs Wood had no explanation for her family's talents yesterday. But
one clue could lie in the fact that she is a great-niece of Louis Levy,
who composed music for films and had an orchestra that played for George
VI.
</TEXT>
