<HEADLINE>Business sceptical on Europe and single currency</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JONATHAN NORTHCROFT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584349</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEARLY half of UK businesses oppose a single European currency,
according to a survey published today.
The research, by the Forum of Private Businesses which represents
23,000 independent UK firms, shows 47% against a single currency.
However, one in five businesses were ''undecided''. The survey also
found an overwhelming 71% against faster European integration.
A regional breakdown shows that Scottish opposition to a single
European currency almost matches the UK average. But Scottish opposition
to faster European integration is lower.
Forum Scottish spokesman Mr Jim Gorie said the results confirmed Scots
were outward-looking, though this was tempered by the currency issue.
He added: ''There is a much higher complacency and ignorance towards
Europe down south, particularly in middle England.
''Scottish business is much more informed and interested, but there is
a great nervousness that we might be less competitive under a single
European currency.
''There is still a residue of caution that if there is a level
playing-field, Scotland might suffer particularly if it has strings such
as a minimum wage.''
Across the UK, the report shows a significant draining of support for
a single currency, which stood at 59% prior to the Maastricht summit in
1991.
Sectors most strongly opposed were agriculture, construction and
manufacturing, where businesses felt a single currency might affect raw
material costs.
The FPB forum survey also shows two out of three in the business
community now want a referendum on the Government's European policy.
This compares to 33% who wanted a similar vote this at the time of
Maastricht.
</TEXT>
