<HEADLINE>Archbishop's son is ordained</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584350</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Archbishop of Canterbury watched with pride as his son followed in
his footsteps yesterday, at Wakefield Cathedral.
At a special ceremony watched by 700 people, Dr George Carey saw his
30-year-old son Mark ordained as a priest.
However, Dr Carey admitted it was a day he thought he would never see.
''I was surprised when he told me he wanted to be a priest. I am
delighted and very proud of Mark, and I am sure he is going to be a very
fine priest.''
Mark Carey, who accepted the cloth in a two-hour ceremony watched by
wife Penny, 32, and mother Eileen, left a job as a social worker and
manager of a children's home in Avon to join the ministry. He has been
curate of Christ Church at South Ossett, in the Wakefield diocese, for
more than a year.
''When I started out in social work I didn't want to be a priest, and
I had to think very carefully about following my dad,'' he said.
''But in the end God made me join the church. This is what I want to
do, and I am very happy.''
</TEXT>
