<HEADLINE>Tour firm could face death charge. Police probe Thomson holiday tragedy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584351</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOUR operator Thomson could be charged with corporate manslaughter
over the death last October of a holidaymaker in Spain, it emerged
yesterday.
Following a request by a coroner, police are investigating the death
from carbon monoxide poisoning of Miss Janet Smith at Veramar holiday
apartments, Fuengirola, during a week-long break booked through Thomson
Tour Operators.
Miss Smith, 31, of Hornchurch, Essex, who was sharing her apartment
with friends Linsey Moore and Sharon Fisher, was exposed to high levels
of carbon monoxide, believed to have come from a faulty water heater.
Her friends, who were part of a group of mentally-handicapped
holidaymakers, recovered after four days in intensive care.
Waltham Forest coroner Harold Price opened an inquest but adjourned it
to allow the police investigation to be carried out.
A Scotland Yard spokesman said: ''It is alleged that the carbon
monoxide poisoning was caused by defective water heaters, and that
Thomson Tour Operators knew about the defective heaters prior to the
holiday booking.''
A spokeswoman for Thomson said: ''We take the responsibility for the
safety of our customers extremely seriously.
''It would be wholly inappropriate for us to comment on the tragic
death of Janet Smith while the Spanish authorities continue their
inquiries and before the UK coroner has conducted an inquest.''
A corporate manslaughter charge is rare in Britain. Eight defendants,
including ferry company Townsend Thorensen and three former directors,
were acquitted in 1990 over the Herald of Free Enterprise disaster, when
193 people died in 1987.
The managing director of an activity centre was jailed for three years
in 1994, after four teenagers died in the Lyme Bay canoeing tragedy.
* Striking Greek seamen have promised to end a walkout that has halted
ferry traffic to the Aegean islands, stranding thousands of tourists.
''We will end this strike on Monday,'' said Mr John Halas, secretary
general of the Panhellenic Seamen's Federation. ''We will then consider
renewing action if there is no progress in our talks with the
government.''
The strike, to press their demands for higher pensions and lower
taxes, has stranded at least 10,000 tourists -- some Britons -- in ports
around the country, and virtually halted seaborne traffic between the
mainland and the islands.
Piraeus, Greece's largest commercial and passenger port, looked like a
refugee camp, with foreign tourists sleeping on the docks. Others slept
in the grounds of Athens international airport, awaiting a place on a
charter flight.
At the port, trucks carrying supplies for the islands backed up at
Piraeus as perishables rotted in the sun. The strike has hurt the
country's many islands, which get most of their supplies by sea.
Union leaders said that although the strike had been nearly 100%
successful, the government was not willing to satisfy their demands.
''Participation so far in the strike is total. No passenger ships have
left port,'' Halas said.
The socialist government has repeated a pledge made in March that it
would raise minimum pensions in 1996. It also said it would try to deal
with pension fund problems in the budget for that year.
A spokesman for Thomson said none of the hundreds of people on its
holidays in the Greek islands this weekend had been hit by the strike.
''In the places affected we have arranged hydrofoils or chartered our
own boats, so our customers have not had to change any travel
arrangements,'' said a spokeswoman for the tour operator.
Meanwhile, a sharp earth tremor struck yesterday near the
quake-battered Greek port of Egion, but officials reported no injuries
or serious damage.
The town was hit by a major quake on June 15, that left 26 dead and
over 60 injured. Most of the dead were in a block of flats and a hotel
that collapsed.
The Athens Geodynamic Institute said the tremor measured 4.5 on the
Richter scale, with its epicentre in the Gulf of Corinth, 90 miles
south-west of Athens.
</TEXT>
