<HEADLINE>Tory plans would give employers access to Scotland Yard computer. Job seekers to face crime record checks</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584352</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROPOSALS requiring job applicants to produce an official certificate
stating whether they have a criminal record, and costing them #5, are
set to be published by the Government later this year.
A draft White Paper, due to be unveiled at the Tory Party conference
in October, would allow a large section of employers access to a
computer, currently at Scotland Yard, containing applicants'
convictions.
Those looking for work in the ''most sensitive areas of employment''
will have to submit to ''full criminal record checks'' with a new
privatised Criminal Justice Record System, known as Phoenix.
This will reveal not only recent unspent convictions, but details of
offences committed in the distant past, according to a confidential
Whitehall paper obtained by a Sunday newspaper.
The Home Office said yesterday that Home Secretary Michael Howard
''could certainly mention this at the Tory conference'', but a spokesman
would neither confirm nor deny that the certificate would cost job
applicants #5.
''We cannot go into details until the White Paper is published,'' he
said.
The Scottish Office said it was ''aware of the Home Office work in
this area and it is a matter which is also under consideration by the
Scottish Office.''
A spokesman was also unable to talk in detail about the proposals, but
added that the Scottish Office was looking at how arrangements could be
put into place ''which best reflect Scottish circumstances''.
Childcare employers already have full access to criminal records, but
the White Paper introduces many new categories of employers who can vet
applicants.
These are understood to include teachers, probation officers, social
workers, health staff, opticians, dentists, osteopaths, chiropractors,
vets, pharmacists, managers of clinics or nursing homes, accountants,
lawyers, and legal executives.
National lottery ticket-sellers, firefighters, and managers of banks,
building societies, and insurance companies are also included.
The second category -- all other employers -- would be entitled to
insist that job applicants present a ''criminal conviction certificate''
-- a computer printout recording whether they have ''unspent
convictions'' together with details of any offences committed.
A Bill containing the plans could be introduced in the next
parliamentary session.
According to the Observer, job applicants will have to pay #5 for the
certificate, even if they have no convictions.
It quotes the White Paper as stating: ''The criminal conviction
certificates should alert employers to individuals with a recent and/or
very serious convictions on their record, but should not prejudice the
prospects of those who have committed offences incurring long prison
sentences and who have reformed.''
Mr Alan Miller, chairman of the Scottish Council for Civil Liberties,
said yesterday that, while the criminal convictions of people seeking
jobs in sensitive areas of work such as childcare had to be considered,
he would be concerned about matters of confidentiality affecting people
seeking jobs in less sensitive areas.
''It seems to be an extension beyond the previous situation covering
people working with children, and I think it's an extension too far.
''It is also shifting the onus on to the employee to get the
certificate, and some of the jobs to which this applies don't seem at
all appropriate.''
Mr Miller added: ''If you have increased access to police criminal
records, we would have concern about what other use or abuse that could
be put to.
''The whole point of the Rehabilitation of Offenders Act is that
people should get over their offences and be rehabilitated into society,
so we would be concerned that old convictions were dragged up and
prejudiced someone from getting a job.
''People should be able to reintegrate into society without having
these held against them.
''I would like to know what the reason for this move is. Our concern
is that a lot of these kind of moves arise from Conservative Party
conferences and pressure to appease Tories and come up with something
new rather than the perceived need to introduce things.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000175</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000175</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Charities press for a wider safety net</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584353</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE charities Shelter and the Scottish Council for Single Homeless
yesterday urged the Scottish Office to widen the safety net for
youngsters leaving local authority care.
Their last-ditch appeal comes two days before the Children (Scotland)
Bill is debated in the House of Lords.
At present, the legislation proposes that councils should provide
after-care support for children up to their 19th birthday, and the
Government has rejected amendments that this should be extended to the
age of 21.
However, both Shelter and the SCSH argued yesterday that the increase
had backing from across the political spectrum, and from many child-care
groups, including Barnardo's, the Scottish Child Law Centre, and the
Association of Directors of Social work.
They also quoted Tory MP Phil Gallie, who told a Commons committee
during an earlier reading of the Bill: ''I have some sympathy for the
argument. A youngster between the ages of 19 and 21 still needs
support.''
Shelter spokesman Michael Thain pointed out that recent legislation
for Northern Ireland had given individuals rights to after-care support
until they were 21.
He said: ''Young people who have been in local authority care are 70
times more likely to become homeless than other young people. We have
asked for a minimal concession from the Government to ensure that young
people are helped through an extremely difficult time in their lives.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
