<DOCNO>GH950703-000177</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000177</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Geese may ground wind farm</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584355</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GEESE are the reason why Argyll and Bute District Council will this
week be advised to refuse permission for a wind farm.
Director of planning George Harper will recommend that Trigen
(Kintyre) Ltd's plan to build a 25-turbine wind farm at Largie Estate,
Kintyre, be turned down because of fears that it could interfere with
Greenland white-fronted geese which winter in the area.
Each of the turbines is to be 62 metres high, and both the Royal
Society for the Protection of Birds and Scottish Natural Heritage fear
that the geese, which have special protection status under an EC
directive, might fly into them and be killed.
The proposal has also prompted local concern over visual impact and
noise, but it is clearly the goose factor which perturbs Mr Harper.
In a report to his council's planning committee this week, he states
that the planned site lies between a Site of Special Scientific
Interest, where internationally important numbers of the geese feed, and
lochs to the east where the birds roost.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000178</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000178</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Number of 19-year-olds staying-on in education increases with jobs slump</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY MCBAIN,EDUCATION CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584356</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE number of Scottish 19-year-olds going on to higher education has
more than doubled over the last eight years, mainly because of reduced
employment opportunities for school-leavers.
The finding is contained in a report by the Centre for Educational
Sociology at Edinburgh University, published today, which says that most
pupils are staying on at school in the hope of going to university.
But social class remains an important factor in progress to tertiary
education. The Government's overhaul of Scottish secondary education,
Higher Still, which aims to cater for the growing numbers of children
staying on after 16, will have to cater for all social classes and meet
their employment and training needs, says the report.
The findings are based on the Scottish Young People's Survey, a
regular postal survey of school-leavers and year groups to provide a
picture of participation trends among 16 to 19-year-olds in education
and training.
The analysis, based on data collected from samples of 16-year-olds
between 1985 and 1991 followed over a 30-month period, shows that
participation in higher education rose from 16% of 19-year-olds in 1987
to 31% in 1993.
The proportion who stayed in full-time education after 16 rose from
46% to 58%, an increase offset by a fall in full-time employment.
There was also a decline in unemployment among 16-year-olds and the
centre says this might be partly explained by benefit changes in 1988
which ruled out unemployment as an option for the under-18s.
Over the survey period, the proportion of 19-year-olds in full-time
work fell from 59% to 41% while unemployment remained stable at about
12%.
''Changes in the labour market, and in higher education, have weakened
the 'pull' of young people out of education at 16 and increased the
incentives to stay on,'' says the report.
In a finding which will be of particular interest to educationists and
secondary headteachers, the data shows that what young people do after
16 is less dependent than before on the fourth-year qualifications they
obtain.
The fastest increase in participation in fifth and sixth years, and in
further and higher education, occurred in the group with the lowest
fourth-year attainment, and more girls than boys participated in these
four ''educational'' routes.
The data also show significant differences in participation between
young people from working and middle-class backgrounds.
According to the most recent group of young people suryeved, the
proportion going on to higher education from non-manual backgrounds was
58%, while for those from manual backgrounds it was 20%.
Professor David Raffe, who worked on the survey with colleague Paula
Surridge, said: ''Staying on rates have risen fastest among the
least-qualified 16-year-olds, and this trend should continue if Higher
Still fulfils its promise to offer 'opportunity for all'.
''One of the biggest challenges for Higher Still will be to satisfy
the needs and aspirations of those aiming for university, while also
providing worthwhile routes into employment and occupational training.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000179</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000179</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Marks and Spencer passes on card trial</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584357</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARKS and Spencer is refusing to take part in the first trial of a
revolutionary new payment card.
M&amp;S will be the only major store not involved in the trial of the
Mondex card which begins in Swindon, Wiltshire, today.
Mondex -- invented by the NatWest bank -- is the latest in plastic
smart cards and the biggest step so far down the road to the cashless
society.
It can be electronically charged with cash and allows the holder to
shop without coins or notes.
NatWest, the Midland and British Telecom, which jointly developed the
project, persuaded hundreds of shops in Swindon to take part in a trial
over the next one to two years.
But M&amp;S, which only began to accept debit cards in May, is standing
back -- to the disappointment of the trial's organisers.
''They have a history of being very cautious about these things and we
have to respect that,'' said a Mondex spokesman.
M&amp;S said its priority was to gear all stores to accept debit cards.
''We have looked at Mondex and we do not rule it out for the future,''
said an M&amp;S spokeswoman. ''It's simply that our priority at the moment
is to press on with Switch and Visa Delta cards as fast as possible.''
Mondex cards contain a microchip which allows users to charge them up
with cash at NatWest or Midland hole-in-the-wall machines or over the
telephone.
They are then swiped through a shop terminal and payments docked from
the card.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000180</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000180</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gardener dies after petrol fireball tragedy at wedding</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584358</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 70-YEAR-OLD man died yesterday after he was turned into a human
fireball in front of horrified wedding guests.
Church gardener Mr Arthur Handy was engulfed by flames moments before
the wedding ceremony began when he turned on a shed light after filling
a lawn mower with petrol.
Members of the congregation smothered him with morning suits and a
blanket as he staggered from the outbuilding in agony.
Mr Handy was taken to hospital and later transferred to a special
intensive care unit but died nine hours later.
The tragedy happened at the weekend at St Jude's Church, South
Shields, Tyne and Wear, just before Miss Joanne Bailey, 25, and Mr
Joseph Goss, 27, were to be married.
The bride was not told about it until after the ceremony.
Mr Handy was about to mow the lawn, before the wedding photos were
taken, and he had taken a can of petrol into the shed.
Safety officer Mr Colin Kennedy, 39, who helped to smother the fire
with a blanket said: ''It was a terrible thing to happen on what should
have been a happy day.''
His wife, Joyce, added: ''We saw smoke coming from a shed and thought
the door was on fire but then this poor man came out covered in flames.
''He was obviously in a lot of pain and had his arms stretched out --
it was awful. The ceremony went on after the accident. We didn't tell
Joanne what had happened until afterwards.
''We told her that someone had collapsed outside the church.''
The Rev Pat Bealing said: ''We were all terribly shocked by what
happened.''
Another guest was treated in hospital for shock following the
incident.
Paramedics took Mr Handy, of Dacre Street, South Shields, to the
town's general hospital and he was later taken to Newcastle General,
where he died in the intensive care unit while his sister, Eunice, was
at his bedside.
A Northumbria police spokesman said last night: ''This appears to have
been a terrible tragedy.
''Mr Handy was spotted shortly before the fire carrying a red petrol
can -- we can only assume he got some of the fuel on his body and it
ignited when he switched on the light.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000181</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000181</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The night two secret drinkers led to unfair sacking of Gleneagles barman</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584359</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE potted palms were swaying at the Gleneagles Hotel after two
private detectives poured drinks over them, an industrial tribunal has
heard in relation to a claim for unfair dismissal.
The men, undercover Pinkerton agents, surreptitiously poured #63.60
worth of drinks into the plants in the cocktail lounge while carrying
out a routine security audit at the five-star hotel in Auchterarder,
Perthshire, on January 23, 1995.
At around 8pm, they went into the American Bar to buy drinks with
''marked'' money, which showed up under ultraviolet light, and for an
hour observed Mr Lyndon Bowring and Miss Nicola Stewart, the two duty
cocktail bartenders.
Mr Bowring, of Clos Nant-y-Cym, North Penwtyn, Cardiff, who claimed he
was unfairly dismissed by the hotel, said the private detectives had
bought two rounds but the Pinkerton pair claimed to have bought six.
The morning after the night in the American Bar the detectives
reported to Mr McKenzie, the security manager, that they had spent
#63.60, which could not be reconciled with the till report.
Two days later the barman was summoned to a meeting in front of Mr K
Poulter, former deputy general manager, and Mr B Graham, former acting
personnel manager, at which he denied knowledge of the irregularities.
The tribunal notes: ''He stated he could remember only two rounds of
drink being served to the Pinkerton agents. He confirmed he had banked
cash takings when the bar closed and that these amounted to #22.60.''
At the end the barman, who was suspended on full pay, was ''visibly
distressed by the nature of the meeting''. A search of his quarters
revealed nothing.
A disciplinary hearing followed on January 27 but despite requests by
Mr Bowring, Mr Poulter refused to give him any documentation, including
the Pinkerton report.
The hearing sacked the barman and he lost an appeal on February 23.
Before the appeal, Mr G Graham, the hotel's operations director, carried
out some investigations of his own.
He noted Mr Bowring's claim that the undercover agents had only bought
two rounds of drinks, none of which he had taken to their table.
Mr Graham also noted the surveillance report, which ''indicated that
the Pinkerton agents had disposed of the six rounds of drinks they had
purchased by surreptitiously pouring them over nearby plants in the
American Bar''.
The operations manager visited the bar to check whether this was
feasible and also spoke to the hotel gardeners about the matter.
In issuing its judgment the tribunal unanimously decided the
Gleneagles Hotel plc had not adopted a fair procedure in dismissing the
applicant by not issuing him with a copy of the Pinkerton report, and
awarded Mr Bowring #2114 compensation.
But because of contributory conduct the tribunal halved the award and
noted: ''He had by his own admission during the investigative process
been unable to account for the sum of #10.60.
''As that sum represented one round of drinks purchased by the
Pinkerton agents it would have been reasonable to expect the respondents
to have investigated whether responsibility for misappropriation of that
sum lay with the applicant and Miss Stewart jointly, or with one of them
alone.
''In all the circumstances it seems just and equitable to reduce the
applicant's compensation by 50% by reason of contributory conduct.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000182</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000182</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Home owner feels stung by council</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584360</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TENS of thousands of bees swarmed into Mr Keith Dodson's house in
Stornoway. But, despite calls to police and the Western Isles Council,
Mr Dodson, a sports centre officer, says that no-one would help and his
panic-stricken family.
For almost a week, Mr Dodson, his wife, Catherine, and daughters,
Sandra, 19, and Caroline, 17, have fought to clear their private house
at Mackenzie Street of the bees, which were covered in soot and made
three rooms filthy in minutes. Life is only now getting back to normal
after they used sulphur candles to fumigate the rooms.
The Dodsons had closed off the three affected rooms and called police
and the environmental health department. Mr Dodson said: ''The
department didn't even come and see. They did nothing. The depute
environmental health director, Mr Bryan Barrett, suggested a pest
control company.'' The Dodsons said that only Councillor Katie Mackenzie
came to see the bees for herself.
Mr Dodson rang the council chief executive, Mr Brian Stewart. ''When
the chief executive heard it was not a council house, he said there was
nothing they could do.''
Mr Barrett confirmed that he referred Mr Dodson to a private company.
He said: ''He did not get back to me, so I had no idea he still had the
problem. If he had, I would have done something about it. It's not a
statutory duty of the council to do something about bees. We have
neither the training nor the equipment.''
Local councillor Al Macrae promised to have a close look at the
problem of bees as dangerous pests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000183</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000183</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lords to hear Fettes bullying allegations</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584361</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The House of Lords will this
week discuss allegations of bullying at one of Scotland's most famous
independent schools, Fettes College in Edinburgh, whose old boys include
Labour leader Tony Blair.
At its annual founder's day ceremony at the weekend the school's
headmaster, Mr Malcolm Thyne, strongly denied claims of bullying and
sexual assault on pupils.
He told an audience of about 1500 people that he thought the
allegations were the result of a campaign to cause embarrassment to the
school, where fees cost #10,000 a year.
He said: ''The issue, I think, has arisen following my decision in
1992 to ask six members of the school to leave following an incident
involving cannabis. Since that time there has been a sustained campaign
to cause embarrassment to the school.''
Mr Thyne said he was very proud of the school, his staff who served
it, and the current pupils, adding that he believed parents were
delighted with the quality of education being provided.
The Lords will be discussing an amendment to the Children (Scotland)
Bill, which could result in independent schools receiving annual
inspections instead of one every five years, as proposed by the
Government.
Submissions on the allegations have been sent by parents and former
pupils to the Earl of Mar and Kellie and other peers, and the matter
will be discussed on Wednesday in the House.
Fettes has not been inspected sinced 1981, but a spokesman for the 475
pupil co-educational school said yesterday it would be ''quite happy''
to have annual inspections as it regarded the 14-year gap as too long.
Around a marquee set up in the grounds of the 125-year-old college for
the founder's day ceremony parents were dismissive of the allegations.
Landowner Eileen Monk, from Aberdeen, whose son was at the school for 10
years, said: ''It is a load of codswallop.''
Yesterday, the Earl of Mar and Kellie was unavailable for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000184</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000184</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Two guilty of film production fraud</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584362</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FILM starring Omar Sharif and Glenda Jackson was abandoned after a
swindle by two businessmen.
Lawyer Euan McIlvride, 35, and Michael McLetchie, 39, were convicted
at the High Court in Glasgow at the weekend of defrauding the film's
producer.
They had pretended they could raise #12m to fund a historical film
called The Castle.
The producer, Kenteas Brine, 45, spent nearly #lm building a village
in Czechoslovakia as a set. She told Mr Scott Brady, prosecuting, that
she had to sell her home when cash ran out for the project, and the two
accused pretended they could fund the money she needed.
Miss Brine told how, in 1990, she borrowed $35,000 from the late Sir
John Anthony Langford-Holt, a former Tory MP and Lloyd's name, and gave
it to the accused. Both were directors of RTR Estates Ltd, of West Nile
Street, Glasgow, which dealt in raising finance for businesses.
But McIlvride and McLetchie failed to produce the money they promised.
The jury returned its verdict on Saturday after spending the night in
a hotel at the end of a five-week trial.
McIlvride, of Stewart Drive, Glasgow, and McLetchie, of Islay Drive,
Newton Mearns, were found guilty of defrauding Miss Brine of $35,000.
McIlvride was also found guilty of embezzling #3450 while a lawyer
with another firm seven years ago.
He was also found guilty of embezzling #13,244 in a swindle involving
a fishing boat skipper. McIlvride gave the skipper #37,000, less #2000
in fees, and sold a licence for #50,000 to a firm in Buckie, the court
heard.
The jury found fraud charges against both accused not proven in two
other cases involving a total of #15,000.
Temporary judge Alexander Wilkinson deferred sentence for three weeks
for background reports, and continued bail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000185</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000185</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Another weekend devoted to cricket</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584363</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Employment Secretary became involved with the ''wets'' yesterday
when he turned out to support his department at a rained-off cricket
match.
Mr Michael Portillo, despite heavy showers and a battery of TV
cameras, joined an Employment Department team due to play against
industrial and labour newspaper correspondents.
However, he ended up sheltering with his wife, Carolyn, beneath a huge
umbrella at Mill Hill School, north London, close to his Enfield
constituency.
''Why is it always raining in Mill Hill?'' he asked.
Employment Department officials said Mr Portillo was not sporty and he
was not due to play in the match.
Mr Portillo stayed for an hour, chatting with officials from his
department, and sipping a glass of diet cola.
Half an hour after he left, the sun came out, and the match started.
But it was abandoned after less than an hour when heavy rain returned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000186</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000186</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Media lay siege to castle. Blonde disguise is a fantasy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>977584364</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN THE latest episode of the Grant-Hurley saga, the brunette
girlfriend disguised in a blonde wig took refuge in a castle, having won
the support of Estee Lauder, and the boyfriend's fantasy was
''revealed''.
The president of the cosmetic giant, Mr Leonard Lauder, said in a
statement: ''Elizabeth Hurley's contract with Estee Lauder remains
unchanged.'' It is reported to be worth #1m.
0 However, the future of the couple looked less settled. Lord
Brocklehurst said: ''She has made no decision about the future of her
relationship.'' Miss Hurley had fled at the weekend to Lord
Brocklehurst's family home, Sudeley Castle.
The 550-year-old castle at Winchcombe in Gloucestershire is open to
the public and attracts thousands every year.
Coachloads of visitors were shown round the castle, crammed with
historical treasures and once the palace of Katherine Parr, who is
buried in the castle church.
Reporters and photographers hoping to catch sight of Miss Hurley were
given their marching orders by a member of staff as soon as they veered
off the tourist trail.
However, a blonde wig fooled no one when she emerged from the castle
for a drive with Lord Brocklehurst.
Grant, meanwhile, could relive the opening episode where he was
charged with lewd conduct in public. In the News of the World, Divine
Brown said Grant paid her #40 for sex in his BMW convertible. She said
the actor told her: ''I always wanted to sleep with a black woman.
That's my fantasy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950703-000187</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950703-000187</DOCID>
<DATE>950703</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Europe the key in contest. The great divide for Tories</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGREGOR,PARLIAMENTARY CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584365</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE differences over Europe emerged again yesterday as the crucial
issue between Tory leadership contenders John Major and John Redwood.
Mr Major stuck to his guns over his policy on Europe, refusing to rule
out a single currency or come down in favour of a referendum: Mr Redwood
made clear that no Government led by him would ever agree to the
abolition of the pound.
In his stance, Mr Major also warned of the dangers of appealing to the
hard-right Euro view. ''There is no point in the Conservative Party
enthusing 20% of the electorate if the other 80% is not prepared to
understand its policies.''
Mr Redwood, on his determination to avoid scandal by using a moral
screening programme of potential Ministers, said there would no problem
in appointing a homosexual if they were quite open about it.
Both men will try to sell their message to the right-wing 92 Group of
Tory MPs at Westminster today, in what could be a last attempt to win
support. Opinion poll evidence at the weekend indicated Mr Major will
win tomorrow, but a question mark exists over whether he can win by
enough to make him safe.
A survey of Tory MPs in the Sunday Express found Mr Major would get
about 224 votes compared with 60 for Mr Redwood and 45 abstentions. The
Sunday Times found the Prime Minister's rating among people who voted
Tory in 1992 had risen seven points to 55% since last week, compared
with Mr Redwood on 10%. A poll by the BBC's political research unit
showed some 93% of 150 constituency chairmen who replied to the survey
favoured the Prime Minister.
However, if many more than 100 MPs fail to support him, either through
voting for Mr Redwood or abstentions, the feeling is that he will stand
down, opening the way for a second ballot in which the big guns such as
Mr Michael Heseltine and Mr Michael Portillo would enter the fray. Some
believe their supporters may deliberately abstain on the first ballot to
force the issue.
Mr Major's only concession yesterday to the Euro-sceptics was to adopt
his traditional ''wait-and-see'' approach, holding out the possibility
of Britain setting itself up as a leader of nations excluded from the
single currency.
He said only a small number of nations would be ready to move to
monetary union in 1999 and no thought had been given to those left out.
Making clear the decision would have to be taken at the time and could
not be prejudged, he said: ''Once the decision has been made, if we do
have a two-core Europe, an inner core and an outer core, I think small
nations in the outer core will probably look to some of the bigger
nations and we might well be that nation.''
He combined his remarks on Europe with a strong call for party unity.
''The Conservative Party wins elections from the centre-right, and that
is where I stand. There is no point in the Conservative Party enthusing
20% of the electorate if the other 80% is not prepared to understand its
policies. We need to win 40% or 45% of the vote -- closer to 45% than
40% -- in order to form the next government.''
Mr Redwood claimed his message was gaining ground, particularly in the
constituencies.
''I am saying there have to be changes for us to win the election. I
have put forward policy changes, I am also putting myself forward to
take those policy changes through and to lead the party to the future.
We have found as the week has progressed a growing amount of support
coming in from around the country for what I am saying and that is
beginning to have an impact on MPs.''
On the aspect of scandal and sleaze, he told ITV's Jonathan Dimbleby
programme: ''Anybody being offered a job for the first time in a
government under my leadership would talk to me or a senior colleague
about the intrusiveness of the modern media.''
On homosexuality, Mr Redwood said: ''We would have to discuss whether
or nor that was going to be an embarrassment to them. If someone was a
homosexual, but said so, and that was on the public record, I'd see no
problem with that at all.''
One of Mr Major's campaign leaders, Scottish Secretary Ian Lang,
appeared to concede that a ''technical'' victory tomorrow would not be
enough for Mr Major, though he believed the question was academic since
the mood was shifting ''firmly and decisively towards a very substantial
victory''.
Former Tory party chairman Lord Tebbit, a declared supporter of Mr
Redwood, said Europe remained the key issue. ''I hoped that when John
Major took this decision to precipitate this election and stand down as
leader that he would take up the Euro-sceptic flag and carry it. He did
not do so,'' he told BBC Radio.
Laour, meanwhile, held out the prospect of a ''no confidence'' vote on
the Government in the Commons. Deputy leader John Prescott said: ''If it
goes to a second ballot then the question of whether this party can
govern the country is a very clear issue and we will have to judge it
there and then.''
</TEXT>
