<HEADLINE>Drivers vote.    Railways braced for disruption. Railways braced for strike vote</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584366</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RAIL travellers could face an other summer of disruption if a train
drivers' ballot result out today backs strike action.
Officials of Aslef (the Associated Society of Locomotive Engineers and
Firemen) believe the 12,000 British Rail drivers, including about 1500
in Scotland, will come out in support of a series of 24-hour strikes in
protest at what the union has described as a ''derisory'' 3% pay offer
which BR says is final.
The executive of Aslef will meet today to consider the ballot result,
but was not officially predicting the outcome because voting does not
end until noon today. However union sources yesterday forecast a
''significant majority'' in favour of strike action.
One Scottish union official said such backing would mean all rail
services, including freight and InterCity trains, would grind to a halt
on strike days and warned that disruption would be much more widespread
than during last year's signalworkers' dispute since BR would not be
able to replace train drivers as easily as signalworkers were replaced.
ScotRail admitted yesterday that it was bracing itself for widespread
disruption and warned that a further loss of revenue on top of the
signalworkers' dispute could lead to job losses.
Aslef, which has to give BR seven-days' notice of strikes, could start
the first walk-out from next Monday, while Rail, Maritime, and Transport
union members at BR and on London Underground are also voting on one-day
strikes over pay, with the result expected on Friday.
Mr Pat O'Connor, Aslef district secretary for Scotland, said yesterday
that he was ''100% confident'' that the union would be given a mandate
to start industrial action, adding that its executive would meet
immediately afterwards and would probably decide to hold one 24-hour
stoppage each week.
''Depending on the time of day the strike action started, that could
mean a complete shutdown of all services in Scotland and the rest of
Britain for a minimum of 24 hours.''
He said the dispute was solely about the ''derisory'' 3% pay increase
offered by management, which would be the fourth consecutive pay rise of
less than the rate of inflation.
Train drivers currently earn a gross pay rate of #220 per week, and
can earn about an extra #30 in ancilliary payments for overtime and
variations in conditions such as driver-only operations.
Describing the train drivers' wage rate as ''unbelievable'' given the
responsibilty of their jobs, Mr O'Connor said that rail privatisation
meant it was vitally important ''to establish a reasonable wage before
we go into company-bargaining when they will be looking for all sorts of
changes in conditions such as an increase in hours and shifts.''
He added: ''We hope the public realise that the last thing Aslef
members want is to cause them any inconvenience.''
BR is expected to declare a healthy profit for the last financial year
when its annual report is published on tomorrow.
RMT's general secretary, Mr Jimmy Knapp, said: ''The expected profit
justifies the arguments we made during the pay negotiations that BR can
afford more, and that the workforce deserve a better offer than 3%.''
A ScotRail spokeswoman said yesterday that, although every effort
would be made to maintain as many services as possible, the implications
of a train drivers' strike would be very serious.
''The majority of train crews are Aslef or RMT members so any strike
action would mean there would be very limited services.
''The implications in terms of loss of customers and income just don't
bear thinking about. There was a small percentage of people who did not
return to railway services last time.
''UK-wide, from the strikes in the late 1970s and early 1980s,
railways lost between 1% and 3% of passengers who just didn't come back
after finding alternative means of transport to rail.''
She further warned: ''In the long-term, if the railway loses more
money because of strike action it has to cut costs. ScotRail's major
cost is its staff -- the only asset -- so if cuts in budget have to be
made, one area it would have to look at would be staff.''
She said it was difficult to say if strikes would affect the viability
of services but admitted that, if the railway loses a lot of money as a
result of industrial action, the Office of Passenger and Rail
Franchising (whose Passenger Service Requirement document is presently
out for public consultation and will be finalised later this year)
''might say that some things have to be withdrawn''.
Aslef later dismissed such warnings as ''scare tactics.''
* Meanwhile the white-collar Transport Salaried Staffs' Association
yesterday accused BR of trying to ''torpedo'' efforts to resolve its pay
dispute by mediation.
The union, which has 23,000 members at BR, wanted to refer its pay
claim to mediation rather than hold a ballot for industrial action, but
BR would not agree.
The union's general secretary, Mr Richard Rosser, accused the
Government of ''meddling'' in the negotiations. But a BR spokesman said:
''With our two main unions engaged in balloting it would be
inappropriate to become involved in mediation at this time.''
