<HEADLINE>Prison staff are suspended</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584367</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIVE members of staff at Perth Prison, including a senior assistant
governor and a supervisor, have been suspended from duty.
The Scottish Prison Service said three officers and a supervisor have
been suspended pending the outcome of inquiries by Tayside police and
prison governors ''following allegations made by a number of
prisoners''.
The SPS said it could not reveal the nature of the inquiries but it is
understood they are based on allegations of assault.
A spokesman for the SPS said the four, whose names have not been
revealed, were put on special leave on Thursday. It is technically not a
suspension but has the same effect.
A spokesman for Tayside police in Perth said: ''We can confirm that
there is a police investigation in progress regarding allegations
against three officers and a supervisor at Perth Prison.''
A senior official, whose position was described as a middle-ranking
governor, has also been suspended on full pay following an internal SPS
inquiry and a disciplinary hearing last Wednesday.
It is understood the matter is related to expenses claims and that the
person involved admitted alleged irregularities.
After the hearing, prison Governor Mike Duffy recommended on Friday
that the person concerned, who has also not been named, should be
dismissed from the SPS. However, the decision is subject to the
ratification of the Secretary of State for Scotland and the person has
the right to appeal against the finding.
Perth Prison, Scotland's oldest, houses more than 400, including a
mixture of short and long-term inmates and local remand prisoners.
The prison population also includes about half of the country's 12
category A inmates who are regarded as those prisoners who pose the
greatest danger to the public and prison staff and require the highest
security.
Perth was the scene of riots by about 120 inmates in December 1992,
when prison officers were taken hostage in D hall. There were previous
riots in 1987.
</TEXT>
