<HEADLINE>Scots to bottle Irish whiskey</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RON MACKENNA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>977584368</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IRISH whiskey is to be blended and bottled in Scotland, then sold to
retail chains in Britain. The arrangement is part of a 10-year deal
between Invergordon Distilleries in Glasgow and Ireland's only
independent whiskey maker, the tiny Cooley Distillery.
Cooley will provide the bulk whiskey which Invergordon will blend and
bottle for sale to 10 leading British chains, including Tesco and Asda,
as an own-brand product. Another brand, Erin's Isle, will be sold
through smaller retailers who do not want an own label.
According to Cooley's chief executive, Dr John Teeling, the deal
follows an approach by Invergordon. ''They were apparently very
impressed by the success of a Cooley single-malt whiskey which is being
sold by the Sainsbury's chain as an own-brand product,'' he said.
Irish whiskey sells at around #13 a bottle in the UK. The new brands
will be some #2 cheaper. But Dr Teeling expects prices to fall further
as Irish Distillers, the dominant Irish whiskey maker, reacts to this
latest move.
Invergordon is part of American Brands, which also owns Whyte &amp; Mackay
which last week dispensed with the services of the chairman and chief
executive, Mr Michael Lunn.
Meanwhile, the first whisky to be produced on Arran in 150 years was
yesterday run from the copper stills of the island's new distillery at
Lochranza. Isle of Arran Distillers are producing an eight-year-old
single malt, which ''is robust with a nice sweetness and a nutty,
peppery flavour''.
It was in middle of last century that the last legal whisky was made
on the island, at Lagg.
The company has also launched the Arran Bond, a scheme for
pre-purchasing the distillery's early production, and is building a
visitor centre which it hopes to open next summer.
